1. e4 c5 2. g3 d5 3. exd5 Qxd5 4. Nf3 Bg4 5. Bg2 Qe6+ $1 {An important check that disturbs the coordination between white pieces.} 6. Kf1 (6. Qe2 Qxe2+ 7. Kxe2 Nc6 $15) 6... Nc6 7. h3 Bh5 $1 (7... Bxf3 {Carlsen chooses this move, but I think keeping the bishop makes more sense} 8. Bxf3 Qd7 9. d3 Nf6 10. Nd2 e6 11. Nc4 Be7 12. a4 O-O $11 {½-½ (49) Artemiev,V (2704)-Carlsen,M (2847) Chess24.com INT 2021}) 8. d3 Qd7 9. Na3 {This multipurpose move is the main try for White} (9. Be3 e6 10. Nbd2 Rc8 11. Nb3 b6 $15 {Black consolidates and White doesn't have compensation for the f1-king}) (9. Nc3 e6 10. Bf4 f6 $5 11. Qe1 (11. Kg1 Nge7 12. Be3 Nf5 13. Ne5 Bxd1 14. Nxd7 Nxe3 15. Nxf8 Rxf8 16. Bxc6+ bxc6 17. Nxd1 Nxc2 18. Rc1 Nb4 19. Rxc5 Ke7 $15 {0-1 Somlai,L (2400)-Madl,I (2410)/Hungary 1993/(41)} 20. a3 $140 Nxd3 21. Rxc6 Rfc8) 11... Bf7 12. a4 Rc8 {0-1 (38) Zatonskih,A (2419)-Sebag,M (2312) Leon 2001}) 9... e6 10. Nc4 f6 $1 {[%cal Rf8d6,Rg8e7] Preventing the occupation of e5-square after g3-g4.} (10... Bd6 {[%cal Rg8e7] is a very simple way to handle the position which also equalizes}) 11. Be3 Rd8 12. a4 (12. g4 Bf7 13. a4 b6 14. Qe2 Nge7 15. Bf4 Nd5 $17 {0-1 (27) Flower,D (2045)-Aseev,K (2540)/London 1994}) 12... e5 $11 {[%cal Rh5f7,Rb7b6]} 13. Kg1 Qc7 14. Qd2 Nd4 $11 *

