1. e4 c5 2. b3 {The best strategy against b3 is always to try to put our pawns on d6 and e5 to restrict the bishop} Nc6 {I prefer to start with this move followed by e5} 3. Bb2 e5 4. f4 (4. Bc4 {This move deserves serious attention after 3...e5, but with such passive b2-bishop White can't be better. Black can develop his dark-squared bishop on g7 and start actions on the kinside} Nf6 5. Nc3 g6 6. Nge2 Bg7 7. O-O d6 8. d3 O-O 9. a4 (9. h3 a6 10. a4 Nh5 11. Qd2 Rb8 12. f3 Bd7 $15 {½-½ (47) Eckhardt,T (2450)-Pirs,M (2559) ICCF email 2010}) 9... Kh8 (9... Be6 $5) 10. Nd5 Nxd5 11. Bxd5 Ne7 (11... Nb4 $1 12. Bc4 f5 {is the correct move order}) 12. Bc4 g5 13. Ng3 f5 $132 {0-1 (35) Vallejo Pons,F (2710)-Gukesh,D (2730) chess.com INT 2023}) (4. Nc3 Nf6 5. Bc4 (5. Bb5 {Is not dangerous for Black, because Bxc6 is not actually a threat} d6 6. Bxc6+ bxc6 $15 {[%csl Yb2] Black has massive centre and will continue with g6-Bg7 or with immediate d6-d5 followed by Bd6}) 5... d6 6. Nge2 g6 {[%cal Rf8g7] transposes to 4.Bc4}) 4... exf4 5. Bc4 (5. Nf3 Nf6 6. e5 Nh5 $1 7. Be2 d5 8. O-O Bg4 9. d4 cxd4 10. Nxd4 Bxe2 11. Qxe2 Bc5 $1 12. Qxh5 Nxd4 13. Kh1 Ne6 $1 $17 {Blatny - Serper, New York 1996}) 5... Qh4+ 6. Kf1 Nf6 7. Nf3 Qh6 8. Nc3 Be7 9. e5 (9. d3 O-O 10. Nd5 Nxd5 11. Bxd5 d6 12. Kf2 Nb4 $19 {0-1 (62) Saulin,D (2438)-Babayev,T (2370) Suvorov 2012}) 9... Ng4 10. Qe2 O-O 11. h3 d6 $17 *

