1. e4 c5 2. b4 {the famous Wing Gambit I studied this position and even recommend this move to some students. The positions are fresh, so you must be well-prepared.} cxb4 3. a3 (3. d4 {Is very well met by} d5 4. e5 (4. exd5 {doesn't make any sense to me} Qxd5 5. c4 Qd8 6. Nf3 Nf6 7. a3 (7. Bb2 g6 8. a3 bxa3 9. Rxa3 Bg7 10. Be2 O-O $15 {0-1 (35) Gareyev,T (2606)-Vorontsov,P (2539) Costa Mesa 2017}) 7... e6 8. Be2 bxa3 9. O-O Be7 10. Nxa3 O-O 11. Bf4 Na6 12. Qb3 Nc7 13. Rfd1 b6 14. Ne5 Bb7 {0-1 (24) Vavruska,A (2140)-Krejci,J (2503) Stare Mesto op 2012 (3)}) 4... Nc6 {This resembles the advanced French, but the bishop is not passive on c8 and Black has an extra pawn} 5. a3 Qb6 $1 {[%csl Rd4]} (5... Bf5 6. axb4 {gives Black some compensation}) 6. Ne2 (6. Be3 Bf5 7. Bd3 Bxd3 8. Qxd3 e6 $15 {This looks like a clear pawn up for me}) (6. Nf3 Bg4 $15 {This is a much better square for the bishop than f5. Now we still attack the d4-pawn}) 6... Bf5 7. axb4 Nxb4 8. Na3 Rc8 9. Nf4 Nxc2+ 10. Nxc2 Bxc2 11. Qg4 e6 12. Nxd5 Qc6 13. Ra5 Bf5 14. Qd1 Qxc1 15. Bb5+ Kd8 16. Qxc1 Rxc1+ 17. Kd2 Rxh1 18. Rxa7 exd5 19. Ra8+ Bc8 {0-1 Simonsen,O (2184)-Ziska,H (2550) FAI-chT 1819 Faroe Islands 2018 (9.3)}) (3. Nf3 {doesn't change the character of the position, so Black can prepare d5 break or do it immediately} d5 (3... e6 $5)) 3... b3 {very practical and strong move. It is the simplest reply against the Wing Gambit} 4. cxb3 (4. c4 {Is a nice try by Dubov} e5 $1 {We can't allow three pawns in the cenre} 5. Qxb3 (5. f4 Nc6 6. Nf3 Bc5 $1 {This strong move just closes the variation} (6... Nf6 $6 7. fxe5 (7. Nc3 $5) 7... Nxe4 8. d4 {White has some compensation and won a nice game} Qa5+ 9. Nbd2 Qc3 10. Bb2 Qxb2 11. Nxe4 Bxa3 12. Rxa3 Qxa3 13. Nd6+ Kf8 14. Bd3 b2 15. O-O Nb4 16. Bb1 Qe3+ 17. Kh1 h5 18. Nh4 Qc1 19. Ng6+ {1-0 Dubov,D (2720)-Golubev,M (2461) Titled Tuesday intern op 01st Mar Early Chess.com INT blitz 2022 (7)}) 7. fxe5 (7. Bb2 d6 $17) 7... Nd4 $17 {White needs to think how to survive here, the situation is critical}) 5... Nc6 6. Nf3 Bc5 {With an advantage due to the control of the dark squares.}) 4... d5 5. exd5 (5. e5 Nc6 6. d4 Bf5 7. Bb2 e6 8. Bd3 Nh6 9. Ne2 Be7 {With a dream version of advanced Caro Kann for Black 0-1 (47) Forster,R (2449)-Bauer,C (2624) Switzerland 2008}) 5... Nf6 6. Nc3 Nxd5 {[%csl Rd2] I like Kamsky's approach, it is very simple and we simply get a better game. A wonderful version of IQP position.} 7. Bb2 (7. Bc4 Nxc3 8. dxc3 Qxd1+ 9. Kxd1 $11 {Is another version of equal endgame which looks slightly easier to play with Black 0-1 (28) Cioara,A (2417)-Artemiev,V (2716) Chess.com INT 2020}) 7... Nc6 8. Nf3 Bg4 9. h3 Bh5 10. Bb5 a6 11. Bxc6+ bxc6 12. O-O e6 $11 {[%csl Rc6] The position objectively should be about equal, but I prefer to play it with Black} *

