1. g3 c5 2. Bg2 Nc6 3. d3 g6 4. e4 Bg7 5. f4 e6 6. Nf3 Nge7 7. O-O O-O 8. c3 d6 {[%cal Ra8b8,Rb7b5] This is our starting position. White is playing in the spirit of the Closed Sicilian, but instead of Nc3, he puts the pawn there. You can say that thi} 9. Be3 (9. Nbd2 Rb8 {[%cal Rb7b5,Rb5b3] Is a very typical idea for this structure} (9... d5) 10. a4 a6 {[%cal Rb7b5]} 11. Qe2 b5 12. axb5 axb5 {[%cal Ra1a8,Rc8b7] It seems that we open the a-file for White's rook, but very often we are going back Ra8 and we take the initiative on the queenside}) 9... b6 10. d4 {The main thing that you need to remember is that we are not taking on d4 immediately. We first prepare for this by playing moves like Ba6, Rc8, Qd7, etc.. Then, we await the best possible moment to open the game.} (10. Bf2 {After any prophylactik move we play Ba6, Rc8 preparing d5-break} Ba6 11. Re1 Qd7 12. d4 cxd4 $11 {½- (39) ½ Neiksans,A (2503)-Fridman,D (2645) EU-ch rapid Warsaw 2010 (9)}) (10. Na3 Ba6 {[%cal Rd8d7,Rd6d5]} 11. Re1 Rc8 12. Nc2 Qd7 13. Qd2 Rfd8 14. g4 d5 15. e5 d4 $15 {0-1 (38) Paragua,M (2526)-Banikas,H (2572) WMSG Blitz KO 1st Beijing 2008 (2.4)}) 10... Ba6 11. Re1 Rc8 {[%cal Rd8d7,Rc5d4,Rd6d5]} 12. Qd2 (12. Nbd2 Qd7 13. a3 cxd4 14. cxd4 Na5 $11) (12. Na3 cxd4 13. cxd4 Qd7 $11) (12. d5 $2 $15 exd5 13. exd5 Na5 $15) 12... cxd4 13. cxd4 Na5 {[%csl Re3][%cal Ra5c4]} 14. b3 Bb7 {[%csl Re4]} 15. Bf2 e5 (15... Qd7 $1 $11 {[%cal Rf7f5]}) 16. Na3 exf4 17. Qxf4 f5 18. Ng5 Qd7 19. exf5 Bxg2 20. Kxg2 Rxf5 {0-1 (37) Radovanovic,M (2485)-Martinez Alcantara,J (2606) Montebelluna 2020} *

