1. e4 c5 2. f4 {This move is much stronger on move 3, with the move order 2.Nc3 Nc6 3.f4. Here Black can simply proceed with d5 and get a very good position} d5 3. exd5 Nf6 {This is the main line which is also perfectly playable} (3... Qxd5 {I like this approach because of its simplicity. We are playing similar to Scandinavian and White has this strange f-pawn which weakens all dark squares, also the king can be weak in the feature.} 4. Nc3 Qd8 {0-1 (50) Lui,K (1859)-Fedoseev,V (2678) Lichess.org INT 2020}) 4. Bb5+ (4. c4 {Playing this immediately is even worse. Black continues with e6 and obtains more than enough compensation for the pawn.} e6 5. dxe6 Bxe6 {[%cal Gb8c6]} 6. Nf3 Nc6 7. Nc3 Bd6 8. d4 cxd4 9. Nxd4 O-O {0-1 (24) Rosich Valles,A (2220)-Kasparov,G (2750) Barcelona 1988}) 4... Bd7 5. Bxd7+ Qxd7 6. c4 e6 7. Qe2 Bd6 8. d3 (8. f5 {If White is too greedy, this could lead to a disaster after:} O-O 9. fxe6 fxe6 10. Qxe6+ (10. dxe6 Qe7 $15 {[%cal Rb8c6]} 11. Nf3 Nc6 12. Nc3 Rae8 13. O-O Nd4 14. Nxd4 cxd4 $19 {0-1 (15) Zernovic,F (2337)-Makovsky,P (2500) ICCF email 2007}) 10... Qxe6+ 11. dxe6 Nc6 $19 {You can just compare the development and the activity of the pieces}) 8... O-O 9. dxe6 fxe6 10. Nf3 Nc6 11. O-O Rae8 12. Nc3 e5 13. f5 Nd4 14. Qd1 Nxf5 {Black won the pawn back and has an advantage: 0-1 (59) Shkuro,I (2415)-Kryvoruchko,Y (2612) Alushta 2008} 15. Rb1 *

