1. e4 c5 2. c3 {Alapin Variation is a severe weapon. I was wondering what to offer you, but finally I decided to go for a very trendy system that is quite simple to play.} d5 3. exd5 Qxd5 4. Nf3 Nc6 {I like this system also because the move order can't trick us. Let's say If White plays 2.Nf3 Nc6 and only then 3.c3} 5. d4 Nf6 {This is the starting position of the variation. We are still not committing to e6 or to Bg4 and keep all our options open. White has four different options here.} 6. dxc5 {was considered for a long time the strongest move, which gives an advantage, but recent practice shows that Black is perfectly fine here} (6. Na3 $6 {This move doesn't work well here. Black continues with Bg4 followed by 0-0-0 with an advantage} Bg4 $1 7. Nb5 (7. dxc5) (7. Be2 {There are 300 games in the database, but White is simply worse here after} cxd4 8. Nb5 O-O-O 9. Nbxd4 e5 10. Nxc6 Qxc6 11. Qb3 Be6 12. Qb5 Qxb5 13. Bxb5 Bc5 (13... a6 14. Be2 Bd6 $15) 14. Be3 Bxe3 15. fxe3 Rd6 (15... Ne4 $1 $17) 16. Be2 Ng4 $15 {0-1 (35) Lajthajm,B (2414)-Kovchan,A (2567) Debrecen 2019}) 7... O-O-O 8. Be2 a6 9. Na3 cxd4 10. Nc4 Qe4 $17 {and White is on the verge of losing}) (6. Be3 {Is not very critical, because when White committed to Be3, he couldn't play the plan with Bf4 later on. We can continue in the spirit of our repertoire and play 6...e6.} e6 7. Bd3 Be7 8. O-O O-O 9. Qe2 Rd8 {Black is not in a hurry to take on d4 and for White is not easy to develop his b1-knight. If White plays Na3 or Nd2, we will immediately take on d4 and get a wonderful position} 10. h3 (10. Rd1 {Usually, when we see Rd1, we take on d4 not to allow any possible tactics} cxd4 11. cxd4 Nb4 12. Nc3 Qh5 13. Bc4 b6 14. a3 Nbd5 15. Rac1 Nxc3 16. Rxc3 Bb7 {Black is slightly better in this typical IQP position. White has no attack and we already exchange one minor piece 0-1 (44) Yudin,S (2599)-Artemiev,V (2803) Almaty 2022}) 10... b6 11. Rd1 cxd4 {Finally Black takes on d4 and reaches IQP position. But as you can see, White's setup is not optimal} 12. cxd4 Bb7 13. Nc3 Qh5 14. a3 Na5 15. b4 Bxf3 16. Qxf3 Qxf3 17. gxf3 Rac8 18. Rac1 Nc4 19. Bxc4 Rxc4 $15 {0-1 (32) Mamedov,R (2646)-Gukesh,D (2718) Chess.com INT 2023}) (6. Be2 {This is the main line and I like the approach of young Indians Gukesh and Prag to continue with e6} e6 7. O-O cxd4 (7... Be7 $6 8. c4 Qd7 9. dxc5 Bxc5 10. a3 O-O 11. b4 $14 {1-0 (39) Carlsen,M (2839)-Nepomniachtchi,I (2771) Chess.com INT 2023}) 8. cxd4 Be7 9. Nc3 Qd6 {Let me explain you with a few words what we want in this position.  1. We want to complete the development with b6-Bb7, followed by Rd8 and then we are trying to exchange at least two minor pieces.  2.White's setup is passive with the bishop on e2. If he tries to put it on d3, he will lose more time. 3.If White has no attack in this structure, he is simply worse due to the weakness of the d4-pawn.} 10. Nb5 {Only this move creates some small problems for Black. After everything else, Black gets a very good version of IQP with a passive white bishop on e2} ({For example} 10. Bg5 {is just harmless} O-O 11. Qd2 (11. Bxf6 $6 {this doesn't look right} Bxf6 12. Ne4 Qe7 13. Bb5 Bd7 14. Rc1 Rfd8 15. Re1 $2 (15. Nxf6+ Qxf6 16. Ne5 $132 {with chances for White to equalize}) 15... Nxd4 $17 {0-1 (47) Nozdrachev,L (2367)-Sarana,A (2670) Chess.com INT 2022}) 11... b6 (11... Rd8 {Is another possible move. In such positions, knowing the plans is much more important} 12. Rfd1 Nd5 13. Rac1 Bxg5 14. Qxg5 h6 15. Qd2 Nf6 $11 {0-1 (45) Chekhov,S (2453)-Sjugirov,S (2712) Sochi 2023}) 12. Rac1 (12. Rad1 {This move doesn't change the character of the position} Bb7 13. Rfe1 Rad8 14. Bf4 Qd7 15. a3 Qc8 16. Bd3 Na5 17. Qe2 Qa8 $132 {0-1 (57) Mamedyarov,S (2770)-Nepomniachtchi,I (2789) chess24.com INT 2021}) 12... Bb7 13. Rfd1 Rfd8 14. Bf4 Qd7 15. h3 Nd5 16. Bg3 Rac8 {½-½ (67) Abdusattorov,N (2713)-Gukesh,D (2725) Kolkata 2022}) (10. Be3 {As we already said, such moves don't create any problems for Black} O-O 11. a3 b6 12. Bd3 (12. b4 {This is not in the spirit of the structure, and Black easily gets a comfortable position after:} Bb7 13. Qb3 Rfd8 14. Rfd1 Bf8 15. h3 Ne7 16. Ne5 Nf5 $17 {0-1 (35) Demin,V (2430)-Van Foreest,J (2671) Chess.com INT 2020}) 12... Bb7 13. Qe2 Nd5 14. Ne4 Qd7 15. Rad1 Rad8 $11 {0-1 (42) Preotu,R (2487)-Artemiev,V (2716) Chess.com INT 2020}) 10... Qd8 11. Bf4 Nd5 12. Bg3 O-O 13. Rc1 {Trying to stop b7-b6} Bd7 14. Nc3 (14. Nd6 {The bishop pair doesn't guarantee White an advantage} Bxd6 15. Bxd6 Nce7 16. Ba3 Re8 17. Ne5 Ng6 18. Qd2 Ngf4 19. Bf3 Bb5 20. Rfd1 Qf6 21. Bd6 Rad8 $11 {½-½ (58) Abdusattorov,N (2734)-Praggnanandhaa,R (2690) Dusseldorf 2023}) 14... Rc8 $1 (14... Qb6 15. Bc4 Nf6 16. Na4 Qa5 17. Nc5 $14 {½-½ (59) Carlsen,M (2835)-Gukesh,D (2744) Baku 2023}) 15. Nxd5 ({Black is ready to meet} 15. Bc4 {with} Nxc3 16. bxc3 Na5 $15) 15... exd5 16. Qb3 Qb6 17. Qxb6 axb6 18. Bb5 f6 (18... Bf6 19. Rfe1 Be6 20. Be5 Be7 21. Bf4 Bf6 22. Be5 Be7 {½-½ (22) Stevic,H (2565)-Gajewski,G (2589) Germany 2023}) 19. Rfe1 Kf7 20. Bf4 g5 21. Be3 Bf5 {½-½ (37) Stevic,H (2565)-Gupta,A (2607) Germany 2023}) 6... Qxd1+ 7. Kxd1 Bf5 $1 {the newest discovery. The idea is to castle queenside as quickly as possible.} 8. Be3 Nd5 9. Nbd2 (9. Bb5 e5 $1 {very strong move} 10. Bxc6+ (10. Ke2 {allowing f6 is not reccomendable} f6 11. b4 Bxb1 $19 {[%cal Rd5c3] 0-1 (37) Reis,R (2266)-Shabalov,A (2520) Arlington 2013}) 10... bxc6 11. Nxe5 Nxe3+ 12. fxe3 O-O-O+ {The powerful bishops and the open files for the rooks fully compensate for the material deficit} 13. Nd2 Bxc5 14. Re1 Rhe8 15. Nxc6 Rd3 16. Nd4 Bg6 {0-1 (61) Bulmaga,I (2438)-Garifullina,L (2372) Petrovac 2023}) 9... O-O-O 10. Bb5 e6 (10... f6 $5 11. Nd4 Nxd4 12. cxd4 e5 $11) 11. Bxc6 bxc6 12. Nd4 Nxe3+ 13. fxe3 Bxc5 14. Ke2 Bg4+ 15. Kf2 (15. N2f3 $1 e5 16. h3 exd4 17. hxg4 dxe3 $11) 15... e5 16. N4b3 Be7 17. h3 Be6 $17 {1-0 (52) Naroditsky,D (2618)-Kramnik,V (2753) Chess.com INT 2023} *

