1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 {The Closed Sicilian is one of the most serious weapons against 1...c5. White often doesn't want to go into heavy theoretical battles in the Open Sicilian and chooses the tricky 2.Nc3. Black should be very careful with the move order, depending on the open Sicilian he wants to play. For example, players who want to play Najdorf or Dragon can't opt for 2...Nc6, because White can continue with 3.Nge2 followed by 4.d4 and trick them.  For our purposes (entering the Accelerated Dragon), the move 2...Nc6 is perfectly playable and clearly the best one.} Nc6 {Here I analyzed three moves} 3. f4 (3. Bb5 Nd4 $1) (3. g3 g6) 3..delightedy satisfied with my discovery that Black has nothing to worry about after this move. The Grand Prix attack always was unpleasant for me, and now I am confident to face it} *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Closed Sicilian 3.g3"]
[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]
[Annotator "GM Petar G. Arnaudov"]
[PlyCount "82"]
[EventDate "2023.10.19"]
[SourceTitle "CBM 171"]
[Source "ChessBase"]
[SourceDate "2016.03.14"]
[SourceVersion "2"]
[SourceVersionDate "2016.03.14"]
[SourceQuality "1"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 {The Closed Sicilian is one of the most serious weapons against 1...c5. White often doesn't want to go into heavy theoretical battles in the Open Sicilian and chooses the tricky 2.Nc3. Now Black should be careful with the move order, depending on the open Sicilian he wants to play. For example, players who want to play Najdorf or Dragon can't opt for 2...Nc6, because White can continue with 3.Nge2 followed by 4.d4 and trick them.  For our purposes (entering the Accelerated Dragon), the move 2...Nc6 is perfectly playable and the best one.} d6 {Just to remind you that our move order is 2...Nc6, but the game transposes after:} 3. g3 Nc6 4. Bg2 g6 5. d3 Bg7 6. f4 (6. Nge2 e6 7. Be3 Nd4) 6... e6 {the most flexible continuation: Black wants to develop his knight to e7, to castle quickly and then to start actions in the centre or on the queenside. Usually, White's plan is connecting with a kingside attack by means of g3-g4 followed by f5. The other possible plan is to open the game with d3-d4 at an appropriate moment.} 7. Nf3 Nge7 8. Be3 O-O 9. O-O b6 {[%cal Rd6d4] This is my choice here. Black defends the c5-pawn and is ready for the advance d6-d5. The other idea is to develop the bishop on "b7" or even "a6". The main drawback of this move is that it allows d3-d4 break and also weakens the diagonal h1-a8 for a momment} (9... Nd4 {Is the main line, but I don't like it that much} 10. e5 Nef5 (10... Bd7 {is a tricky move, which Black could try}) 11. Bf2 Nxf3+ 12. Qxf3 Nd4 13. Qd1 dxe5 14. fxe5 Bxe5 15. Ne4 $44 {White has tremendous compensation for the sacrificing material, in my opinion.  1-0 (32) Muzychuk,A (2560)-Lagno,K (2543) Khanty-Mansiysk 2014}) (9... Rb8 {Is also popular with the idea to gain space on the queenside. This plan works well, but it is a bit slow and too static. I prefer 9...b6, because it gives us more dynamic possibilities.}) 10. d4 (10. Qd2 {This move is very popular but allows Black to execute his main idea. I think that Black is just better after it.} d5 11. exd5 (11. Bf2 {allows} dxe4 12. dxe4 Qxd2 13. Nxd2 e5 $15 {[%cal Rc8e6,Rc6d4]} ({or} 13... Ba6 14. Rfd1 Bxc3 15. bxc3 Rad8 $15)) 11... exd5 12. Bf2 (12. d4 $2 {allows} Nf5 $17) 12... d4 13. Ne4 h6 14. Ne5 Bb7 15. Nxc6 Bxc6 16. Qd1 Nf5 17. Rb1 Re8 {0-1 (32) Martin Fuentes,A (2393)-Perez Ponsa,F (2532) Chess.com INT 2023}) (10. Bf2 {Is the other alternative, but it seems that Black is doing very well after:} Ba6 {[%cal Rd3d4,Ra8c8,Rd8d7] Is the most popular move, stopping d4} (10... Bb7 {Is also good, Black is ready to meet} 11. d4 cxd4 (11... d5 $5) 12. Nxd4 Nxd4 13. Bxd4 e5 $11) (10... Nd4 11. Nxd4 cxd4 12. Ne2) 11. Re1 {White renews the threat of d4} Qd7 12. d4 {Black is ready for this now} (12. Qd2 Rac8 13. Rad1) 12... cxd4 (12... Rad8 {There is nothing wrong to continue with the waiting strategy}) 13. Nxd4 Rac8 14. a4 Rfd8 15. Ndb5 (15. Qd2 Na5 {[%csl Rc4][%cal Ra5c4] Now the position resembles an Open Sicilian and it seems that Black has the upper hand} 16. Rad1 Nc4 (16... e5 $1) 17. Qc1 e5 $11 {0-1 (31) Larino Nieto,D (2375)-Chigaev,M (2632) chess.com INT 2023}) 15... Bb7 16. Qd2 d5 $2 (16... a6 $1 {We should kick the knight first} 17. Na3 d5) 17. e5 Ba8 18. Ne2 $14 {0-1 (51) Cubas,J (2586)-Fier,A (2595) Florianopolis 2019}) 10... d5 (10... Ba6 $5 {Is also good for Black} 11. Re1 Rc8 12. a4 (12. d5 $2 {Is tempting, but inacurrate} exd5 13. exd5 Na5 $17 {This looks like a "dream" Benoni for Black}) 12... d5 13. exd5 exd5 {Black has at least equal chances} {Of course} 14. dxc5 $4 {is a blunder due to} d4 $19) (10... cxd4 {even this move is playable, but Black needs to be accurate to maintain the ballance} 11. Nxd4 {[%csl Rd6][%cal Rg2c6] White has some temporary intiative}) 11. e5 (11. exd5 {This is an important line} Nf5 $1 {Remember this idea} 12. Bf2 (12. Qd2) 12... Ncxd4 13. dxe6 (13. Ne5 exd5 14. Nxd5 Be6 15. c4 b5 16. b3 (16. Ne3 Nxe3 17. Bxe3 Bxc4 18. Nxc4 bxc4 19. Bd2 (19. Bxa8 Qxa8 {[%csl Rd4]}) 19... Rb8 {0-1 (50) Thomas,N (2286)-Turner,M (2517) England 2010}) 16... h5 {½-½ (30) Kuzmin,V (2418)-Szerlak,A (2406) ICCF email 2020}) 13... Bxe6 14. Nxd4 cxd4 15. Bxa8 Qxa8 {[%cal Ra8h1]} 16. Nb5 Bc4) (11. dxc5 d4) 11... Nf5 12. Bf2 Ba6 13. Re1 cxd4 (13... Ncxd4 14. Nxd4 Nxd4 15. Bxd4 cxd4 16. Ne2 d3 17. cxd3 b5 {[%cal Rd8b6,Rb5b4,Rf8c8]}) 14. Nxd4 Nfxd4 15. Bxd4 Nxd4 16. Qxd4 Qe7 {[%csl Rg7][%cal Rg7f8,Rf8c5]} 17. Qa4 Qc5+ 18. Kh1 Bb7 $17 19. Ne2 b5 20. Qb3 a5 21. Qd3 Rfc8 22. Nd4 b4 23. a4 Qb6 24. Rad1 Rc4 25. b3 Rc3 26. Qd2 Rac8 27. g4 Bh6 28. Rf1 Ba6 29. Rf3 Rxf3 30. Nxf3 Rc3 31. Re1 Qc5 32. Nd4 Bd3 33. Ne2 Bxe2 34. Rxe2 Qe7 35. g5 Bf8 {[%csl Ra5,Rb4][%cal Rd5d3]} 36. Re3 Qc5 37. Re2 Qb6 38. Qd1 Bc5 39. Qe1 Be3 40. Qf1 Qd4 41. f5 gxf5 {[%csl Re5,Rg5] 0-1 (41) Arakhamia Grant,K (2346)-Wojtaszek,R (2727) Caleta 2016} *

