1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. f4 {The Grand Prix Attack was always a scary weapon for unprepared players, but I believe that I found a very nice setup to meet it.} e6 {[%cal Rg8e7,Rd7d5] Black has a very simple idea. He want to continue with Ne7 followed by d5.} (3... g6 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. Bc4 e6) (3... d6) 4. Bb5 (4. Bc4 {Is not very logical. Because Black plays d5 with a tempo} Nge7 5. Nf3 (5. d3 d5 6. Bb3 dxe4 {the endgame is good for Black} (6... b5 $1 {is also very good} 7. Nf3 (7. a3 dxe4 8. dxe4 (8. Nxe4 Nf5 {[%cal Rf8e7,Rc8b7]}) 8... Qxd1+ 9. Kxd1 a6 $15 {[%csl Rb3][%cal Rc8b7]}) 7... c4 8. dxc4 dxc4 9. Qxd8+ Kxd8 10. Ng5 cxb3 11. Nxf7+ Ke8 12. Nxh8 Nb4 $15 {The position looks wild, but It is obvious that Black has the upper hand.}) 7. dxe4 Qxd1+ 8. Nxd1 Nd4 9. c3 Nxb3 10. axb3 b6 {Black enjoys the bishop pair and a very easy play. Black went to win a nice game 0-1 (36) Yuksel,A (2248)-Malakhatko,V (2508) Karlsruhe 2019}) 5... d5 6. Be2 Nd4 (6... dxe4 7. Nxe4 Ng6 $15 {[%cal Rf8e7,Re6e5]}) 7. d3 g6 8. O-O Bg7 9. a4 O-O $15 {0-1 (74) Kirwald,F (2360)-Tomek,D (2513) Remote email 2012}) (4. Nf3 d5 5. Bb5 Nge7 {transposes}) 4... Nge7 {avoiding doubled pawns on the c-file. The f8-bishop is temporarily trapped, but White can't open the position.} (4... d5) 5. Nf3 d5 {[%cal Ra7a6] This is one of the main positions of the line. White can choose between different continuations.} 6. exd5 (6. b3 {doesn't look too challenging.} a6 7. Bxc6+ Nxc6 8. Bb2 Be7 9. O-O O-O 10. d3 d4 (10... f6 $3 {[%cal Re4e5] I like this flexible move} 11. Qe1 (11. e5 fxe5 12. fxe5 Qc7 $17) 11... b5 12. Kh1 (12. e5 f5 $17 {[%csl Re4][%cal Rg1h1,Rg2f3,Rg2g4,Rd5d4,Rc8b7]}) 12... d4 13. Ne2 a5 {[%cal Ra5a4]} 14. a4 bxa4 15. Rxa4 Nb4 $17 {[%cal Rf6f5,Rc8b7,Rd8d7]}) 11. Nb1 b5 {[%cal Rf7f5]} 12. a4 Bb7 13. Nbd2 Qc7 14. Qe1 Nb4 15. Rc1 bxa4 16. bxa4 Bc6 17. Qe2 Bxa4 $19 {0-1 (37) Tari,A (2639)-Korobov,A (2683) Chess.com INT 2021}) (6. Qe2 {This move is always met by d5-d4} d4 7. Nd1 a6 8. Bxc6+ Nxc6 9. d3 Be7 10. O-O O-O {[%csl Rd1]} 11. Nf2 f5 12. a4 (12. Bd2 Bd7 13. g3 b5 14. Rae1 Qc7 $15 {0-1 (44) Kunin,V (2528)-Baramidze,D (2608) Nuremberg 2013}) 12... b6 13. b3 Qc7 14. Bd2 Kh8 15. h3 Bb7 16. Rae1 Rae8 {0-1 (74) Maghsoodloo,P (2676)-Korobov,A (2688) Chess.com INT 2020}) (6. O-O {doesn't pose any problems} a6 7. Bxc6+ Nxc6 8. d3 Be7 $15 {White has no compensation for the bishop pair}) 6... Nxd5 (6... exd5 $5 {First I analyzed this logical move, but I believe Black must be careful here.} 7. Qe2 $1 {[%cal Rb5c6,Re7c6]} (7. O-O a6 8. Bxc6+ Nxc6 9. Re1+ Be7 10. d3 O-O 11. Kh1 d4 12. Ne4 Qd5 13. Qe2 Bd7 14. Qf2 f5 15. Neg5 h6 16. Rxe7 Nxe7 {0-1 (31) Dilmukhametov,A (2293)-Demchenko,A (2654) Chess.com INT 2021}) 7... f6 (7... Bg4 {doesn't work very well} 8. Bxc6+ bxc6 9. O-O g6 10. Qe5 Rg8 11. f5 {Black's king stuck in the centre and White has dangerous initiative}) (7... g6 {also doesn't equalize clearly} 8. Qe5 Rg8 9. Bxc6+ bxc6 10. O-O Bg7 11. Qe2) 8. d4 $14 (8. Bxc6+ $6 bxc6 9. d3 Kf7 10. O-O Nf5 11. Bd2 h5 {[%cal Rc8d7] 0-1 (36) Jones,G (2640)-Van Wely,L (2656) Chess.com INT 2018})) 7. O-O (7. Bxc6+ {White can double the c-pawns} bxc6 8. d3 Nxc3 (8... c4 {leads to an interesting endgame after} 9. dxc4 Nxc3 10. Qxd8+ Kxd8 11. bxc3 Ba6 {Black probably will win the pawn back, but the position remains complicated}) 9. bxc3 c4 10. Ne5 (10. dxc4 Qxd1+ 11. Kxd1 {It is much better version of the endgame mentioned above}) 10... cxd3 11. cxd3 Bd6 {[%csl Rc3,Rf4][%cal Re5c6,Rd8c7] Black's bishop pair and White's weaknesses gives Black an edge} 12. O-O O-O 13. Kh1 Qc7 $15 {0-1 (25) Carmaciu,L (2398)-Wang,H (2712) Mamaia 2015}) (7. Ne5 {seems like the most promising try} Bd7 {[%cal Rc6e5,Rd8c7]} 8. Bxc6 Bxc6 9. Nxc6 (9. O-O) 9... bxc6 10. Qf3 {Now Black doesn't have bishop pair, but he has a strong knight and activity on the semi-open b and d files} (10. O-O) 10... Be7 (10... g6 {[%csl Rc5] I prefer this approach. Putting the bishop on the long diagonal leaves the c5-pawn unprotected, but Black has enough activity to compensate this} 11. b3 Nb4 (11... Bg7 12. Bb2 O-O 13. Na4 Bxb2 14. Nxb2 Qf6 $11) 12. O-O (12. Kd1 Bg7 13. Bb2 O-O {The engines is trying to tell me that White is slightly better, but no human can agree with that with a king on d1}) 12... Bg7 13. Bb2 O-O 14. Qd1 c4 {Black took the initiative and won 0-1 (51) Simacek,P (2464)-Shirov,A (2683) Czech Republic 2015}) 11. d3 O-O 12. Ne4 Qa5+ 13. c3 Rad8 {now the d3-pawn is a weakness} 14. O-O Qa6 $11 {[%csl Rc5,Rd3] ½-½ (26) Yakubboev,N (2600)-Kasimdzhanov,R (2652) Tashkent 2019}) 7... Be7 8. Ne5 Bd7 9. Bxc6 Bxc6 10. Nxc6 bxc6 {[%csl Rc5,Rc6,Rd8][%cal Ra8b8,Rc3e4]} 11. Ne4 {this move is premature, but White is not better anyway} f5 12. Ng5 Bxg5 13. Qh5+ g6 14. Qxg5 Qxg5 15. fxg5 Nb4 $1 {[%cal Rb4c2]} 16. c3 Nd3 $19 {amazing position. White is hopeless here} 17. b3 e5 18. Ba3 a5 19. Rae1 {[%cal Re5e4]} Nxe1 20. Rxe1 O-O-O 21. Bxc5 Rxd2 22. Rxe5 Rd5 23. Rxd5 cxd5 24. Kf2 Kd7 25. Bb6 Ra8 26. Kf3 a4 27. Bd4 Rb8 28. b4 Kc6 29. g4 fxg4+ 30. Kxg4 Re8 31. a3 Kb5 32. h4 Kc4 33. Kf3 Kb3 34. b5 Kxa3 35. b6 Kb3 36. b7 Rb8 {0-1 (36) Tari,A (2660)-Vokhidov,S (2536) Chess.com INT 2022} *

