1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {This move can cause a lot of trouble if you are unprepared. For the untrained eye, it looks very similar to Rossolimo, but there is one big difference - the f-pawn is not blocked, and White is threatening to continue with 4.Bxc6 followed by 5.f4 with an advantage.} Nd4 {This is the only move} 4. Nf3 (4. Bc4 {would be discussed in the next example}) 4... e6 (4... Nxb5 {Is also possible, but White compensates the loss of the bishop pair with an active play.} 5. Nxb5) 5. O-O (5. Nxd4 {Is the main alternative} cxd4 6. Ne2 Qg5 $1 {This is the key move for Black} 7. Bd3 (7. Nxd4 $2 {Is losing on the spot after:} Qc5 $1 8. c3 e5 9. Qa4 exd4 {White doesn't have enough compensation for the piece 0-1 (27) Moiseenko,V (2541)-Grachev,B (2611) Tuapse 2021}) 7... Qxg2 8. Ng3 Qh3 $17 {Black has a pawn up and White's king is vulnerable 0-1 (44) Ortiz Suarez,I (2520)-Bosiocic,M (2536) Waterloo 2022}) 5... a6 6. Bd3 Nc6 {It seems strange to return with the knight, but White bishop also stays awkward on "d3". If Black keeps the knight on "d4" then White will exchange it and play Ne2} (6... Ne7 {Is a decent alternative} 7. Nxd4 cxd4 8. Ne2 Nc6 9. c3 {is the main move and was tried by Magnus, but Black can improve MVL play on move 12} (9. a3 Bc5 10. b4 Ba7 11. Kh1 O-O 12. f4 d6 13. Ng1 e5 14. f5 d5 15. Nf3 $2 (15. f6 {gives White a winning attack}) 15... dxe4 ({Black could equalize with} 15... f6 $1 $11) 16. Bxe4 f6 17. c4 $6 (17. d3 $1 $16) 17... Ne7 (17... dxc3 $1 18. dxc3 Qxd1 $11) 18. Nh4 Rb8 19. d3 {0-1 (54) Grabinsky,A (2461)-Gelfand,B (2676) Chess.com INT 2020}) 9... Bc5 10. b4 Ba7 11. a4 O-O 12. b5 Ne5 (12... axb5 $1 {Is a good improvement} 13. axb5 Ne5 14. Bb1 (14. Qc2 $1 dxc3 15. Kh1 {with a complicated game}) 14... d3 15. Nd4 d5 16. exd5 exd5 $17 {0-1 (27) Deng,H (2117)-Rego,P (2305) Chess.com INT 2023}) 13. Bb1 dxc3 $6 {Is a mistake} (13... d3 14. Nf4 $14) 14. d4 Nc4 15. Nxc3 $16 {1-0 (64) Carlsen,M (2864)-Vachier Lagrave,M (2760) Zagreb 2022}) 7. b3 {seems logical to try to develop the bishop on the long diagonal. The drawback of this plan is that it gives Black enough time to smoothly finish the development.} (7. Re1 {Is very well met by the aggressive} g5 $1 {After this move, there is only one question. Can White equalize here? Black is threatening the very nasty g5-g4 and White knight has no squares available} 8. Rf1 {Giving Black two tempis hardly can be a good idea} (8. Kh1 {This is the most played move, but it leads to a big advantage for Black} g4 9. Ng1 h5 $1 {Black can keep the advantage in many ways. Probably Ivic didn't play the most accurate moves, but won a brilliant miniature} 10. Bf1 d6 11. d3 Nf6 12. Bg5 Bh6 13. Qd2 Bxg5 14. Qxg5 Rg8 15. Qd2 h4 16. g3 b5 17. Bg2 Bb7 18. Nge2 h3 19. Bf1 Ne5 20. Ng1 b4 21. Nd1 d5 22. Qf4 dxe4 23. Qxe5 exd3+ 24. f3 gxf3 25. Nf2 Ng4 26. Qxc5 Qd6 {0-1 (26) Timofeev,A (2567)-Ivic,V (2553) Chess.com INT 2022}) (8. h3 $2 {Is always bad in such position, because now Black has a hook} h5 9. Nh2 g4 $17) (8. h4 {Is one of the first computer lines, but looks weird and was tried only once in practice} g4 9. Nh2 Qxh4 (9... Ne5 {This looks very simple.} 10. Nxg4 Nxd3 11. cxd3 Qxh4 {My engine says equal, but with a human eye, the position looks horrible for White}) 10. Qxg4 Qh6) (8. g3 g4 9. Nh4 Be7 10. Qxg4 Ne5 11. Qf4 {White can choose another square for the queen, but it leads to transposition} Nxd3 12. cxd3 Bxh4 13. Qxh4 Qxh4 14. gxh4 Ne7 $15 {[%cal Rh8g8,Re6e5,Re7c6] White has an extra pawn, but just look at his pawn structure.}) 8... h5 9. Be2 g4 10. Ne1 Bg7 11. d3 {Two high-level games reach this position and Black won both of them} b5 (11... Nge7 12. Bg5 Qc7 13. Qd2 Nd4 14. Bd1 Ng6 15. Ne2 Nxe2+ 16. Bxe2 Bxb2 $15 {0-1 (48) Kamsky,G (2657)-Bellahcene,B (2528) Cap d'Agde 2021}) 12. f4 Bb7 13. Be3 Nd4 14. Qd2 Ne7 15. Nd1 f5 {0-1 (37) Harsha,B (2582)-Yoo,C (2573) Chess.com INT 2022}) (7. Be2 {is well met by} Nd4 {with a funny repetition. Of course Black can choose another move} (7... Qc7 {This transposes to not so dangerous lines in Taimanov after:} 8. d4)) (7. Nd5 {is the most recent try for White, which proves to be quite nasty} g6 (7... g5) (7... d6 8. Ne3 g5 9. c3 h5 10. Bc2 g4 11. Ne1 Bg7 (11... Nge7) (11... d5) 12. f3 Nh6 13. fxg4 hxg4 14. Nxg4 Qh4 15. Nxh6 Qxh6 16. h3 Qh4 17. Qf3 Qe7 18. Qg4 Rg8 19. Qh5 Rh8 20. Qg4 Rg8 21. Qh5 Rh8 22. Qg4 Rg8 {½-½ (22) Shevchenko,K (2684)-Vachier Lagrave,M (2742) Warsaw 2023}) 8. Re1 Bg7 9. c3 d6 10. Ne3 Nge7 11. Bc2 e5 12. a3 O-O 13. b4 (13. d3 Kh8 {[%cal Rf7f5]}) 13... b5) 7... d6 (7... Nd4) 8. Bb2 Nf6 9. Re1 {White is planning Bf1, followed by d2-d4 break or an immediate e5} g6 {Prag comes up with this interesting idea to develop the bishop on g7} (9... e5 {this move stops both threats but weakens the d5-square} 10. Nd5 (10. Bc4 {Is well met by} b5 11. Bd5 Bb7 12. Ne2 Be7 13. c3 O-O 14. Ng3 Nxd5 15. exd5 Na7 $11) 10... Be7 11. Bf1 O-O 12. c3 Bg4 13. h3 Bh5 14. Bc4 b5 15. Nxf6+ Bxf6 16. Bd5 Rc8 $11 {0-1 (41) Indjic,A (2618)-Theodorou,N (2591) Sharjah 2023}) (9... Be7 10. e5 (10. Bf1 O-O (10... e5 {is probably the simplest move, but we can also allow d4}) 11. d4 cxd4 12. Nxd4 Bd7 {White's setup is a bit weird}) 10... dxe5 11. Nxe5 Nxe5 12. Rxe5 Bd7 13. Qf3 Bc6 14. Qh3 Qc7 15. Rae1 O-O-O $15 {0-1 (30) Matinian,N (2460)-Dreev,A (2623) Chess.com INT 2022}) 10. e5 (10. Nd5 {could be simply met by} Bg7 $11) 10... Nxe5 11. Nxe5 dxe5 12. Rxe5 Bg7 $1 {the pawn on c5 is not important} 13. Rxc5 {Carlsen decides to accept the challenge} Nd7 {but now Black takes the initiative} 14. Rc4 Ne5 15. Ne2 Nf3+ 16. gxf3 Bxb2 17. Rb1 Bg7 {Black's bishop pair and the weakened position of White's king provide Prag with more than enough compensation for the sacrificing pawn, and he won a nice game.} 18. a4 O-O 19. Re4 Bd7 20. Re3 e5 21. Be4 Rb8 22. c4 Qh4 23. Bd5 Kh8 24. Qe1 f5 25. Kh1 b6 26. Nc3 Rbe8 27. Qg1 Bh6 28. b4 Bxe3 29. fxe3 f4 30. exf4 Qxf4 31. Qxb6 Qxd2 32. Ne4 Qd3 33. Re1 Qxf3+ 34. Kg1 Qg4+ 35. Ng3 Bxa4 36. Qxa6 Qd4+ 37. Kh1 Bb3 38. Re4 Qd1+ 39. Kg2 Bc2 40. Re2 Bd3 41. Qa2 Bxe2 42. Qxe2 Qd4 43. b5 Rd8 44. Kh3 Rxd5 45. cxd5 Qxd5 46. Ne4 Rf4 47. Ng3 h5 48. Qc2 Kg7 49. b6 Rf7 50. Qb2 Rb7 51. Qc3 Qe6+ 52. Kg2 Qxb6 53. Qxe5+ Qf6 54. Qd5 Re7 55. Qc5 h4 56. Nf1 Qe5 57. Qf2 Qe4+ 58. Kg1 Qg4+ 59. Kh1 Re2 60. Qa7+ Kh6 61. Qa8 Qe4+ {0-1 (63) Carlsen,M (2864)-Praggnanandhaa,R (2661) Miami 2022} *

