1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 e6 4. Bxc6 {This is a very important line. You need to understand very well the nuances of the position.} bxc6 {Black's structure is ugly, but also strengthened because we bring one more pawn to the centre. Also, Black can handle the structure in many different ways. For example: d7-d5, d6-e5, f6-e5. It depends on White's play. There are several options for White to continue. We will check them one by one.} (4... dxc6 {Is a bad move. Black can't play Bg4. Can't play e7-e5 in one move, because we are already committed to e6. White is better and has an effortless play - d3, b3, 0-0, etc...}) 5. e5 (5. O-O {This move is a small mistake. Let me explain you why. If the game continues with random moves, Black will be much better. Let me give you an example:} Ne7 6. e5 (6. Re1 Ng6 7. c3 (7. d3 e5 8. b3 d6 9. Bb2 Be7 10. Nbd2 O-O $15 {Black is much better and ready for the break f7-f5. The bishop on b2 is very passive, and White has no compensation for the bishop pair. I like this variation because White can get in trouble without making any obvious mistakes}) 7... d5 8. d4 dxe4 9. Rxe4 Be7 10. Qc2 cxd4 $15 {0-1 (28) Ponkratov,P (2613)-Moiseenko,A (2659) Chess.com INT 2018}) (6. d3 Ng6 7. Ng5 f6 8. Nh3 d5 9. Nc3 Be7 10. Qh5 O-O $15 {0-1 (39) Pranav,V (2597)-Ibarra Jerez,J (2563) Chess.com INT 2023}) (6. b3 Ng6 7. Bb2 (7. e5 f6 8. Bb2 Be7 9. d3 O-O 10. Nbd2 fxe5 11. Nxe5 Nxe5 12. Bxe5 d6 13. Bg3 Bf6 14. Rb1 e5 15. Ne4 Bf5 (15... Be7 {[%cal Rc8f5]}) 16. Nxf6+ Qxf6 17. Qf3 Rac8 18. Rbe1 Qg6 {½-½ (18) Pietinen,P (2024)-Topi Hulmi,T (2253) Pori 2014}) 7... f6 8. c3 d5 9. Re1 Be7 10. d4 O-O 11. dxc5 Bxc5 12. Ba3 Bxa3 13. Nxa3 e5 14. exd5 cxd5 15. c4 d4 $19 {0-1 (27) Samhouri,A (2355)-Moiseenko,A (2667) Riadh 2017}) 6... Ng6 7. Re1 f6 (7... Be7 8. c4 f6 9. Nc3 fxe5 10. Nxe5 Nxe5 11. Rxe5 O-O 12. Re1 Bh4 13. Rf1 e5 14. d3 d5 $17 {0-1 (33) Stoyanov,T (2450)-Theodorou,N (2575) Chennai 2022}) 8. exf6 gxf6 9. d4 cxd4 10. Nxd4 Be7 11. Bh6 Qa5 12. c4 Rg8 13. Nc3 Ba6 14. Qd3 Qh5 15. Bd2 Ne5 16. Qc2 c5 $19 {0-1 (71) Murzin,V (2465)-Gelfand,B (2676) Lichess.org INT 2020}) (5. b3 {Is a move in which Anand tried to beat Gelfand in a crucial game in the World Championship. There are many moves for Black in this position, but let me explain White's main idea first. White wants to meet the Ne7-g6 maneuver with h2-h4 and he wants to meet the immediate f6 with Nh4} Ne7 {is the main move in this position, but I believe that White is doing fine after:} (5... f6 6. O-O Nh6 7. d4 Nf7 8. c4 cxd4 9. Nxd4 c5 (9... Qc7 10. Nc3 Be7 11. Na4 O-O 12. Qc2 Re8 13. Be3 d6 14. Rad1 Bf8 15. Ne2 Qa5 16. h3 Bb7 {½-½ (16) Roques,P (2380)-Vinchev,S (2491) ICCF email 2020}) 10. Ne2 Bb7 11. Nbc3 Be7 12. f4 O-O 13. f5 Bd6 14. Bf4 Be5 15. Bxe5 Nxe5 16. Qd6 Rc8 17. Rad1 $14 {½-½ (67) Onischuk,V (2622)-Gelfand,B (2680) Riga 2021}) (5... e5 {this is Gelfand's choice, but it leads to some pretty sharp positions after:} 6. Nxe5 Qe7 7. Bb2 (7. d4 d6 8. Nxc6 Qxe4+ 9. Qe2 Qxe2+ 10. Kxe2 Bb7 11. Na5 Bxg2 12. Rg1 Bh3 13. dxc5 dxc5 14. Nc3 $14 {1-0 (77) Anand,V (2791)-Gelfand,B (2727) Moscow 2012}) 7... d6 8. Nc4 d5 9. Ne3 d4 10. Nc4 Qxe4+ 11. Qe2 Qxe2+ 12. Kxe2 $14 {½-½ (25) Anand,V (2791)-Gelfand,B (2727) Moscow 2012}) (5... d6 6. e5 {Is the most serious try} (6. O-O Ne7 {Black is waiting for Bb2 to play e6-e5} 7. Re1 (7. e5 {Carlsen went for an immediate e5, but then Radjabov shows the dynamic potential of the position} Ng6 8. exd6 Bxd6 9. Nc3 e5 {Despite the ruined structure on the queenside, Black is perfectly fine here. He has great attacking chances on the kingside.} 10. Re1 O-O 11. d3 f5 12. Ba3 Be6 13. Na4 Qe7 14. c4 Rad8 15. Qe2 Bc8 16. Qe3 f4 $15 {½-½ (37) Carlsen,M (2872)-Radjabov,T (2793) London 2013}) 7... Ng6 8. Na3 Be7 9. Nc4 O-O (9... e5 {I prefer this move and think Black is better here, but the plan Radjabov chose also deserves attention.}) 10. e5 d5 11. Ne3 f6 $1 {undermining the centre} 12. Bb2 a5 13. a4 Rb8 14. d3 Qc7 15. Ng4 f5 {Black won space on both flanks. His only weakness is the c-pawn, but it is not easy for White's pieces to attack this pawn.} 16. Ne3 Bd7 17. Qc1 Be8 18. Nf1 Nh8 $1 19. Ba3 Nf7 20. Qe3 Qb6 21. Qd2 Rb7 22. Ng3 Qa7 23. Ne2 g5 {Black starts his active play on the kingside} 24. Ng3 g4 25. Nd4 Bg5 26. f4 gxf3 27. Qf2 cxd4 $19 {0-1 (59) Nepomniachtchi,I (2721)-Radjabov,T (2713) Beijing 2013}) (6. Bb2 $6 e5 $15 {and as we know, in this type of position, Black is better}) 6... f6 $1 (6... dxe5 {taking on e5 is the main move for Black and leads to interesting complications} 7. Nxe5 (7. d3 {New move tried by Magnus} f6 {we should accept the challenge} 8. Nbd2 Nh6 9. Rg1 Ba6 $2 (9... Qa5 $1 {Is a critical test for White's idea. Black wants to break with c4 and e4 and to open the position for his bishops. White's king must have no safe spot.} 10. g4 {is simply not very good due to} (10. Kf1 Ba6 {[%cal Re8c8]}) 10... c4 11. bxc4 (11. g5 Nf7 $15) 11... e4 12. dxe4 Rb8 $15) 10. g4 Nf7 11. Qe2 Be7 12. Bb2 Qa5 13. c4 g5 14. h4 h6 15. Rh1 O-O-O 16. O-O-O {1-0 (43) Carlsen,M (2835)-Abasov,N (2632) Baku 2023}) 7... Qd4 $2 (7... Qd5 8. Nf3 Qe4+ 9. Qe2 Qxe2+ (9... Qxc2 {this move looks too risky for me. Usually I would like to play with compensation} 10. O-O) 10. Kxe2 $14 {This endgame is slightly worse for Black}) (7... Qg5 {Abasov tried this interesting idea, which seems to be close to equality after:} 8. Ng4 Nh6 9. Ne3 Nf5 10. O-O Nxe3 11. fxe3 Bd6 12. Bb2 O-O 13. Qf3 f5 14. Na3 Ba6 {½-½ (109) Vidit,S (2719)-Abasov,N (2632) Baku 2023}) 8. Nc4 Qxa1 9. Nc3 $18 {This looks almost winning for White1-0 (30) Zhao,J (2434)-Zhang,P (2579) Moscow 2004}) 7. exd6 (7. exf6 $2 Nxf6 $15 {[%cal Re6e5,Rc8g4] Black is simply better here}) 7... Bxd6 $1 {why to hurry with e6-e5} (7... e5 8. d3 Bxd6 9. Nfd2 $1 $14 {[%cal Rd2c4,Rb1c3] 1-0 (42) Esipenko,A (2723)-Moiseenko,A (2602) Germany 2022}) 8. Nc3 e5 {We are ready to abandon the c5-pawn and start our own play on the kingside and the centre.} 9. Ne4 Ne7 10. Ba3 O-O 11. Qe2 Bc7 (11... Nd5 12. Nxd6 Qxd6 13. Qc4 Qc7 14. Bxc5 Re8 15. d3 Be6 {Black has enough compensation for the pawn 0-1 (50) Garifullina,L (2409)-Paehtz,E (2475) Riga 2021}) 12. Qc4+ Nd5 13. Qxc5 Re8 14. Qxc6 Be6 {[%cal Rd5f4,Re6d5]}) 6. d3 (6. Bb2 Ng6 (6... f6 7. Nh4 $14) 7. h4 {is already unpleasant for Black: 0-1 (42) Sidhant,M (2376)-Shevchenko,K (2684) Bucharest 2023}) 6... d6 7. h4 e5 8. h5 Ng8 9. Nbd2 Be7 10. Nc4 f5 11. Qe2 Nf6 12. Bd2 O-O 13. exf5 Bxf5 14. Ne3 Qd7 15. Nxf5 Qxf5 16. h6 g6 17. Bg5 Rae8 18. O-O Nd5 19. Bd2 Nf4 20. Bxf4 Qxf4 21. Qe3 Rf5 22. Rae1 Qxe3 23. fxe3 Ref8 24. Nd2 Rxf1+ 25. Rxf1 Rxf1+ 26. Kxf1 Kf7 27. Ke2 Bf8 28. Ne4 Ke7 29. g4 Bxh6 30. Kf3 Bf8 31. c4 h6 32. Kg3 Ke6 33. Nd2 Be7 34. e4 Bg5 35. Nf3 Bf4+ 36. Kg2 d5 37. Nh4 Bg5 38. Nf3 Bf6 39. Kg3 d4 40. Kh3 Kd6 41. Kg3 Kc7 42. g5 hxg5 43. Kg4 Kd6 44. Nxg5 Ke7 45. Nf3 Kf7 46. Nh2 Kg7 47. Nf3 Kf7 48. Ne1 Be7 49. Nf3 Bf6 {½-½ (49) Yu,Y (2729)-Yakubboev,N (2630) Chess.com INT 2023}) (5. d3 Qc7) 5... f6 6. b3 (6. h4 fxe5 7. Nxe5 Qf6 (7... d6 8. Qh5+ (8. Nf3 e5) 8... g6 9. Nxg6 Nf6 $19) 8. Qe2 Bd6 9. Ng4 Qg6 $15 {0-1 (43) Koziol,K (2276)-Yilmaz,M (2630) Chess.com INT 2021}) 6... fxe5 7. Nxe5 Nf6 8. Bb2 d6 9. Ng4 e5 10. Nxf6+ Qxf6 11. Nc3 Qg6 (11... Bf5) 12. Qf3 d5 13. d3 Bd6 14. O-O Bg4 15. Qg3 e4 16. Qh4 Bf3 17. Qh3 O-O 18. dxe4 d4 19. Na4 Bxe4 20. f3 Bxc2 21. Ba3 Rf5 22. g4 Re5 23. Qg2 Rae8 24. Rf2 Bd3 25. Rd2 Re2 26. Rxe2 Rxe2 27. Qxe2 Bxe2 28. Bxc5 Bxc5 29. Nxc5 Bxf3 {0-1 (29) Dourerassou,J (2573)-Lagarde,M (2659) Orsay 2018} *

