1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 e6 4. Bxc6 bxc6 5. d3 Qc7 {[%cal Rf3h4] This is a perfect waiting move. We are waiting for White to castle short, and in the meantime, we are preparing to play e6-e5.} (5... d5 {this move is connected with some strategical risks}) (5... Ne7 {[%cal Re7g6,Rd7d6,Re6e5] This is a move that we always play in the Rossolimo, but in this variation, I don't like this approach because White is not committed to 0-0 and can play h2-h4 in any moment.} 6. h4 $1) (5... d6 {this time is well met by e5} 6. e5) 6. Nbd2 (6. O-O {After this move the threat h2-h4 is not so dangerous, although still playable} Ne7 {[%cal Re7g6]} (6... e5 {[%cal Rc2c3,Rd3d4,Rf3h4,Rf2f4] seems premature. White can quickly blow up the center using c3-d4 or Nh4-f4 breaks}) 7. h4 (7. Ng5 h6 8. Qh5 (8. Nh3 d5 9. f4 c4 $13) 8... g6 9. Qh4 Bg7 10. Nh3 g5 11. Qh5 e5 $15 {0-1 (82) Vokhidov,S (2521)-Sjugirov,S (2663) Chess.com INT 2021}) (7. e5 $5 Ng6 8. Re1 Be7 9. h4 f6 10. h5 (10. Nbd2 O-O 11. exf6 Bxf6 12. Ne4 Bxh4 {1-0 (32) Grover,S (2505)-Lupulescu,C (2640) Al Ain 2014}) 10... Nxe5 11. Nxe5 fxe5) (7. c3 Ng6 8. h4 (8. d4 Be7 9. Re1 O-O) 8... h5 $132) 7... d6 {[%cal Re6e5,Rh7h5,Re7g6]} 8. h5 h6 9. Nbd2 (9. Nh2 {Aronian chooses this move, but Black has an astonishing move at his disposal} Ng8 (9... g5 $1 {[%cal Rf8g7,Re8g8,Rf7f5] This move is extremely strong here. Black wants to develop his bishop to g7, and If White takes on g6, then Black starts an attack on the semi-open g-file.} 10. hxg6 Nxg6 11. f4 f5 {[%cal Re8f7,Re8d7]} 12. Nd2 Qg7 {[%cal Re8d7,Rf8e7]} 13. Kh1 Kd7 {[%cal Rd7c7,Rc8d7,Rf8e7,Rh6h5] Amazing concept. Black has serious attacking chances on the kingside.}) 10. f4 Nf6 11. Nc3 Be7 12. Qe2 e5 13. fxe5 dxe5 14. b3 $14) (9. e5 $1 {is probably the strongest, but I like Black's chances after the simple} dxe5 10. Re1 Nf5 (10... f6 $6 11. Nh4 $16) (10... g5 $5 {is possible here too}) 11. Nxe5 Bd6 12. Nc4 Bh2+ 13. Kh1 O-O 14. Nbd2 Bf4 {with an acceptable possition}) 9... g5 10. e5 dxe5 11. Re1 Bg7 12. Nc4 Ba6 13. Nfxe5 Rd8 14. Bd2 Rd5 {0-1 (41) Volokitin,A (2674)-Theodorou,N (2575) Chennai 2022}) (6. Qe2 {White loses time and Black can proceed with his main plan} e5 7. O-O (7. Nbd2 Ne7 8. Nc4 Ng6 9. h4 (9. a3 f6 10. h4 h5 11. Ne3 Nf4 12. Qd1 d5 $1 13. g3 Ne6 14. exd5 cxd5 15. Nxd5 Qc6 16. c4 Nc7 $17) 9... h5 10. g3 d6 11. Bd2 f6 $11 {1-0 (43) Firouzja,A (2728)-Carlsen,M (2863) chess24.com INT 2020}) 7... Nf6 (7... Ne7 {also works well} 8. g3 d6 9. Nh4 Bh3 10. Ng2 h5 {[%cal Rh5h4]} 11. f4 h4 12. fxe5 $2 (12. g4 $13) 12... hxg3 13. hxg3 Ng6 $17 {½-½ (60) Aveskulov,V (2471)-Kovalev,A (2526) Pardubice 2006}) 8. Nfd2 Be7 9. Nc3 O-O 10. f4 exf4 11. Nc4 f3 12. Qxf3 d5 13. Bf4 Qb7 14. Ne5 Be6 $11) (6. e5 {Here we use one of our main principles in this line. When White plays e5 without Black's pawn on d6, we undermine the center by means of f7-f6.} f6 7. Qe2 fxe5 8. Nxe5 Ne7 9. O-O d6 10. Nc4 Nf5 11. Bf4 Be7 12. Nc3 O-O {Black is ready to advance with e6-e5 followed by Nd4 0-1 (25) Sanchez Romero,M (2259)-Antoli Royo,J (2441) Burguillos 2008}) (6. b3 {[%cal Re6e5] is simply met by} e5 7. O-O Ne7 8. Bb2 d6 $15 {[%cal Rf7f5]}) 6... Ne7 (6... e5 {After this move, the position becomes a mess} 7. O-O (7. Nh4 Ne7 8. f4 exf4 9. O-O h6 10. b3 g5 (10... d5 $5) 11. Bb2 Rg8 12. Nf5 d5 13. Qh5 Bxf5 14. exf5 Nxf5 15. Rfe1+ Ne3 16. Nf1 d4 $19) (7. a3 a5 8. Nc4 d6 9. a4 Nf6 10. h3 Be7 11. O-O O-O $11 {Later Grischuk becomes ambitious and lost, but the outcome of the opening is definitely in his favor 1-0 (65) Pichot,A (2637)-Grischuk,A (2745) Chess.com INT 2022}) 7... Ne7 8. Nc4 (8. Re1 {This type of move are always in Black's favour. Black can easily finish his development. The only sensible plan for White is to open the centre by means of a c3-d4 break, but then Black's bishops have a lot of freedom.} Ng6 9. c3 Be7 10. d4 cxd4 11. cxd4 d6 12. Nc4 Bg4 13. dxe5 dxe5 14. h3 Be6 $11 {0-1 (56) Xu,Y (2527)-Yu,Y (2709) Xinghua 2021}) 8... f6 9. Bd2 d5 {Black's position looks fantastic} 10. Ba5 Qb8 11. Ne3 Be6 12. b4 d4 $17 {½-½ (41) Svidler,P (2723)-Gelfand,B (2676) chess24.com INT 2020}) 7. O-O (7. h4 {Anand tried this ambitious move} h5 {[%cal Re7g6,Rf8e7]} (7... e5 {Gelfand tried this, but I believe White's position is easier to handle after:} 8. h5 f6 9. Nf1 d5 10. c4 Be6 $13) 8. e5 $1 {The only way to pose problems. Otherwise Ng6 will come} Nf5 9. Ne4 d5 10. exd6 Bxd6 {The engine likes White, but I believe that it is playable. For the ruined structure, we have free development. In the only game that reached this position, Black did very well, but If you don't like the position, you can always opt for 7...e5} 11. Nxd6+ Qxd6 12. Qe2 f6 13. Be3 e5 14. O-O-O Be6 15. c4 Rb8 $11 {½-½ (42) Vokhidov,S (2521)-Sjugirov,S (2663) Chess.com INT 2021}) 7... Ng6 8. Nc4 d5 ({Of course we can proceed with:} 8... e5 {but 8...d5 is more ambitious}) 9. Ne3 Be7 10. g3 O-O 11. h4 dxe4 12. dxe4 Ba6 13. Re1 Rfd8 14. Bd2 Ne5 15. Kg2 Nxf3 16. Kxf3 Qe5 $17 17. Qc1 Qh5+ 18. Kg2 Qg6 19. f3 Bxh4 20. Ng4 h5 21. Rh1 Bxg3 22. Kxg3 hxg4 23. Rh4 gxf3+ 24. Rg4 Qf6 25. Bc3 e5 26. Qe3 f2 27. Qxf2 Qxf2+ 28. Kxf2 f6 29. Rh1 Bc8 30. Rgh4 Be6 31. b3 Kf7 32. Ke2 a5 33. a4 c4 34. bxc4 Bxc4+ 35. Ke3 Rd7 36. Rb1 Rc7 37. Rb6 Be6 38. Rh1 c5 39. Rb5 Bd7 40. Rxa5 Rxa5 41. Bxa5 Ra7 42. Bb6 Rxa4 43. Bxc5 Rxe4+ 44. Kd3 Bb5+ 45. Kd2 Rc4 46. Be3 f5 47. Rb1 Bc6 48. Ra1 f4 {0-1 (48) Sjugirov,S (2712)-Sadhwani,R (2627) Krasnogorsk 2023} *

