1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 e6 4. O-O Nge7 5. d4 {This move is very ambitious. The game transposes to an Open Sicilian. White's bishop is slightly misplaced on b5, but also our knight is already committed to "e7"} cxd4 6. Nxd4 Ng6 {This is the modern way to handle the position. Black is ready to proceed with Be7, 0-0 and only later to think about how to handle the position in the center.} (6... Qb6 {is the old main line, but it seems that Black can't equalize after:} 7. Nxc6 bxc6 8. Be2 {White is ready to proceed with c4, Nc3, Be3, etc...}) 7. Be2 {Is the most popular move, which some strong players, including Anand played many times.} (7. Be3 {is another setup for White} Be7 8. c3 $5 {With the idea to met Nxd4 with cxd4.} (8. Be2 $5 O-O 9. c4 (9. Nc3 $5 a6 $1 10. f4 $5 Qc7 11. a4 b6 12. Nxc6 Qxc6 13. Bd3 Bb7 14. Kh1 f5 {0-1 (41) Kulaots,K (2526)-Meskovs,N (2576) Tallinn 2023}) 9... Nxd4 $1 10. Qxd4 b6 $5 11. Nc3 Bb7 12. Rfd1 Bc6 13. Qd2 f5 {0-1 (30) Darini,P (2432)-Maghsoodloo,P (2676) Teheran 2021}) 8... O-O 9. Nd2 a6 {Here the simplest is to play a6 followed by Nxd4 and b5.} 10. Be2 (10. Bd3 b5 11. Qh5 Bb7 12. Rad1 Nxd4 13. cxd4 Qe8 14. f3 f6 {½-½ (70) Navara,D (2676)-Gelfand,B (2668) Czech Republic 2022}) 10... Nxd4 11. cxd4 b5 {[%cal Rc8b7]} 12. Bd3 $1 (12. a4 $6 bxa4 $1 13. Qxa4 Bb7 14. Rfc1 f5 $132) 12... Bb7 13. Qh5 Qe8 $5 {[%csl Rg6][%cal Rf7f6] This is a very typical defensive mechanism: ½-½ (17) Nguyen,T (2645)-Praggnanandhaa,R (2688) Sharjah 2023}) 7... Be7 {We will follow in the footsteps of GM Gelfand. Black's main idea is to finish the development and open the position using f7-f5 break.} 8. c4 O-O 9. Nc3 b6 {[%cal Rf7f5]} 10. Be3 (10. Ndb5 $146 a6 11. Nd6 Qc7 12. Nxc8 Raxc8 {[%csl Rb5,Rc8,Rd4,Rd6,Rf3,Rg1]} (12... Rfxc8 $5 13. Be3 Bc5 $11) 13. Be3 Bc5 $11 {Fedorchuk eventually won, but for me Black has at least equal position. I believe that Black is even slightly better here. 1-0 (30) Fedorchuk,S (2619)-Gukesh,D (2732) Mayrhofen 2022}) (10. Nb3 $5 Bb7 11. f4 (11. Be3 {transposes to the main line}) 11... f5 12. exf5 Nh4 $5 13. fxe6 dxe6 14. Bg4 Nf5 $44 {I always like this type of positional sacrifice. For the sacrificing pawn, Black has good initiative. All White pieces are kind of misplaced.}) (10. f4 $4 {Is just a blunder} Nxd4 11. Qxd4 Bc5) 10... Bb7 11. Nb3 (11. g3 {Looks inferior} Nxd4 12. Qxd4 (12. Bxd4 Qc7 $11 {[%cal Gf7f5]}) 12... Bf6 13. Qd3 Bxc3 14. bxc3 (14. Qxc3 Bxe4 $15) 14... f5 $17 {1-0 (27) Saric,I (2668)-Gelfand,B (2668) chess24.com INT 2022}) (11. Ndb5 {As we know this move is just waste of time} Qb8 12. Qd2 a6 13. Nd4 (13. Na3 f5 $5 $132) 13... Nxd4 14. Qxd4 Bf6 $11) (11. Nxc6 $6 {This is from another opera, Black has at least equal chances after the simple:} Bxc6 12. Qd2 (12. Rc1 $6 f5 $1 $15) 12... f5 $1 13. exf5 Nh4 $1 $11) 11... Qc8 $1 {[%cal Rc6e5,Re5c4] One of the ideas is to play Ne5 and simply to take on c4.} (11... Qc7 {The queen is misplaced here. White always has some Nb5 ideas.} 12. Rc1 Rad8 13. f4 Qb8 14. g3 Rfe8 15. Bf3 d6 16. Nd4 Nxd4 17. Qxd4 d5 18. cxd5 Bc5 19. Qd2 Bxe3+ 20. Qxe3 exd5 $15 {0-1 (52) Anand,V (2756)-Gelfand,B (2668) Leon 2022}) 12. f4 f5 $1 13. exf5 Nh4 $1 14. fxe6 dxe6 {[%csl Rd8] one more reason why we needed to move the queen from d8} 15. Ne4 (15. g3 Nf5 16. Bf2 Rd8 $19 {[%cal Rc6b4]}) (15. Bg4 Nxg2 16. Kxg2 Ne5+ 17. Bf3 Nxf3 18. Rxf3 Bf6 $44) 15... Nb4 16. Nbd2 Rd8 17. Qb1 Qc6 {[%cal Re2f3]} 18. a3 Rxd2 $3 19. Bxd2 Bc5+ 20. Rf2 (20. Nxc5 Qxg2#) (20. Kh1 Qxe4 21. Qxe4 Bxe4 {[%cal Rb4c2]} 22. axb4 Bxg2#) 20... Bxf2+ 21. Kxf2 Na6 22. Bf3 Nxf3 23. gxf3 Qxc4 {The computer still says 0.00, but White's position looks horrible from a human eye.} 24. Qa2 Qxa2 25. Rxa2 Bd5 $15 26. Ra1 Bxe4 27. fxe4 Nc5 28. Ke3 Rd8 29. Bb4 Rd3+ 30. Ke2 Rb3 31. Bxc5 bxc5 32. Rc1 Rxb2+ 33. Ke3 Rxh2 34. Rxc5 Rh3+ 35. Kd4 Rxa3 36. Ke5 Ra6 37. Rc8+ Kf7 38. Rc7+ Kg6 39. Re7 h5 40. Rxe6+ Rxe6+ 41. Kxe6 h4 42. f5+ Kh7 43. e5 h3 44. f6 h2 45. f7 h1=Q 46. f8=Q Qh3+ 47. Qf5+ Qxf5+ 48. Kxf5 a5 49. Ke6 a4 50. Kd6 a3 51. e6 a2 52. e7 a1=Q 53. e8=Q Qd4+ 54. Kc7 Qa7+ 55. Kd6 Qb6+ 56. Kd5 Qg6 57. Qe3 Qf5+ 58. Kd4 Qd7+ 59. Kc3 Qd5 60. Qh3+ Kg6 61. Qg3+ Kf6 62. Qf4+ Qf5 63. Qh4+ Qg5 64. Qh8 Kf5 65. Kd3 Kf4 66. Kc4 Kg3 67. Qe8 Kf2 68. Qf7+ Kg2 69. Qe6 Qf4+ 70. Kb5 g5 71. Qd5+ Kh2 72. Ka6 g4 73. Qh5+ Kg1 74. Kb7 Qe4+ 75. Kb8 Qb4+ 76. Ka8 Qf8+ 77. Kb7 Qf3+ 78. Kb8 Qf4+ 79. Ka8 g3 80. Qd1+ Qf1 81. Qd4+ Qf2 82. Qa1+ Kg2 83. Qe5 Qf8+ 84. Kb7 Qf7+ 85. Kb8 Kf3 86. Qc3+ Kg4 87. Qc8+ Qf5 88. Qg8+ Kf4 89. Qc4+ Qe4 90. Qf7+ Kg4 91. Qg7+ Kf3 92. Qc3+ Qe3 93. Qc6+ Ke2 94. Qc2+ Ke1 95. Qb1+ Kf2 96. Qc2+ Kg1 97. Qb1+ Kh2 98. Qh7+ Kg2 99. Qc2+ Qf2 100. Qe4+ Kg1 101. Qb1+ Qf1 102. Qb6+ Kh2 103. Qh6+ Qh3 104. Qf4 Qh8+ 105. Ka7 Qh7+ 106. Kb8 Kh3 107. Qe3 Qg6 108. Ka7 Qd6 109. Ka8 Kh2 110. Qe2+ g2 111. Qh5+ Kg1 112. Qf5 Qh6 113. Qc5+ Kh1 114. Qd5 Qh4 115. Kb7 Qe7+ 116. Ka8 Qa3+ 117. Kb7 Qb4+ 118. Ka7 Qe7+ 119. Ka8 Qf6 120. Qh5+ Kg1 121. Qd5 Kh2 122. Qd2 Qc6+ 123. Kb8 Kh1 124. Qd1+ g1=Q 125. Qh5+ Qh2+ {0-1 (125) Mishra,A (2550)-Gelfand,B (2678) Malmo 2023} *

