1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 e6 4. O-O Nge7 5. Re1 a6 (5... Ng6 {[%cal Rf8e7,Re8g8]} 6. c3) 6. Bf1 Ng6 {I can suggest you a very simple setup. As in the 5.d4 line, we can just finish the development and then play d7-d5. This move was considered slow because White can build a strong centre by means of c3-d4, but it appears that Black is just fine there.} (6... d5 {For many years this was the main theory, but it seems that White has the upper hand in this line. The most important game is Carlsen-Gelfand.} 7. exd5 Nxd5 {[%csl Rf1]} 8. d4 Nf6 9. Be3 cxd4 10. Nxd4 Bd7 11. c4 Nxd4 12. Bxd4 Bc6 13. Nc3 $14 {Magnus manages to convert his slight advantage to a full point 1-0 (48) Carlsen,M (2872)-Gelfand,B (2740) London 2013}) 7. c3 {[%cal Rd2d4]} Be7 {[%cal Re8g8,Rd7d5]} 8. d4 cxd4 9. cxd4 {[%cal Rd4d5]} d5 10. Nc3 {allows also dxe4} (10. e5 {This "French" structure is good for Black now. His plan is simple: 0-0, Bd followed by f6 in an appropriate moment.} O-O {[%cal Rc8d7,Rf7f6]} 11. Nc3 Bd7 12. g3 (12. Be3) (12. Bd3 {against this move, Black has a very nice plan} h6 {[%cal Rg6h4] with the idea Nh4} 13. Bxg6 $6 {is just wrong} fxg6 $15) 12... h6 $1 {Is an alternative way to continue. Black covers the g5-square and he is ready to continue with f6, followed by Rxf6. I like this approach more than the immediate f6} (12... f6 {Is of course perfectly playable.} 13. exf6 Rxf6 14. Bg5 Rf8 15. Bxe7 Ngxe7 {[%cal Re7f5]} 16. Bg2 Nf5 {0-1 (31) Giri,A (2764)-Carlsen,M (2859) chess24.com INT 2022}) 13. Be3 (13. Bd3 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Rg6h8,Rh8f7]} Be8 {[%cal Rf7f6]}) 13... f5 14. exf6 Rxf6 {[%cal Re7d6]} 15. Bg2 Bd6 16. Rc1 (16. h4 Nge7 {0-1 (39) Boruchovsky,A (2553)-Caruana,F (2766) Chess.com INT 2023}) 16... Nge7 17. Na4 (17. Ne2 Nf5 (17... Be8 $1 $11) 18. Bf4 Bxf4 19. Nxf4 Qb6 $14 {1-0 (52) So,W (2772)-Caruana,F (2791) Chess.com INT 2021}) 17... Nf5 18. Nc5 Bxc5 19. Rxc5 Qb6 20. Qd2 Raf8 {½-½ (45) Rapport,R (2752)-Carlsen,M (2835) Zagreb 2023}) (10. exd5 {Transposes to the main line} exd5 $1) 10... O-O (10... dxe4 11. Nxe4 O-O 12. g3 b6 13. h4 Bb4 {[%cal Rg6e7]} 14. Re2 h6 15. Qc2 Bb7 16. h5 Nge7 17. a3 Rc8 $15 {0-1 (30) Bacrot,E (2656)-Caruana,F (2783) Chess.com INT 2022}) 11. exd5 exd5 {[%cal Re7f6] It is hard to suggest a constructive idea for White here. The knight on g6 is actually much more useful than on f6. He controls the center, leaves the f6-square for the bishop, and can be easily transferred to a more active position via e7-f5 or "f4" in some cases} 12. g3 (12. Be3 Be6 13. Na4 Bb4 14. Bd2 Qd6 15. Bxb4 Qxb4 16. h3 Rae8 17. Nc5 Bc8 18. Rxe8 Rxe8 19. Qb3 Qxb3 20. Nxb3 f6 21. Rc1 Nge7 22. a3 Kf7 {[%csl Rd4] Caruana manages even to win this endgame 0-1 (68) Grandelius,N (2662)-Caruana,F (2800) Riga 2021}) (12. h3 Be6 13. Bd3 Rc8 14. Be3 Na5 15. Qd2 Qd7 16. Ng5 Bf5 17. Bxf5 Qxf5 $11 {and suddenly Black is better here.0-1 (40) Mekhitarian,K (2554)-Korobov,A (2683) Chess.com INT 2021}) 12... Be6 13. Bg2 h6 14. a3 Re8 $11 {Black has a very easy game. Just Bf6, Ne7-f5, Rc8, etc...} 15. h4 Rc8 16. Qd3 Bf6 17. h5 Nge7 18. Ne5 Nf5 19. Nxf7 Bxf7 20. Rxe8+ Qxe8 21. Qxf5 Nxd4 22. Qd3 Qe1+ 23. Kh2 Qxf2 24. Bf4 Qxb2 25. Rc1 Bxh5 26. Nxd5 Nf3+ 27. Kh3 Rxc1 28. Bxc1 Ng1+ 29. Kh2 Qxc1 30. Nxf6+ gxf6 31. Qd5+ Bf7 32. Qxb7 Ne2 33. Qa7 Kg7 34. Bd5 Qg1+ 35. Qxg1 Nxg1 36. Bxf7 Kxf7 37. Kxg1 Ke6 38. Kf2 Kf5 39. Kf3 h5 40. a4 a5 41. Kf2 Ke4 42. Kg2 Ke3 43. Kh3 f5 44. Kh4 Kf2 45. Kh3 Kg1 46. g4 hxg4+ 47. Kg3 Kf1 {0-1 (47) Bacrot,E (2653)-Caruana,F (2766) Chess.com INT 2023} *

