1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 e6 4. O-O Nge7 5. c3 {This is the old mainline. The move is very logical. White immediately wants to create a strong centre, by means of d2-d4. The drawback of this move instead of 5.Re1 is that now the f1 square is not available for the bishop.} a6 $1 {We need to play immediately a6 to attack the bishop and to force him to go not optimal play} 6. Ba4 b5 7. Bc2 Bb7 {Now we are on a crossroad} 8. Re1 {Is natural and the strongest move} (8. d4 $6 {is an innacurate move} cxd4 9. cxd4 (9. Nxd4 {Is some strange kind of open sicilian} Ng6 $11 {[%cal Rf8e7]}) 9... Nb4 10. Nc3 Nxc2 11. Qxc2 Rc8 $15 {0-1 (24) Nitin,S (2381)-Jacobson,B (2491) Chess.com INT 2021}) (8. Qe2 d5 (8... Rc8 9. d4) 9. e5 d4 $1 10. Be4 (10. d3 {is a mistake because it leaves the c2-bishop passive} Ng6 $17) 10... Nd5 11. d3 dxc3 $1 12. bxc3 b4 $1 13. c4 Nb6 14. a3 a5 15. a4 Be7 {[%cal Rd8d7,Rh7h6,Re8h8] 0-1 (44) Fedorchuk,S (2648)-Moiseenko,A (2667) Riadh 2017}) 8... Ng6 9. d4 cxd4 10. cxd4 Rc8 (10... Nb4 $6 11. Bb3 {and the bishop is alive. The e4-pawn is protected}) 11. Nc3 (11. a3 Na5 12. Nbd2 Bd6 {Usually we develop the bishop on this square, keeping the pawn on d7.} 13. g3 O-O 14. h4 h6 15. Bd3 Bb8 16. h5 Ne7 17. Nh4 f5 18. exf5 Nxf5 {½-½ (111) So,W (2772)-Caruana,F (2791) Chess.com INT 2021}) 11... Na5 12. g3 (12. a3 Bd6 13. g3 O-O 14. h4 f5 15. h5 Ne7 $11) (12. Bd3 Bd6 13. g3 O-O 14. h4 h6 15. a3 Ne7 16. d5 Bb8 17. Bc2 Nc4 {½-½ (58) So,W (2772)-Caruana,F (2791) Chess.com INT 2021}) 12... Bb4 13. h4 h6 14. h5 Ne7 15. Qd3 Qc7 16. Bf4 Bd6 17. Bxd6 Qxd6 18. Rac1 Qb4 19. Nd1 f5 {0-1 (29) Grandelius,N (2660)-Yakubboev,N (2630) Chess.com INT 2023} *

