{The last two lectures are dedicated to the Accelerated Dragon. I find sidelines very easy to handle, but I can't decide which line to choose in the main line. So I leave this to the reader. My favourites are 8...Re8, 8...a5 and 8...d6 and I analyze them in great depth}  *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6.Nxc6"]
[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B34"]
[Annotator "GM Petar G. Arnaudov"]
[PlyCount "16"]
[Source "ChessBase"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 g6 5. Nc3 Bg7 6. Nxc6 {We will start with this move, which I believe is not dangerous for Black, but deserves attention.} bxc6 7. Bc4 {This is the main position of the variation. I analyzed three moves here: 7...Nf6 and 7...d6 and 7...Qc7. In my opinion, the latest is the best.} Qc7 $1 8. O-O Rb8 {This is Xiong's choice. You can find the analysis in the model game Shimanov-Xiong} (8... Nf6 {Played by Abdusattorov}) *

[Event "Titled Tue 22nd Nov Early"]
[Site "chess.com INT"]
[Date "2022.11.22"]
[Round "8"]
[White "Shimanov, A.."]
[Black "Xiong, Jeffery"]
[Result "0-1"]
[ECO "B34"]
[Annotator "GM Petar G. Arnaudov"]
[PlyCount "66"]
[EventDate "2022.11.22"]
[EventType "swiss"]
[EventRounds "11"]
[Source "ChessBase"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 g6 (2... Nc6 {Is our move order} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 g6 5. Nc3 Bg7) 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 (4. Qxd4 {Allowing this move is one of the drawbacks of this move order}) 4... Nc6 5. Nc3 Bg7 {[%csl Rd7][%cal Rd7d5]} 6. Nxc6 {This move doesn't make sense to me here. Usually this exchange makes sense, If White can proceed with e4-e5 later on. Nevertheless, GM Shimanov and other strong players use this line successfully, so it deserves attention.} bxc6 7. Bc4 Qc7 $1 {This is not the most popular move, but it is quite good. Black wastes some time, but stops e5 and prepares Nf6} (7... Nf6 {Even this is possible here, because Black has a nice tactical idea at his disposal. Still I think that White's position is preferable} 8. e5 Ng4 9. Qxg4 (9. Bxf7+ {Also seems promising for White} Kxf7 10. Qxg4 (10. e6+ Kxe6 11. Qxg4+ Kf7 12. Qf4+ Bf6 13. Ne4 $14) 10... Bxe5 11. Qf3+ Bf6 12. Ne4 $14) 9... d5 10. Qf3 dxc4 11. Qxc6+ Bd7 12. Qxc4 $14) (7... d6 {Is the most logical move, but I don't want to commit to d6 too early} 8. O-O Nf6 9. e5 $1 {Leading to double-edged endgame.} dxe5 10. Qxd8+ Kxd8 11. Re1 {[%cal Re1e5]} Bf5 $5 (11... e6 12. Rxe5 Nd5 13. Re2 $14 {1-0 (55) Van Foreest,J (2702)-Mamedov,R (2656) Warsaw 2021}) 12. Rxe5 Nd5 $11 {White's active pieces compensate for the slightly awkward position of the king.}) 8. O-O Rb8 (8... Nf6 {This looks natural to me and I believe it equalizes. Black is developing the kingside and is ready to start actions in the center or on the semi-open b-file} 9. Re1 d6 10. Bf4 Nd7 11. Qd2 Rb8 12. Bh6 O-O 13. Bxg7 Kxg7 14. b3 f6 $1 {[%cal Rd7e5,Re5f7] I like this idea to transfer the knight to f7. Black is also ready to met f4 with e7-e5.} (14... Nf6 $6 15. Rad1 Qa5 16. h3 $14 {1-0 (47) Shimanov,A (2581)-Abdusattorov,N (2661) Chess.com INT 2022}) 15. f4 e5 16. Rad1 (16. f5 {[%cal Rd7c5,Rd7b6]}) 16... exf4 17. Qxd6 Qxd6 18. Rxd6 Ne5) 9. Bb3 Nf6 {[%cal Rf1e1]} 10. Bg5 (10. Re1 {This leaves White without a clear plan after:} d6 11. Bf4 {[%cal Rf6g4,Rf6d7]} Nd7 {[%csl Rb3,Rb8][%cal Re8g8,Ra7a5]} 12. Qf3 O-O $11 {The position is equal, but I would prefer Black here. He can choose between different plans: Ne5, a5, even e6 followed by c5.}) 10... O-O (10... h6 {It makes sense to start with this move}) 11. Qd2 d6 12. Rfe1 (12. Bh6 {Is typically met by} Bxh6 $1 13. Qxh6 c5 $5 {[%cal Rc5c4] Black is the one fighting for an advantage here. White queen can create any serious threats alone on the kingside.}) 12... Re8 {The idea is to prepare Nd7-e5 maneuver} 13. Rad1 Nd7 {[%csl Re8] Standart maneuver for this position} 14. Qf4 Ne5 15. Qh4 a5 16. f4 $2 (16. Kh1 {This prophylactic move keeps the position in the equaility zone}) 16... Ng4 $1 {[%cal Rc7b6]} 17. f5 $2 (17. Kh1 {White can minimilize the damages by playing:} Qa7 18. Re2 h6 19. f5 hxg5 20. Qxg4 Bf6 $17) 17... Qa7+ $1 18. Kf1 Ba6+ $1 19. Ne2 Ne3+ 20. Bxe3 Qxe3 21. Qf2 Qxf2+ 22. Kxf2 Bxb2 23. Rb1 Be5 {Black is completely winning with an extra pawn and two powerful bishops} 24. Ng1 Bc3 25. Red1 Rb4 26. Nf3 a4 27. Bxf7+ Kxf7 28. Ng5+ Kg8 29. Rxb4 Bxb4 30. Ne6 Bc4 31. Rb1 Rb8 32. Kf3 Bxa2 33. Ra1 Bxe6 0-1

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7.Nxc6 bxc6 8.e5"]
[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B34"]
[Annotator "GM Petar G. Arnaudov"]
[PlyCount "30"]
[Source "ChessBase"]

{Now it is time to see the idea of Nxc6 in a more unpleasant situation. When our knight is already developed on f6, White can continue with e5.} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 g6 5. Nc3 Bg7 6. Be3 Nf6 7. Nxc6 $5 bxc6 8. e5 {Black is in a crossroad. He can choose between 8...Nd5 to sacrifice a pawn and the calm 8...Ng8} Nd5 {When I studied Accelerated Dragon 15 years ago, this move was considered the best (at least by me and some authors). Now, I find out that 8...Ng8 is more popular and less forced. Still 8...Nd5 is a serious alternative and it could fit your repertoire if you like sharp and complicated positions. The drawback is that you must remember several lines and still not equalize completely. White has forced draw in one variation. Nevertheless, if you are looking for sharp play and complication this is your way to go.} 9. Nxd5 cxd5 10. Qxd5 Rb8 {[%cal Rb8b2]} 11. O-O-O (11. Bxa7 {The materialistic approach is also possible, but I believe Black holds here after:} Rxb2 12. Bd4 Rxc2 {This is a well-known drawish line} (12... Rb8 $5 {Looks like a great choice to me. Black has a very nice tactical shot here after:} 13. Bc4 O-O 14. O-O Bb7 15. Qc5 d6 $1 {Forces a draw} (15... e6 {looks promising too, with the simple idea Qg5. This keeps the game alive} 16. Rfd1 Qg5 $11 {[%cal Rf8c8] It is equal, but White needs to be careful. All three results are possible.}) 16. exd6 exd6 17. Qa7 Bxg2 {Very nice move} 18. Kxg2 Ra8 19. Qb6 Qd7 {[%cal Rf8b8] The threat is Rfb8 to trap the queen and White can't avoid the perpetual after:} 20. Bxg7 Qg4+ 21. Kh1 Qf3+ $11) 13. Bd3 e6 14. Qa8 Rc6 15. O-O (15. Bb5 {This move is not very accurate, although it is possible.} Ra6 16. Bxa6 Qa5+ 17. Kf1 O-O $13 {Black has very serious compensation for the exchange. You can dig deeper if you are interested.}) 15... O-O 16. Bb5 Ba6 {This move forces a draw} 17. Qxd8 Rxd8 18. Bxc6 Bxf1 19. Kxf1 dxc6 20. Bc3 Rd3 $11 21. Rc1 Rd5 {It should be a draw, but probably Black is the one who should be careful} 22. Re1 Rc5 23. Bb4 Rc2 24. Re2 Rc1+ 25. Re1 Rc2 26. Re2 Rc1+ 27. Re1 Rc2 {½-½ (27) Cornette,M (2533)-Maze,S (2565) Nimes 2014}) (11. Bc4 {is definitely the main move by statistic, but it scores poorly.} O-O 12. O-O-O {this is far more ambitious than the simple 12.0-0, but also White is risking, because his king will be under attack.} (12. O-O $5 {Is a positional line, Black can equalize or almost equalize, but it seems pretty hard to play for a win.} Qc7 13. f4 (13. Bf4 {Is rare, but suggested by the engine. And even if I manage to find the right way for Black, White probably has some small practical chances.} Bb7 14. Qd4 d6 15. Rfe1 Rfd8 16. Bf1 dxe5 17. Bxe5 Qxc2 18. Qf4 Bxe5 19. Qxe5 e6 $11 {To be honest, I would prefer White here. He has two vs. one on the queenside and Black's king could be weak in the future.}) 13... d6 14. Bb3 (14. exd6 {Simply transposes to the main line after:} exd6 15. Bb3) 14... Be6 (14... dxe5 {Also leads to more or less equal endgame after:} 15. fxe5 Be6 16. Qc5 Qxc5 17. Bxc5 Bxe5 18. Bxe7 Rfc8 19. Bf6 Bxf6 20. Rxf6 Bxb3 21. cxb3 Rc2 $11) 15. exd6 exd6 16. Qd3 Bxb2 $11) 12... Qc7 $1 13. f4 (13. Bb3 a5 14. f4 d6 15. exd6 exd6 16. Qxd6 Qxd6 17. Rxd6 a4 18. Bxa4 Bxb2+ 19. Kd2 Bf5 $44 {Black definetely has compensation, but probably not enough}) (13. Qc5 Qxe5 14. Qxe5 Bxe5 15. c3 a5 16. Rhe1 $14) 13... d6 $1 14. Qd3 $2 (14. exd6 {is losing on a spot after:} Bxb2+ 15. Kb1 Be5+ 16. Bb3 Bxd6 $19) 14... dxe5 15. fxe5 Bf5 16. Qe2 Rfc8 17. Bd3 $4 {the final mistake which allows a beautiful finish} Qxe5 18. c3 Rxc3+ 19. bxc3 Qxc3+ 20. Qc2 Rb1+ {0-1 (20) Carvalho,A (2047)-Collas,D (2378) Lisbon 2001} 21. Kxb1 Qa1#) 11... Bb7 {The engines are optimistic here about White's chances, but it looks scared} 12. Qd4 (12. Qc5 O-O 13. c3 Rc8 14. Qxa7 Bc6 15. Qb6 Qe8 {The engine gives very big advantage for White here, but somehow it remains tricky in all the lines.} (15... Qxb6 $6 16. Bxb6 Bxe5 17. f3 {The pawn majority on the queenside looks scary}) 16. f4 (16. Bf4 {Is more accurate} Ra8 17. a3 Ra4 18. Rd4 Qa8 $44) 16... d6 17. Bd4 $2 {after this move White is just worse} Rb8 18. Qa6 Ra8 $17 {1-0 (41) Sevian,S (2660)-Taher,Y (2455) Lichess.org INT 2020}) (12. Qd2 $1 {Is a new idea, it seems that GM Moranda did his homework and scored a nice win} Bxe5 (12... O-O 13. Bd4 Qc7 14. f4 $14) 13. Bxa7 Ra8 14. Qe3 $1 Qc7 15. Bb6 Qb8 16. Kb1 Bf4 17. Qb3 O-O 18. Be3 (18. h4 $5 {Looks very scary for Black}) 18... Bxe3 19. Qxe3 Qc7 20. a3 e5 21. c4 Rfb8 {Definetely Black has compensation, but I can't say that it is enough  1-0 (48) Moranda,W (2623)-Plat,V (2548) Terme Catez 2021}) 12... O-O 13. Qxa7 (13. Qxd7 $2 Qa5 $17) 13... Bxe5 14. Bd4 Bf4+ 15. Kb1 d6 {with a standard compensation, as always in this line. Black is a pawn down, but has some hopes for the attack against White's king.} *

