1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 g6 3. d4 Bg7 4. Nc3 cxd4 5. Nxd4 Nc6 6. Nb3 Nf6 7. Be2 O-O 8. O-O d6 9. Re1 b6 {The setup we recommend for Black.} 10. Nd5 Bb7 (10... Nxe4 $4 11. Bb5 $18) 11. Bg5 {White puts pressure on f6 to provoke Nxd5. If this happens, he intends to exploit the weakness of e7.} (11. Nxf6+ {This simplification does not cause the second player any inconvenience.} Bxf6 12. c3 Bg7 13. Bf1 Rc8 14. Bg5 Re8 15. Qd2 Qd7 16. a4 Ne5 17. Bb5 Bc6 18. Bxc6 Rxc6 19. Qe2 Nc4 {Black has completely equalized. 0-1 (25) Zagrebelny,S (2490) -Tolnai,T (2500)/Budapest 1993}) 11... e6 $1 {This is not forced, but we find it very interesting if Black seeks to play a positional Sicilian game.} 12. Nxf6+ Bxf6 13. Bxf6 Qxf6 14. c3 ({Capturing the pawn is a mistake.} 14. Qxd6 $2 Qxb2 15. Qc7 Rab8 $17 {[%cal Gf8c8]}) 14... Rfd8 $1 {[%cal Gd6d5,Ga8c8]} 15. Qc1 (15. Qd2 d5 $1 {The typical and correct central blow.} 16. exd5 Rxd5 17. Qe3 Rad8 {Black came out of the opening with a satisfactory position.}) 15... g5 $5 {An ambitious plan by the Russian player, demonstrating the wealth of this variation. His idea is to get strong control of the dark squares.} ({Objectively the best answer is} 15... d5 $1 16. exd5 Rxd5 17. Bf3 Rd7 {, and Black has an excellent position.}) 16. Qe3 Ne5 17. Rad1 Qf4 $5 18. Qxf4 $1 ({More passive is} 18. Bf1 Qxe3 19. Rxe3 Kg7 20. Re2 Kf6 21. f3 $8 ({An error is} 21. Red2 $2 Bxe4 22. Rxd6 Rxd6 23. Rxd6 Bd5 $19 {[%cal Gf6e7]}) 21... Ba6 22. Red2 Bxf1 23. Kxf1 Nc4 24. Re2 Rac8 $13 {We are faced with a typical Sicilian endgame. Black has a good position due to his control over the dark squares and is the only one who can improve his position.}) 18... gxf4 19. f3 h5 20. Kf2 ({More accurate was} 20. g3 $1 Ng6 $1 21. Rd2 (21. Kf2 h4 22. gxf4 Nxf4 23. Bf1 Kg7 24. Ke3 e5 {, and Black has a plus going for him.}) 21... Kf8 $1 22. Kf2 h4 23. gxf4 (23. Nd4 fxg3+ 24. hxg3 hxg3+ 25. Kxg3 Ke7 $15 {[%csl Gg8,Gh8][%cal Gd8h8,Ga8g8] Making progress on the kingside.}) 23... Nxf4 24. Nd4 d5 25. Red1 dxe4 26. fxe4 Ke7 {The black position is slightly preferable.}) 20... h4 $5 {Trying to fix the white structure on the kingside before executing the d6-d5 break.} 21. Rd4 {White's waiting approach turns out to be too passive.} ({It was necessary to play} 21. g3 $1 fxg3+ 22. hxg3 hxg3+ 23. Kxg3 Ng6 24. Nd4 (24. Kf2 $6 Kf8 25. Ke3 Ke7 26. Rh1 (26. f4 $2 Nh4 27. Rg1 Rg8 $17 {[%csl Re4,Rf4] The white central pawns are weak.}) 26... Rh8 27. Nd4 d5 28. exd5 Bxd5 {White is somewhat worse, but the position is defensible.}) 24... Kf8 25. Rh1 Ke7 $13) 21... Kf8 22. Bf1 Ke7 23. Red1 ({It is too late for any kingside attempts.} 23. g3 $2 fxg3+ 24. hxg3 hxg3+ 25. Kxg3 Rh8 $17) 23... Rac8 24. Ra4 ({Again,} 24. g3 $2 {does not work:} fxg3+ 25. hxg3 hxg3+ 26. Kxg3 Rh8 $19) 24... a5 25. Rad4 d5 $1 $17 {Black executes this blow immediately, transforming the pawn structure. Now the question is which of the majorities is more dangerous.} 26. exd5 Rxd5 27. Re1 Ng6 28. Ba6 Rxd4 29. Bxb7 Rdd8 30. Bxc8 Rxc8 31. Re4 f5 32. Rd4 e5 $1 {The kind of position Motylev was aiming for. A dynamic central majority with great influence over the board versus a passive majority on the queenside.} 33. Rd5 Ke6 34. Rb5 Rc6 35. c4 Nf8 $1 {Rerouting the knight to a central position.} 36. Nd2 (36. c5 $6 a4 $1 37. Nd2 bxc5 38. Nc4 e4 $19) 36... Nd7 37. Rd5 Rd6 $5 ({More precise was} 37... Nc5 $1 38. Rd8 Rd6 39. Rxd6+ (39. Re8+ Kf7 $19) 39... Kxd6 $19 {[%cal Gc5a4,Ga4c3] , and Black is winning.}) 38. Rxd6+ Kxd6 39. Ke2 Nc5 40. Nb1 e4 41. Nc3 Ke5 42. b3 (42. Nd5 {doesn't work either.} Ne6 $1 43. Nxb6 (43. h3 b5 44. Ne7 bxc4 45. Ng6+ Kf6 $19) 43... Nd4+ 44. Kf2 e3+ 45. Ke1 h3 $1 $19) 42... Ne6 $2 ({The Russian player would have finished off an excellent game by playing first} 42... h3 $1 43. gxh3 Ne6 $19) 43. h3 $1 Nd4+ 44. Kf2 Nc2 45. Na4 Kd4 46. Ke2 Nb4 47. a3 Nd3 48. b4 $1 (48. Nxb6 Nc1+ 49. Kd1 Nxb3 $19) 48... Nxb4 {The only attempt to make progress.} (48... axb4 49. axb4 Nxb4 50. Nxb6 Kc5 51. Nd7+ Kxc4 52. Ne5+ Kd4 53. Ng6 $11) 49. axb4 axb4 50. Nxb6 b3 51. Na4 Kxc4 52. Kd2 $4 {A serious error.} ({White would have reached the draw after} 52. fxe4 $1 fxe4 53. Kd2 e3+ 54. Kc1 {The variations are long but forced.} Kb4 (54... Kd3 55. Kd1 $11) 55. Nb2 Ka3 (55... Kc3 56. Na4+ Kd4 57. Kd1 Kd3 58. Nb2+ Kc3 59. Na4+ Kb4 60. Nb2 Ka3 61. Kc1 e2 62. Nd3 b2+ 63. Kb1 Kb3 64. Ne1 Kc3 65. Nf3 Kd3 66. Kxb2 Ke3 67. Kc3 Kf2 $11) 56. Nd3 (56. Kb1 $4 e2 $1 57. Nd3 b2 58. Ne1 Kb3 59. Nf3 Kc3 $19 {Zugzwang.}) 56... Ka2 57. Nb4+ Ka1 58. Nd3 Ka2 $11) 52... e3+ 53. Kc1 Kb4 54. Nb2 Ka3 $4 {Again, allowing White to reach the draw.} (54... Kc3 $1 {guaranteed an easy victory.} 55. Nd1+ Kd3 56. Nb2+ Ke2 $19) 55. Kb1 $4 {White returns the favor.} (55. Nd3 $1 $11 Ka2 56. Nb4+ Ka1 57. Nd3 $11) 55... e2 $1 56. Nd3 b2 57. Ne1 Kb3 58. Nc2 Kc3 59. Ne1 Kd2 0-1

