1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 g6 4. d4 cxd4 5. Nxd4 Bg7 6. Be3 Nf6 7. Bc4 O-O 8. Bb3 Re8 {Entering the variation popularized by Dubov himself.} 9. O-O {Alternatives are 9.f4, 9.f3 and 9.Nxc6. They are all analyzed in Chapter VII.} d6 10. h3 Na5 11. Qe2 a6 12. Rad1 Qc7 13. Bg5 {With the idea of damaging Black's pawn structure after 14.Bxf6 and 15.Nd5.} ({The direct} 13. Nd5 {also has to be taken into account.} Nxd5 14. exd5 b5 15. Rfe1 Nxb3 16. axb3 b4 $1 {This is necessary to prevent White's consolidation with c4.} (16... Bb7 $2 17. c4 {White manages to defend his center well and restrict Black's counterplay.}) 17. Nc6 (17. Qc4 $2 Qxc4 18. bxc4 Bd7 19. b3 a5 $15 {[%cal Ga5a4]}) 17... a5 $1 18. Bg5 e6 $1 $13 {The game is unclear, with chances for both players.}) 13... Qc5 14. Be3 Qc7 15. Rfe1 {The Turkish player decides to play to win. However, Black has neutralized the Nd5 plan and has comfortable play.} b5 16. Nd5 Nxd5 17. Bxd5 $6 ({More interesting for White was} 17. exd5 $5 Nxb3 18. axb3 b4 $1 {, with ideas similar to the variation analyzed above.} 19. Nc6 a5 20. Bg5 e6 $13) 17... Bb7 18. b3 Rac8 19. Qd2 e6 $1 20. Bxb7 Nxb7 {Now Dubov has an excellent Sicilian. He has possibilities in the centre and on the queenside. At the same time, there is no clear plan for White.} 21. Bh6 Bh8 ({Black misses the strong opportunity} 21... e5 $1 22. Bxg7 Kxg7 23. Nf5+ $8 (23. Ne2 $2 Qxc2 {White is at a disadvantage and without any practical chance.}) 23... gxf5 24. Qg5+ Kf8 25. exf5 {Perhaps Dubov calculated the variation with the knight sacrifice on f5 and did not like this position, although objectively it is the best choice for him.} f6 $1 {The decisive move to gain an advantage.} (25... Nc5 $2 26. Qh6+ (26. f6 $4 Ne6 27. Qh6+ Kg8 28. Rd3 Kh8 $19) 26... Ke7 27. Rxe5+ $1 dxe5 28. Qg5+ Kf8 (28... f6 $2 29. Qg7#) 29. Qh6+ $11) 26. Qxf6+ Qf7 27. Qh8+ Ke7 28. Rxe5+ $1 Kd7 $1 $17 (28... dxe5 $2 29. Qxe5+ Kf8 30. Qh8+ $11)) 22. Re2 Qc3 $1 23. Qxc3 Rxc3 24. Nf3 Rec8 25. Ne1 $2 (25. e5 $5 {This blow is not enough to equalize, but it was White's best practical chance.} d5 $1 (25... dxe5 $2 26. Nxe5 Rxc2 27. Rxc2 Rxc2 28. Nxf7 {White manages to complicate the game in his favour.} Kxf7 29. Rd7+ Ke8 30. Rxb7 Bd4 31. Be3 $11) 26. Nd4 Bg7 27. Bd2 (27. Bxg7 $1 Kxg7 28. Kf1 Nd8 29. Rd3 R3c7 30. Ke1 (30. f4 Nc6 $15) 30... Nc6 31. Nxc6 Rxc6 32. Kd1 $15 {White has a passive position, but chances to survive the endgame.}) 27... R3c7 28. f4 Bf8 29. Be3 Nc5 $17 {[%cal Gc5e4,Ge4c3]}) 25... R3c6 26. Kf1 a5 27. Be3 Bc3 28. Bd2 Kf8 29. Bxc3 Rxc3 30. h4 Ke7 31. Rd3 R3c6 {Black has no exploitable weaknesses and can dedicate himself to slow and steady progress.} 32. Rdd2 Nc5 33. Nd3 f5 $1 $17 {This central transformation increases Black's advantage.} 34. Nxc5 {The other options are worse.} (34. f3 $6 fxe4 35. fxe4 e5 $17) (34. exf5 $2 gxf5 35. Nf4 Ne4 $19) 34... Rxc5 35. exf5 (35. f3 {didn't help either:} fxe4 36. fxe4 b4 37. Ke1 h5 38. Kd1 Rf8 {[%cal Gf8f4]} 39. Kc1 Rf4 40. g3 Rf3 41. Rg2 Re5 42. Rde2 g5 $19) 35... gxf5 36. Ke1 e5 {This is what Black had been aiming for. A typical Sicilian endgame with active versus passive rooks.} 37. Kd1 Ke6 38. Rd3 Rg8 39. g3 b4 $1 {Dubov further improves his structure before pushing his central pawns.} 40. Rde3 h5 $1 41. a3 e4 42. axb4 axb4 43. Rd3 Ke5 44. Kc1 (44. f4+ Ke6 $19) 44... d5 $19 {The game is decided. Impeccable technique by the Russian player.} 45. Kb2 d4 46. Rd1 Ra8 47. Rb1 Rca5 48. Kc1 Ra1 49. Re1 Rxb1+ 50. Kxb1 f4 51. gxf4+ Kxf4 52. Rd1 Ke5 53. Rg1 Rf8 54. Rg2 e3 55. fxe3 dxe3 56. Rg7 Rf1+ 57. Kb2 Kf6 58. Rg2 Kf5 0-1

