1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 g6 5. Nc3 Bg7 6. Be3 Nf6 7. Nxc6 bxc6 8. e5 Ng8 {It is time to check the main move in this position - 8...Ng8. Black obviously loses some time, but on the other hand, he gains a tempo by attacking the pawn on e5. White is somehow overextended and now Black can attack this pawn with Qa5 or simply by playing d6 in many lines.} 9. Bd4 {Is the modern way of handling the position. We can easily go wrong here. Black has a variety of options. My preferences are for 9...Qa5 or 9...f6} (9. f4 {is the old main line which doesn't pose any serious problems for Black} Nh6 10. Qd2 (10. Bd3 Rb8 $15) (10. Bc4 O-O 11. O-O d6 $15) (10. Qf3 O-O 11. Bc4 d6 12. O-O-O Rb8 (12... Bg4 {Lorenzini gives this line and proves that Black is OK, but the simple Rb8 also works very well.}) 13. Qxc6 Bb7 14. Qa4 Nf5 15. Bf2 Qc8 {and again Black has a wonderful position.}) 10... O-O 11. O-O-O (11. h3 {Is tricky, but Black has a wonderful resource here.} Nf5 12. Bf2 c5 $1 {with the idea to go Nd4 after g2-g4} 13. O-O-O (13. Bxc5 $2 d6 $1 $15) 13... d6 14. exd6 (14. Bxc5 Bb7 $15) 14... exd6 15. Nd5 Be6 16. Bc4 Nd4 17. c3 Nc6 $15 {[%cal Rc6a5,Ra8b8]}) (11. Bc4 d6 12. O-O-O Nf5 13. Bf2 h5 $15 {[%cal Rd8c7,Ra8b8]}) 11... d6 12. exd6 Nf5 $1 (12... exd6 13. Qxd6 (13. Bd4 {Could be slightly unpleasant for Black}) 13... Qxd6 14. Rxd6 Nf5 15. Rd3 Ba6 16. Bc5 Bxd3 17. Bxf8 Bxf1 18. Bxg7 Bxg2 19. Rg1 Kxg7 {Kasparov manages to win this endgame 0-1 (39) Comp Fritz 2-Kasparov,G (2780) Cologne 1992}) 13. Bf2 Rb8 14. Bxa7 (14. b3 Be6 $11 15. g4 Nxd6 16. f5 Bd5) (14. dxe7 Qxe7 {[%cal Rc8e6,Re7b4,Rb8b2]}) (14. d7 Bxd7 15. Qxd7 Qa5 16. Bc4 Rxb2 17. Rd3 Bxc3 18. Qxa7 {with a double-edged position, in which Black's chances seems to be higher.}) 14... Rxb2 $1 15. Kxb2 Qa5 16. dxe7 Qb4+ 17. Kc1 Qa3+ 18. Kb1 Qxe7 $17) 9... Qa5 {this is my recommendation. The drawback of this move is that White can play e6, but as we will see it is not that dangerous.} (9... c5 $6 {leads to a pleasant position for White after:} 10. Bxc5 Qc7 (10... Bxe5 $6 {This seems impossible here. White is better after:} 11. Qd5 Bxc3+ 12. bxc3 $16) 11. Bd4 Bxe5 12. f4 Bxd4 13. Qxd4 $14) (9... Nh6 {Is another line which didn't equalize} 10. e6 $1 O-O (10... f6 11. exd7+ $14) 11. Bxg7 Kxg7 12. Qd4+ f6 13. exd7 Qxd7 14. Qxd7 Bxd7 15. O-O-O Rfd8 16. Ba6 $16 {1-0 (53) Sindarov,J (2609)-Salem,A (2690) Sharjah 2022}) (9... f6 10. f4 (10. exf6 $6 {this is always very good for Black. Even though we have three pawn islands, Black's centre is very strong.} Nxf6 11. Bc4 d5 12. Bb3 O-O {0-1 (65) Sychev,K (2510)-Antipov,M (2588) Moscow 2017} 13. O-O e6 $11 {[%cal Rf6h5]}) 10... Qa5 11. Qd2 fxe5 12. fxe5 c5 (12... Bxe5 13. O-O-O $44 {½-½ (33) Samusenko,M (2445)-Tiviakov,S (2613) Pavlodar 2019}) 13. Be3 Bxe5 14. Bc4 {White has long-term compensation for the pawn  ½-½ (36) Kasparov,G (2838)-Ivanchuk,V (2711) Prague 2002}) 10. e6 {Is the main line, but I can't see problems for Black here.} (10. f4 {is well met by} Rb8 11. Qd2 f6 12. Bc4 fxe5 13. fxe5 Rxb2 14. Ne4 Qxd2+ 15. Kxd2 Rb6 $13 {[%cal Rg8h6,Rd7d5]}) (10. Bc4 {Is an interesting gambit, but White seems to be better.} Bxe5 11. O-O f6 $1 12. Re1 Nh6 13. a3 Nf5 14. Bxe5 fxe5 15. b4 Qc7 {White still keeps some compensation, but not enough 0-1 (42) Atabayev,S (2461)-Guseinov,G (2636) Chess.com INT 2023}) 10... Nf6 11. exf7+ (11. exd7+ {This doesn't seem critical at all. I think that White is the one who is fighting for an advantage.} Bxd7 {[%cal Rd7g4,Ra8d8] The position looks very promising we are threatening Bg4 followed by Rd8} 12. Qe2 (12. Bc4 Bg4 $1 13. f3 Rd8 $1 14. fxg4 c5 15. O-O cxd4 16. Nb5 O-O 17. Qe1 Qb6 $19 {0-1 (40) Nadj Hedjesi,B (2432)-Atakisi,U (2409) Novi Sad 2009}) 12... O-O 13. O-O-O Be6 14. Qe5 Bd5 {Black can still fight for an advantage after this move} (14... Qxe5 $11 {is just equal: 0-1 (49) Kopylov,D (2344)-Mendonca,L (2557) Paleochora 2021}) 15. Qxe7 Bxa2 16. b3 (16. Bxf6 $4 Bh6+ $19 {is the point of Black's play}) 16... Bxb3 17. cxb3 Nd5 18. Qc5 Qxc5 19. Bxc5 Nxc3 $15) 11... Kxf7 {Black loses the right to castle, but the king is very safe on "f7" and the rook can join the game quickly.} 12. Bc4+ (12. f4 {Looks logical, but Black is much better after:} Rb8 13. b3 (13. Bc4+ d5 14. Bb3 Bg4 (14... Rd8 $1 {looks very strong as well}) 15. Qd3 (15. Qd2 $2 Ne4 16. Nxe4 Qxd2+ 17. Nxd2 Bxd4 $17) 15... Rhd8 $17) 13... Ne4 $19) 12... d5 13. Bb3 e5 $1 (13... Ba6 {is also possible and GM Georgiev won a beautiful game after:} 14. Qd2 e5 15. Bxe5 Rhe8 16. f4 Bh6 17. Qd4 Ng4 18. h3 Nxe5 19. fxe5 Rxe5+ 20. Qxe5 Re8 21. Qxe8+ Kxe8 $19 {0-1 (26) Marholev,D (2407)-Georgiev,K (2651) Plovdiv 2003}) 14. Bxe5 Re8 15. f4 Ng4 (15... Qb6 $5 $19 {[%cal Rc8g4,Rc8a6,Rg7h6,Rf6g4]}) 16. O-O Qc5+ 17. Kh1 Ne3 18. Ne4 Qb4 19. Nd6+ Qxd6 20. Bxd6 Nxd1 {0-1 (26) Madaminov,M (2260)-Savchenko,B (2535) Chess.com INT 2021} *

