1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 g6 5. Nc3 Bg7 6. Nde2 (6. Be3 {If White wants to play with g3, then Be3 is not useful} Nf6 7. g3 O-O 8. Bg2 d6 {[%cal Rf6g4]} 9. h3 Bd7 10. O-O Ne5 11. Nde2 Nc4 $1 (11... b5 {0-1 (35) Malakhov,V (2715)-Naiditsch,A (2685) Sibenik 2009}) 12. Bc1 b5 $11) 6... Nf6 7. g3 d6 {Still, I prefer this natural move over the immediate 7...b5, but it is a matter of taste.} (7... b5 $5 {Black manages to push b7-b5 in one move} 8. Bg2 Rb8 {This move is a prophylactic against e4-e5. We are not in a hurry to advance b5-b4} 9. O-O O-O 10. a3 {Is very slow; it prevents b5-b4 for now, but Black can prepare it, by means of a7-a5.} (10. Nd5 d6 11. Bg5 Nxd5 ({The typical} 11... Nd7 {[%cal Rh7h6,Re7e6,Rd7e5] is possible here too, but I want to show you another plan}) 12. exd5 Ne5 13. Nd4 (13. b3 {is very well met by} Bh3 $1 14. c3 Bxg2 15. Kxg2 Qd7 {[%cal Rd7b7]}) 13... Bd7 (13... Bg4 {It makes sense to try to provoke f2-f3}) 14. b3 h6 $11 {½-½ (68) Tomczak,J (2605)-Li,C (2683) Chess.com INT 2020}) (10. h3 {Here I like the simple plan of advancing the queenside pawns.} a5 11. a3 d6 12. Be3 b4 13. axb4 axb4 14. Nd5 Nd7 $1 {Standart idea in this position} 15. Ra2 e6 16. Ndf4 Qc7 {[%cal Rd7c5,Rf8d8] Black is doing very well here. The pawn on b4 is very well placed, stopping White's pawns from advancing. The d6-pawn is not weak because it is very easy to defend it. Also the g2-bishop is kind of passive.}) 10... d6 11. Nd5 (11. h3 Nd7 12. Nd5 e6 (12... a5 $1 $15 {it is better to start with this move. Now I can't find equality for White}) 13. Nb4 Nde5 $6 (13... Nce5 $1 14. Qxd6 a5 15. Na2 (15. Nd3 Rb6 16. Qd4 Nf3+ 17. Bxf3 Bxd4 18. Nxd4 Qf6 $19) 15... Nc4 16. Qd3 Nxb2 $17) 14. f4 Qb6+ 15. Kh2 $11 {0-1 (64) Bartel,M (2648)-Vidit,S (2726) Chess.com INT 2020}) 11... a5 12. Ra2 b4 $15) 8. Bg2 Bd7 $1 {I quite like this new and aggressive approach. Black's idea is to keep the king in the center for a while and to proceed Qc8 and Bh3 quickly or to play quickly h7-h5.} 9. O-O Qc8 {[%cal Rd7h3] The idea is to make this move before White can play h2-h3.} (9... h5 $5 {This is very aggressive but quite good. I found just a few games in my database. Black wants to continue with h5-h4 and to open the h-file. If this happens, then White's king will be in serious trouble, so White can't allow this. He has two ways to proceed: 1: To play h2-h4 2: To play h2-h3} 10. h3 {seems better to me} (10. h4 {weakens the "g4" square a lot} Ne5 {It is very hard to suggest a good plan for White here.} 11. b3 b5 12. Nd4 b4 13. Nd5 Nxd5 14. exd5 Qb6 {Black has a very big advantage. The queenside is fixed; the d5-pawn could be weak in the future.} 15. Bb2 O-O 16. Qd2 Rac8 17. Kh1 Rc5 18. a3 a5 $15 {[%cal Rf8c8,Re5g4] Black is the one who has the initiative ½-½ (56) Tari,A (2630)-Cheparinov,I (2670) Douglas 2019}) 10... Qc8 11. Kh2 Ne5 12. f4 $2 {doesn't work here} (12. Nf4 $5 {The knight is heading to "d5", but Black can start his typical counterplay on the queenside.} b5 13. Ncd5 Nxd5 14. Nxd5 h4 {Black took the initiative, but the game soon ended in a draw ½-½ (18) Spasov,V (2495)-Petrov,M (2525) Primorsko 2020}) 12... Neg4+ 13. Kg1 (13. Kh1 h4 $17 {Black has serious attacking chances}) 13... Qc5+ 14. Qd4 Qxd4+ 15. Nxd4 Nxe4 $17) 10. Nf4 (10. Nd5 {Is logical because Black doesn't have the typical Nd7, but he can try another plan.} Nxd5 11. exd5 Ne5 12. c3 O-O (12... Bh3 {White's g2-bishop is passive, but without him, the complex of the light squares will be very weak. Also, the d5-pawn becomes a target.} 13. Nf4 Bxg2 14. Kxg2 O-O 15. Re1 Qc4 {Exchanging the queens is in Black's favour. As in many Sicilians, we have our counterplay on the semi-open c-file. 0-1 (59) Dardha,D (2516)-Mamedov,R (2654) Europe Echecs INT 2021}) 13. Nd4 Bg4 $1 14. Qc2 Bh3 15. Bxh3 Qxh3 16. f4 Nc4 {½-½ (56) Quparadze,G (2538)-Yu,Y (2743) Almaty 2022}) (10. Re1 {White is ready to answer Bh3 with Bh1, but we have another idea. We can use that the rook is still on h8 and to advance the h-pawn.} h5 11. Bg5 Nh7 12. Be3 h4 13. Qc1 hxg3 14. hxg3 Nf6 {With an open h-file, White's king is very weak. The game ended after:} 15. Nd5 Bh3 16. Nxf6+ Bxf6 {[%cal Rh3g2,Rc8h3] Crushing win for Black, which shows the danger of White's position. 0-1 (21) Le Hetet,N (2393)-Grandelius,N (2670) Chalons en Champagne 2021}) 10... h5 {again we see this h5 plan. It is always quite annoying} 11. h4 Ng4 12. Ncd5 O-O 13. c3 b5 14. a4 {This move is not very logical against Bd7} bxa4 15. Rxa4 e6 16. Ne3 Nce5 17. Ra2 Rd8 {There is no need to spend a tempo protecting this pawn.} (17... Bb5 $1 18. Re1 a5 19. Qxd6 a4 {and White is paralyzed}) 18. Nxg4 (18. Qxd6 Bb5) 18... Nxg4 19. Qe2 Qb7 {[%cal Rd7c6]} 20. Rd1 Bb5 {provoking c4, which weakens the structure on the queenside even more} 21. c4 Bc6 22. Rd3 a5 23. Rda3 a4 24. Nd3 Bd4 25. Bf4 e5 26. Bg5 f6 27. Bd2 f5 $19 {powerful play by Erigaisi} 28. Nb4 Bxf2+ 29. Kh1 Bxe4 $19 30. Nd5 Bc5 31. Bxe4 fxe4 32. Rxa4 Rxa4 33. Rxa4 Qxb2 34. Ne7+ Kh7 35. Nxg6 Qd4 36. Qf1 Nf2+ 37. Kg2 Qxd2 {0-1 (37) Gukesh,D (2725)-Erigaisi,A (2722) Kolkata 2022} *

