1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 g6 5. Nc3 Bg7 6. Nb3 {If White wants to play with Nb3 and g3, he can do it with this move order. This plan is not very dangerous. There are various systems, but I suggest you the simplest one. We just develop the kingside and then play Bg4 "with the idea to provoke f3" followed by Be6} Nf6 7. g3 (7. Be2) ({and} 7. Be3 {are analyzed with different move order}) 7... O-O 8. Bg2 d6 9. O-O Bg4 (9... a5 10. a4 Bg4 11. f3 Be6 {[%cal Rc6b4,Ra8c8]} 12. Be3 Rc8 {[%cal Rc6e5,Re5c4,Rf6d7]}) 10. f3 Be6 11. Nd5 a5 {Is one possible way to continue and the most logical one. Usually, when you see a knight on b3, the first thought should be to kick it by means of a5-a4.} (11... Rc8 {I like this standard approach as well. Black's position looks very promising} 12. c3 Na5 (12... Ne5 {[%cal Rb7b5,Rf6d5,Re4d5,Re6f5] I would prefer this move}) 13. h3 Bxd5 14. exd5 Nc4 15. Re1 a5 16. f4 (16. a4) 16... a4 $17) 12. a4 {Allowing a5-a4 is just too much and Black will be much better.} Nb4 13. Ne3 Bxb3 $1 14. cxb3 e6 {[%cal Rf6d7,Rd7c5] Very nice move, Black restricts the knights and prepares d6-d5} 15. g4 Nd7 (15... d5 $5) 16. Qe2 (16. Qxd6 Ra6 17. Qd1 Nc5 {and Black's queenside is falling apart}) 16... Nc5 17. Bd2 Nxb3 18. Rad1 Nd4 19. Qf2 Nd3 {0-1 (20) Shirazi,K (2279)-Le Roux,J (2509) Chartres 2023} *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
