[PlyCount "58"]
[Source "ChessBase"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 g6 5. Nc3 Bg7 6. Be3 Nf6 7. Be2 O-O 8. f4 d6 9. O-O {This position is important for the variation theory. Black is perfectly fine here but needs to know how to play.} Qb6 $1 {This move equalizes immediately} ({The alternatives are:} 9... Nxd4) (9... Bd7) 10. Qd3 {The only good move} (10. e5 $6 {not the best, the position remains complicated} dxe5 11. fxe5 Nxe5 12. Nf5 Qxb2 13. Nxe7+ Kh8 14. Bd4 Qb4 $1 15. Bxe5 Qxe7 16. Qd4 Nh5 17. Bxg7+ Nxg7 $15 {everything so far seems to be forced. I can't see full compensation for the sacrificing pawn. 1-0 (40) Olszewski,M (2548)-Duda,J (2645) Germany 2015}) (10. Nf5 $4 {loses on a spot} Qxb2 11. Nxg7 (11. Na4 {doesn't help either} Qa3 12. c3 Nxe4 $1 13. Bc1 Nxc3 $19) 11... Qxc3) (10. Qd2 $2 Nxe4 $1 {standart tactic for this position which you need to remember} 11. Nxe4 Bxd4 $17) (10. Na4 {This move looks playable, but it looks like a draw offer} Qa5 {there is nothing better than} (10... Qc7 {Of course, Black is not forced to repeat the moves} 11. Nc3 a6) 11. Nc3) 10... Ng4 $1 {continuing the forced play} 11. Bxg4 (11. Nd5 {leads to very interesting complications.} Bxd4 12. Nxb6 $6 (12. Bxg4 $1 Bxe3+ 13. Qxe3 Qxe3+ 14. Nxe3 Bxg4 15. Nxg4 Rfc8 {White should hold this, but as always, those endgames are slightly better for Black. He can play on the queenside and on the semi-open c-file. 0-1 (69) Fieberg,S (2159)-Kololli,K (2130) Willingen 2016}) 12... Bxe3+ 13. Kh1 Bxb6 14. Bxg4 Bxg4 15. f5 {the only active try for White} Bh5 (15... gxf5 16. exf5) 16. h3 (16. a4 Ne5 $17 {0-1 (41) Olofsson,D (2535)-Isaev,A (2444) ICCF email 2007}) 16... gxf5 17. exf5 (17. Qg3+ Kh8 18. Qh4 Be2 19. Rfe1 Ba6 20. exf5 f6 $17) 17... f6 $17 {Black's three pieces are much stronger than White's queen. Soon the knight will land on e5 and the rook will be doubled on the g-file}) 11... Bxd4 12. Bxd4 Qxd4+ 13. Qxd4 Nxd4 14. Bd1 $11 {The endgame is about equal} (14. Bxc8 $6 {I believe ,Black's chances are slightly preferable here. The c2-pawn is a weakness. Black's rook has a wonderful square on "c4" with the idea to double the rooks and advance the pawns on the queenside.} Rfxc8 15. Rf2 Kf8 16. Rd1 Rc4 17. Rfd2 Nc6 18. Re1 Rc8 19. Nd5 e6 20. Nc3 Nd4 21. Red1 e5 22. Rf1 Rb4 $17 {0-1 (53) Schaefer,M (2411)-Lobzhanidze,D (2470) Dresden 2007}) 14... Be6 15. Nd5 Bxd5 16. exd5 h5 17. Re1 Nf5 18. c3 Kg7 19. Re4 Rfc8 {Again I would choose Black. The f5-knight is definitely not weaker than White's bishop. Black has a c-file and the d5-pawn can be a weakness} 20. Bb3 a5 21. Rd1 b5 22. a3 Rc7 23. g3 Nh6 24. Rde1 Ng8 25. h3 f5 26. Rd4 Nf6 27. Bd1 Rb8 28. Bf3 Kf7 29. Re3 Rc4 $17 {Abasov plays wonderfully so far and gets a significant advantage, but suddenly offers a draw ½-½ (29) Kryvoruchko,Y (2683)-Abasov,N (2655) Germany 2019} *

