1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 g6 5. Nc3 Bg7 6. Nb3 {Here, we will see another plan connected with Nb3 following with Be2} Nf6 7. Be2 O-O 8. O-O d6 9. f4 (9. Bg5 Be6 10. f4 (10. Kh1 {transposes to 9.Kh1}) (10. Re1 Rc8 11. Bf1 h6 12. Bf4 d5 13. exd5 Nxd5 14. Nxd5 Bxd5 15. c3 e5 {0-1 (52) Andriasian,Z (2585)-Nakamura,H (2781) Chess.com INT 2018}) (10. Qd2 {Doesn't pose any problems, because Black can proceed with his standart plan: Rc8-b5, Ne5-c4} Rc8 11. Rad1 a6 {[%cal Rb7b5,Rc6e5]}) 10... b5 11. a3 a5 12. Bf3 a4 13. Nc1 Nd7 14. Nd3 Nc5 {0-1 (37) Morozevich,A (2774)-Ivanchuk,V (2740) Dagomys 2008}) (9. Re1 {this move is very popular, but I quite like Black's position here} Be6 {White can't stop d6-d5 on the next move} (9... b6 {[%cal Rc8b7] Is another approach}) 10. Bf1 (10. Nd5 {is not possible, because the pawn is hanging} Nxe4 $17) (10. Bg5 {doesn't stop the d5 advance} d5 11. Bxf6 (11. exd5 Nxd5 12. Nxd5 Bxd5 13. c3 Qd6 $11) 11... Bxf6 12. exd5 Bxc3 13. bxc3 Bxd5 $15) 10... d5 $1 {In my opinion, this move at least equalizes} 11. Nc5 (11. exd5 Nxd5 12. Ne4 Ndb4 13. Qe2 $2 (13. c3 $11) 13... Bxb3 14. Rd1 (14. axb3 Nd4 $19) 14... Bd5 15. a3 Nxc2 16. Qxc2 Bxe4 {0-1 (16) Sindarov,J (2661)-Vakhidov,J (2607) Astana 2023}) 11... dxe4 12. Nxe6 fxe6 13. Bc4 (13. Qxd8 Raxd8 14. Bg5 Nd4 15. Rac1 Rc8 16. Red1 Nf5 {½-½ (56) Onischuk,V (2483)-Khalifman,A (2627) St Petersburg 2011}) 13... Qb6 {With queens on the board, White's task is even harder} 14. Bxe6+ Kh8 15. Bb3 Rad8 $17 {0-1 (37) Cyfka,K (2369)-Cernousek,L (2420) Frydek Mistek 2012}) (9. Kh1 {Is another decent try for White. I suggest that we continue in the same fashion. Playing Be6 with the idea to play d5 next} Be6 10. Bg5 (10. f4 Qc8 {[%cal Re6g4]} 11. Be3 (11. h3 Rd8 (11... Bxh3 $2 12. f5 $14 {and White is better}) 12. Bf3 Bc4 13. Re1 e5 {[%cal Re5f4,Rc6e5]}) 11... Rd8 12. Nd4 Nxd4 13. Bxd4 Bc4 14. a4 e5 15. Be3 d5 {0-1 (52) Smirin,I (2663)-Dubov,D (2638) Khanty-Mansiysk 2013}) 10... h6 11. Bh4 g5 12. Bg3 d5 $11) 9... b5 $1 {Again the well-known motif works very well. Black enjoys a very pleasant position.} 10. Bf3 b4 11. Nd5 Nxd5 12. exd5 Na5 13. Kh1 Nc4 14. Nd4 Bb7 15. Nc6 Bxc6 $1 {Kozul calculated that the c6-pawn can't be saved} 16. dxc6 Rc8 $17 17. Qd5 Na5 18. Qb5 Qb6 19. Qxb6 axb6 20. a3 Nxc6 21. axb4 Nxb4 22. c3 Nd3 23. Ra6 b5 24. Ra1 Rc7 25. Be2 Nxc1 26. Raxc1 Rb8 27. Ra1 b4 28. cxb4 Rc2 29. Bd3 Rd2 30. Rad1 Rxd1 31. Rxd1 Rxb4 32. Rb1 Bxb2 33. g3 d5 34. Bc2 e6 35. Kg2 f6 36. h4 Kg7 37. Kf3 e5 38. fxe5 fxe5 39. Ke2 e4 40. Rd1 Bd4 41. Rb1 Rxb1 42. Bxb1 Kf6 43. g4 Ke5 44. Bc2 Bc5 45. g5 d4 46. Bb3 d3+ 47. Kd2 Kd4 {0-1 (47) Loncar,R (2385)-Kozul,Z (2570) Slavonski Brod 1995} *

