1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 g6 4. d4 cxd4 5. Nxd4 Bg7 6. Be3 Nf6 7. Bc4 O-O 8. Bb3 {This is the real crossroad of the line. Black has many options here. I will mention them individually.} a5 {It is an exciting and tactical move. The idea is that Black doesn't want to play d6 immediately and he wants to play a5-a4 in many cases, to disturb the defenders of the e4-pawn. The drawback is that Black is not developing and he is giving the control of the b5-square. Now White has to decide how he wants to proceed: with 0-0-0 or with 0-0} 9. a4 {White can stop a5-a4, but this move has a serious drawback.} (9. O-O $1 {This is probably the most serious try for White} Nxd4 $1 {I like this simple approach for Black} (9... a4 {First I was thinking about this move, but somehow I don't like the arising positions after:} 10. Nxa4 Nxe4 11. Nb5 {Somehow the game is too wild and I am not sure how Black should proceed} Ra6 (11... d5 $5 {is what I analyzed more, but still I believe that White has an advantage after:} 12. Bb6 (12. Nb6 $6 Ra5) 12... Qd7 13. Qe2 $1 Ne5 14. Rad1 e6 15. Bd4 $1 $16) 12. Qe2 d6 13. c4 Be6 14. Rad1 $14 {White's play seems to be easier}) (9... d6 {This move also doesn't equalize} 10. Ndb5 b6 11. a4 $14) 10. Bxd4 d6 11. Qe2 {this move aims to free the d1-square for the rook. You will find more in-depth analyses in the Lorenzini database, which I added to the file. Here I just want to show you the main ideas and ways of development for Black. Black aims to exchange several minor pieces and start counterplay on the semi-open c-file.} (11. a4 Bd7) (11. Re1 {Doesn't change the character of the position. Black is continuing in the same way} Bd7 12. a4 Bc6 13. Nd5 e6 14. Nxf6+ Bxf6 15. Qd3 Be5 $11) 11... Bd7 {First priority is to develop the bishop to "c6"} 12. Rad1 (12. a4 Bc6 13. Rad1 Nd7 14. Rfe1 Rc8 {You can find more in the analysis of Lorenzini later in the pgn file}) 12... Bc6 13. a4 {Sooner or later White needs to stop the a5-a4 idea} (13. e5 dxe5 14. Bxe5 Qc8 (14... Qb6 {"b6" is even better square for the queen}) 15. a4 Qf5 {½-½ (103) Prasanna Raghuram,R (2309)-Roy Chowdhury,S (2473) Bhubaneswar 2010}) 13... Nd7 {another standard idea in this position. For Black is useful to exchange more minor pieces, because White has space advantage} 14. Bxg7 (14. Be3 {White can keep the bishops on the board. Now the b6-square is unavailable for the queen and Black lacks space, but on the other hand our bishop on the long diagonal is very strong} Rc8 15. Rfe1 Re8 16. h4 h5 17. Bg5 Qc7 18. Nb5 Bxb5 {Black is happy to exchange one more minor piece} 19. Qxb5 Nc5 {Suddenly, White will have problems with the a4-pawn} 20. Ba2 Qc6 {[%csl Ra4,Rb2] ½-½ (57) Oparin,G (2674)-Dubov,D (2711) Chess.com INT 2022}) 14... Kxg7 {[%cal Rd8b6]} 15. Bd5 (15. Bc4 Qb6 16. b3 Qc5 17. Nd5 Rae8 18. Nf4 Nf6 19. Nd5 Nd7 20. Nf4 Nf6 21. Nd5 Nd7 {½-½ (21) Grischuk,A (2745)-Dubov,D (2708) Chess.com INT 2022}) 15... Qb6 16. b3 Rac8 17. Rd3 Nf6 18. Re1 Qb4 19. Bc4 Qc5 20. Qd2 Rfe8 {the main idea is to exchange the bishops here and to obtain pressure on the c-file} 21. Rg3 Qb4 22. Re2 Bd7 23. h3 Rc5 24. f4 Be6 25. Bxe6 fxe6 26. Ree3 $2 Rec8 27. f5 Rxc3 28. e5 Rxe3 29. exf6+ Kxf6 30. Qxe3 Qc5 {0-1 (30) Grischuk,A (2745)-Dubov,D (2708) Chess.com INT 2022}) (9. f3 $6 {If White wants to continue with 0-0-0 he needs to play this first. But it is not working very well in this position. Black has a very powerful response.} d5 $1 {Great resource, immediately blowing off the center. The pawn can be taken in three ways, but Black is doing fine everywhere. White has four replies but neither of them is good} 10. exd5 (10. Nxd5 $2 {This move is the worst of all} Nxd5 11. exd5 (11. Bxd5 $4 {is losing a piece} Nxd4 12. Bxd4 Bxd4 13. Qxd4 e6 $19) 11... Nxd4 (11... Nb4 {Is another possibility} 12. c4 (12. a4 Nxd5 $15) 12... a4 13. Bc2 e5 $19) 12. Bxd4 e5 $1 13. Bf2 $8 (13. Be3 $4 a4 14. Bc4 Qh4+) 13... a4 14. Bc4 Qc7 15. Qe2 e4 $1 16. O-O-O (16. O-O exf3 17. gxf3 Bxb2 18. Rad1 Be5 $1 $15) 16... exf3 17. gxf3 b5 18. Bxb5 a3 $15 {It seems that White is in trouble here}) (10. Bxd5 {This is the main move for White} Nxd5 11. Nxd5 (11. exd5 {This move is popular, but I think that Black equalizes easily after the typical} Nb4 12. Nde2 e6 13. Qd2 (13. dxe6 $2 Bxe6 {Those positions with two active bishops and compromised White structure are terrible for White. The c2-pawn is a problem. Also this f3-move creates holes in White's position. With or without queens on the board, this is terrible for White} 14. a3 Nd5 15. Nxd5 Bxd5 $17) 13... exd5 14. a3 d4 $1 15. Nxd4 (15. O-O-O $2 {Allows the beatiful} Nxc2 $1 16. Qxc2 Bf5 17. Qb3 (17. Ne4 Rc8 18. N2c3 Qb6 19. Bf2 Be6 $1 $19) 17... dxc3 18. Rxd8 cxb2+ 19. Kd2 Raxd8+ $19) 15... Bxd4 16. axb4 Bxe3 17. Qxe3 Bf5) 11... f5 $1 {well-timed break. White king is still in the center and Black has two powerful bishops. Still the position is far from clear and both sides must play very accurately. Objectively the position is equal and there are several ways to reach an equal endgame. I will show you the main line} (11... Bxd4 $4 {This time the trick doesn't work} 12. Bxd4 e6 {and White is not winning a piece} 13. Nf6+ $18 (13. Bf6 $18 {or})) 12. Nxc6 bxc6 13. Nb6 Rb8 14. Qxd8 Rxd8 15. Rd1 Rxd1+ 16. Kxd1 fxe4 17. Nxc8 Rxc8 18. b3 exf3 19. gxf3 $11 {There are 40 games in this position, and the majority of them ended in a draw ½-½ (46) Mitkov,N (2552)-Perelshteyn,E (2522) Chicago 2006}) (10. Nxc6 $6 bxc6 11. exd5 a4 $1 12. Nxa4 Nxd5 $15) 10... Nb4 {If we take the d5-pawn for free, we will be better, so White is trying to protect it} 11. Nde2 (11. Ndb5 $6 {After this move, Black is simply better} a4 12. Nxa4 (12. Bc4 Bf5 $1 (12... Bd7 13. Na3 $5 b5 14. Be2 Rc8 15. Bd4 $1 $14) 13. Rc1 Bd7 $1 {This unexpected retreat gives Black an advantage} 14. Na3 (14. O-O Bxb5 15. Nxb5 (15. Bxb5 Nfxd5 16. Nxd5 Qxd5 $17) 15... Nfxd5 16. Bf2 Rc8 17. Bxd5 Nxd5 $15) 14... b5 $1 15. Be2 Rc8 16. Bd4 Bh6 $1 $17) 12... Nfxd5 13. Bf2 Bd7 $1 14. c4 (14. Nbc3 Bxa4 15. Nxa4 b5 {½-½ (55) Ivanovic,B (2440)-Wedberg,T (2425) Eksjo 1980}) 14... Bxb5 15. cxb5 Rxa4 $1 16. Bxa4 Bxb2 17. O-O Bxa1 $1 (17... Nc3 18. Qb3 Bxa1 19. Qxb4 Ne2+ $11 {0-1 (29) Muniz,R (2284)-Lopez Falcon,J (2155) Montevideo 2015}) 18. Qxa1 Nd3 19. Qd4 Nxf2 20. Rxf2 e6 21. Bb3 Qa5 $15 {[%cal Gf8d8]}) 11... a4 12. Nxa4 (12. Bc4 $2 {leaves the c2-pawn without protection} Bf5 13. Nd4 Qc7 (13... a3 $1 {is also very good} 14. b3 b5 $1 {Is well-timed break} 15. Ncxb5 (15. Ndxb5 Nxc2+ $19) (15. Bxb5 Nfxd5 $19) 15... Nfxd5 16. Bf2 Nxc2+ $1 $17) 14. Qe2 $8 (14. Be2 $2 a3 $19) 14... Rfc8 15. a3 $8 Nxc2+ (15... Qxc4 $17) 16. Nxc2 Qxc4 $17) 12... Nfxd5 13. Bf2 $1 {Is the only way to fight for an advantage, but Black still equalizes after:} (13. Bd4 $2 Bf5 $1 14. Bxg7 (14. Qd2 Bxc2 15. Bxc2 Nxc2+ 16. Qxc2 Bxd4 17. Nxd4 Nb4 18. Qb3 Rxa4 $1 $17 {[%csl Rd4]}) 14... Bxc2 $1 15. Bxc2 $6 (15. Qd2 $5 Bxb3 $17) 15... Ne3 $1 $17) 13... Bf5 14. a3 (14. O-O {Is the safest move, but doesn't pose any problems} b5 15. Nac3 Nxc3 16. Nxc3 Qxd1 17. Raxd1 (17. Rfxd1 Bxc2 $11) 17... Bxc2 18. Bxc2 Nxc2 19. Nd5 e6 $11) 14... Nxc2+ 15. Bxc2 Qa5+ 16. b4 Nxb4 17. axb4 Qxb4+ 18. Qd2 Qxd2+ 19. Kxd2 Bxa1 20. Rxa1 Bxc2 21. Kxc2 b5 22. Nec3 Rfc8 $11) 9... Ng4 {The difference now and on the previous move is that with the pawn on "a4" White is forced to take on b3 with the c-pawn} 10. Qxg4 Nxd4 11. Qh4 (11. Qd1 Nxb3 12. cxb3 d6 $15 {[%cal Rc8e6]}) 11... d6 12. Nd5 Re8 13. Rd1 Nxb3 14. Bb6 Qd7 15. cxb3 Ra6 16. Bd4 Qd8 17. O-O Be6 18. Bxg7 Kxg7 19. Nf4 Qc8 20. Rd3 Rc6 21. Qg3 f6 22. Ne2 Bf7 23. Nd4 Rc1 {0-1 (68) Almasi,Z (2676)-Kramnik,V (2807) Monte Carlo 2003} *

