1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 g6 4. d4 cxd4 5. Nxd4 Bg7 6. Be3 Nf6 7. Bc4 O-O 8. Bb3 {This is the real crossroad of the line. Black has many options here. I will mention them one by one.} d6 $1 {This is the last variation we will check. Black makes the most natural move in the position. Black is threatening to play Ng4 here. As always White is at a crossroad. He needs to decide how to proceed here: with f2-f3 followed by Qd2 and 0-0-0 or with h2-h3 followed by 0-0} 9. f3 (9. h3 $6 {here I like the simple approach} Na5 {very simple approach. Black wants to continue with: b6 followed by Bb7, Rc8, Nxb3 and Nd7} 10. O-O b6 11. Re1 (11. Qd3 Bb7 12. Rfe1 Rc8 13. Rad1 Nxb3 14. cxb3 Nd7 15. Bg5 h6 16. Bh4 Rc5 17. f4 Rh5 18. Nf3 Nc5 19. Qc2 Ne6 20. Qd2 Qd7 (20... Nd4 $1 $11) 21. Nd5 Re8 {0-1 (39) Kovalev,V (2623)-Giri,A (2773) Chess.com INT 2022}) (11. Qd2 Bb7 12. f3 Rc8 13. Bh6 Bxh6 {In such positions, Black is not afraid to exchange on h6, because White's queen has no support for an attack} 14. Qxh6 e5 15. Nde2 b5 16. a3 Nxb3 17. cxb3 d5 {½-½ (53) Nepomniachtchi,I (2784)-Carlsen,M (2862) chess24.com INT 2020}) (11. f3 Bb7 12. Rf2 Rc8 $15 {[%cal Ra5c4]}) 11... Nxb3 {Abasov successfully tried this move against Giri} ({more popular is} 11... Bb7 12. Bg5 Nxb3 13. axb3 h6 14. Bh4 Qd7 $1 {Kasparov chooses a very aggressive plan. He is preparing to push e5} (14... a6 $5 {Is the modern way to handle the position.}) 15. Qd2 (15. Nd5 $2 Nxd5 16. exd5 g5 17. Bg3 Bxd5 $15) 15... Nh5 $146 16. f3 (16. Nde2 g5 17. Bg3 f5 $5 18. exf5 Qxf5 $36) 16... e5 $5 17. Nde2 (17. Ndb5 d5 18. Nxa7 (18. exd5 a6 19. Na3 b5 $17) 18... d4 19. Ncb5 f5 20. exf5 gxf5 $17) 17... f5 $36 {½-½ (32) Anand,V (2753)-Kasparov,G (2847) Linares 2003}) 12. axb3 Bb7 13. Qd3 Nd7 14. Bg5 Nc5 15. Qe3 Qd7 16. Rad1 Ne6 17. Nxe6 Qxe6 18. Bh6 Rfc8 19. Bxg7 Kxg7 20. Rd4 Rc5 $11 {0-1 (32) Giri,A (2775)-Abasov,N (2632) Baku 2023}) 9... Bd7 (9... Qa5 {I can also recommend this simple move to avoid complications. Black's idea is very simple: Nxd4 followed by Be6 and then, depending on White's plan, can play either Nd7 against 0-0 or Rfc8 and b5 against 0-0-0} 10. Qd2 Nxd4 11. Bxd4 Be6 12. O-O (12. O-O-O b5 13. Nd5 (13. Kb1 {Heavy analyzed theoretical line is} b4 14. Nd5 Bxd5 15. exd5 Qb5 {but I believe that Black is just in time to equalize} 16. Rhe1 a5 17. Qe2 Qxe2 18. Rxe2 a4 19. Bc4 Rfc8 20. Bb5 Ra5 21. Bxf6 Bxf6 22. Bc6 {½-½ (22) Ibarra Jerez,J (2563)-Theodorou,N (2584) Chess.com INT 2023}) 13... Qxd2+ 14. Rxd2 Bxd5 15. Bxd5 Nxd5 16. Bxg7 Kxg7 17. Rxd5 a6 $11 {½-½ (35) Sindarov,J (2661)-Matlakov,M (2662) Dubai 2023}) 12... Nd7 {We are already familiar with this position} 13. Bxg7 Kxg7 14. Rad1 Nf6 $146 {Giri chooses this interesting novelty, which doesn't change much. The position is still equal, but easier to play with Black.} (14... Qc5+ 15. Kh1 b5 16. f4 Nf6 17. Qd4 Qxd4 18. Rxd4 a6 $11) 15. Qd4 Rac8 $11) 10. Qd2 Nxd4 {This move was played many times, but still is less theoretical than 10...Rc8} (10... Rc8 {Transposes to normal Dragon}) 11. Bxd4 b5 {This is our starting position. Black wants to continue with a5-a4. I will provide you with some brief analyses and directions. If you choose this variation you can check the model games} 12. a4 (12. h4 {The main move. White starts an immediate attack} a5 13. a4 (13. h5 {White can ignore the threats on the queenside and continue with his plan, but this is risky} a4 14. Bd5 b4 15. Bxf6 (15. Ne2 $6 e5 $1 $13 {and Black takes the initiative}) 15... exf6 16. Ne2 Rc8 17. hxg6 hxg6 18. g4 Be6 {Just in time} 19. Bxe6 fxe6 $11 {Black's king is safe now and we can't say the same for his colleague 0-1 (34) Vavulin,M (2604)-Mamedov,R (2688) Moscow 2017}) 13... bxa4 {With this move, we keep White's king in the centre, it will be very dangerous to castle queenside with so many open files. With White's king on "e1", it is hard to believe that White's attack with h4-h5 has a chance to succeed} 14. Nxa4 Be6 15. Nb6 Ra6 16. Nd5 Bxd5 17. exd5 Qc7 {It is easy to imagine that soon we will have an endgame with a knight against a bishop where Black will have an advantage. You can see the game in the Model games section 0-1 (44) Macieja,B (2608)-Shirov,A (2722) Bydgoszcz 2001}) (12. O-O a5 13. a3 $5 Bc6 {0-1 (85) Christiansen,L (2570)-Tiviakov,S (2599) Moscow 2001}) (12. Nd5 {It is too early for this} Nxd5 13. Bxg7 $1 Kxg7 14. exd5 (14. Bxd5 Rc8 15. h4 h6 $11) 14... a5 15. a3 (15. a4 $6 Qb6 16. Qf2 Qxf2+ 17. Kxf2 {This is the dream endgame for Black in such structures} Rfc8 $17 {[%csl Gc2][%cal Yb5a4]}) 15... Qb6 16. O-O-O Rfc8 $11) 12... bxa4 13. Nxa4 Be6 (13... Bc6 14. Nc3 a5 15. O-O Qb8 {½-½ (16) Jakovenko,D (2703)-Gelfand,B (2728) Geneva 2017}) 14. Bxe6 fxe6 15. O-O Qc7 16. Nc3 Rfc8 {0-1 (58) Vallejo Pons,F (2684)-Anand,V (2803) Leon 2008} *

