1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 g6 4. d4 cxd4 5. Nxd4 Bg7 6. Be3 Nf6 7. Bc4 O-O 8. Bb3 {This is the real crossroad of the line. Black has many options here. I will mention them one by one.} Re8 {This is one of my favourite ways how to continue. This modern line was popularized by GM Dubov who is a well-known theoretician. It is a waiting move, the idea is that we keep the pawn on d7 for one more move, Keeping the option to play d7-d5 later on.  One of the main ideas is to meet f3,Qd2 with e6-d5} 9. O-O {This move is a small win for us. We forced White to go for the short castle instead of 0-0-0} (9. Nxc6 {This quite move doesn't pose any serious problems to Black} dxc6 {we are forced to go for an endgame here} (9... bxc6 $2 10. e5 $1 $18) 10. Qxd8 (10. h3 Qc7 $1 11. f4 b5 12. e5 b4 13. Na4 (13. exf6 exf6) 13... Nd5 14. Qf3 (14. Bxd5 cxd5 15. Qxd5 Bb7) 14... Nxe3 15. Qxe3 a5 16. O-O-O Qa7 17. Qe4 Bf5 {0-1 (44) Nakamura,H (2736)-Dubov,D (2699) chess24.com INT 2020}) 10... Rxd8 11. f3 {[%cal Rf6e8]} Nd7 (11... b6 {[%cal Rc8a6]}) 12. O-O-O Re8 13. Rd2 Nf8 14. Rhd1 Be6 15. Ne2 a5 16. Kb1 h5 17. Nd4 Bxd4 18. Bxd4 b5 19. Be3 a4 20. Bxe6 Nxe6 {0-1 (53) Gabrielian,A (2499)-Melkumyan,H (2670) Chess.com INT 2018}) (9. f3 $5 {The most ambitious try. This is somehow more ambitious than 0-0. White wants to continue with Qd2 followed by 0-0-0. We need to play energetically. Otherwise White would be just better.} e6 (9... d5 $5 10. exd5 $1 {The critical try} (10. Bxd5 {Allows Black to equalize after:} Nxd5 11. Nxd5 Be6 12. c4 Rc8 13. O-O Nxd4 14. Bxd4 Rxc4 15. Bxg7 Kxg7 16. b3 Rc8 $11) 10... Nb4 11. Nde2 e6 12. Bd4 exd5 13. Qd2 (13. O-O Be6 14. Bf2 d4 15. Nxd4 Bxb3 16. Nxb3 Qxd1 17. Raxd1 Nxc2 18. Na5 b6 19. Nc4 {½-½ (19) Kovalev,V (2650)-Gelfand,B (2695) Poikovsky 2018}) 13... Nc6 14. O-O-O Nxd4 15. Nxd4 Bd7 16. g4 Bc6 17. Kb1 Nd7 18. h4 $14 {White's attack looks dangerous 1-0 (33) Navara,D (2740)-Gelfand,B (2703) Batumi 2018}) 10. O-O {As we know this move is a small win for us} (10. Qd2 d5 11. O-O-O (11. exd5 $2 {here only Black can be better after:} Nxd5 12. Nxd5 Nxd4 $1 {this intermediate move poses White problems} 13. Nc3 (13. Bxd4 exd5+ {White needs to be careful not to lose on a spot} 14. Kd1 (14. Be3 $4 d4 $19) (14. Kf1 b6 $15 {[%cal Rc8a6]}) (14. Kf2 $4 Qh4+ $19) 14... Bxd4 15. Qxd4 Qg5 $17 {0-1 (70) Morozov,D (2310)-Zvjaginsev,V (2672) Chelyabinsk 2016}) 13... Nxb3 $15 14. axb3 Qxd2+ 15. Kxd2 $15 {Black enjoys the bishop pair in the endgame}) 11... Nxd4 12. Bxd4 e5 13. Bf2 d4 14. Ne2 (14. Nd5 Nxd5 (14... a5 $5) 15. Bxd5 Be6 $17) 14... a5 $1 {[%csl Ra4][%cal Ra4a3]} 15. c3 Qc7 16. Kb1 a4 17. Bc2 dxc3 18. Nxc3 Be6 {[%cal Rg7f8,Ra4a3]} 19. Qd6 Qc8 20. Qc5 Bf8 21. Qxc8 Rexc8 {½-½ (38) Kadric,D (2576)-Abdusattorov,N (2661) Sharjah 2022}) (10. f4 {White is trying to prove that Re8 and e6 are not a very good combination. On the other hand to play f3 followed by f4 also doesn't make much sense. Black has many ways to continue here:} Nd5 $5 {even this move is possible here and I like it very much} (10... d6 {You can investigate it in your own. I will give you just the main line} 11. Ndb5 Bf8 12. Qf3 a6 13. Nd4 Na5 14. O-O b5 15. f5 exf5 16. exf5 Bb7 17. Bxf7+ Kxf7 $13 {½-½ (39) Navara,D (2745)-Mamedov,R (2704) Shamkir 2018}) (10... d5 11. e5 Nd7 12. Qd2 Nxd4 13. Bxd4 f6 14. exf6 Nxf6 $14) (10... Ng4 11. Qxg4 Nxd4 12. O-O-O Nxb3+ 13. axb3 Qa5 14. Kb1 $14) 11. exd5 exd5 12. O-O Rxe3 13. Ndb5 d4 14. Nd5 Rxb3 15. axb3 d6 {Probably White is better here, but we have very interesting compensation for the exchange} 16. Re1 Rb8 17. c3 dxc3 18. Ndxc3 (18. bxc3 a6 19. Nbc7 Bd7 $13 {[%cal Rb8c8]}) 18... Be6 (18... a6 $1 19. Qxd6 Bf5 $44) 19. Qxd6 Qxd6 $2 (19... Bxb3 $1 $11) 20. Nxd6 $14 {1-0 (40) Abdrlauf,E (2523)-Alsina Leal,D (2538) Barcelona 2023}) 10... d5 11. exd5 Nxd5 12. Nxd5 exd5 13. Bf2 Qg5 14. Kh1 Qh5 (14... Bd7 {Probably this move equalizes easier} 15. c3 Nxd4 16. Bxd4 Bxd4 17. Qxd4 Re2 {The activity of Black's pieces fully compensates the weakened structure.}) 15. c3 Be5 16. Bg1 Nxd4 17. cxd4 Bf4 $17 {½-½ (57) Leko,P (2734)-Vitiugov,N (2742) Bilbao 2014}) 9... d6 10. h3 {White prevents Ng4} Na5 $1 {This is the modern way to handle the position. Black wants to exchange the b3-bishop and then simply finish the development and start his counterplay on the c-file} (10... Bd7 {is the old main line} 11. f4 Nxd4 12. Bxd4 Bc6 13. e5 dxe5 (13... Nh5 $1 $13) 14. fxe5 Nd5 15. Qf3 $16 {½-½ (94) Nakamura,H (2786)-Carlsen,M (2832) Chess.com INT 2018}) 11. Qd2 a6 12. Bh6 Bh8 {Black decides to make use of Re8 and to keep the bishops on the board} 13. Rfe1 (13. a4 {prevented b5, but White should now take on b3 with the c-pawn.} e5 $1 14. Nde2 Nxb3 15. cxb3 Be6 {preparing d5 with an advantage} 16. f4 Bxb3 17. Bg5 Qb6+ 18. Kh1 exf4 19. Rxf4 Nh5 20. Rf3 Be5 21. g4 Ng7 $19 {Black has an extra pawn and two powerful bishops 0-1 (54) Sadhwani,R (2619)-Abdusattorov,N (2661) Chess.com INT 2022}) (13. f4 {this move is always met with the move e5} Nxb3 14. axb3 Qb6 15. e5 Nd7 16. Nd5 Qc5 17. c4 dxe5 18. fxe5 Bxe5 {½-½ (39) Jones,I (2333)-Carr,T (2375) ICCF email 2016}) (13. Rae1 b5 14. f4 (14. Nd5 Nxb3 15. axb3 Nxd5 (15... Bb7 $1) 16. exd5 Bb7 {1-0 (67) Hansen,E (2606)-Svane,F (2421) Chess.com INT 2020}) 14... e5 15. Nde2 Nxb3 16. axb3 b4 17. Na4 Nxe4 18. Qxb4 Bf5 {0-1 (33) Djukic,N (2507)-Perunovic,M (2433) Nis 2019}) (13. Rad1 {After such neutral moves, Black can proceed with his main plans} Nxb3 14. axb3 Bd7 15. Rfe1 Qa5 16. Ra1 Qc7 17. Bg5 Bc6 (17... Rac8 $1) 18. Nxc6 bxc6 19. Qe2 a5 {The position is about equal, but Black manages to win it: 0-1 (48) Hou,Y (2628)-Assaubayeva,B (2440) Astana 2023}) 13... Qc7 {this is always possible; sometimes, Black is playing Nc4 here} 14. Nd5 Nxd5 15. Bxd5 (15. exd5 Nc4 $15) 15... e6 16. Bb3 b5 {We have a typical Sicilian position where Black is better. There is no kingside attack and on the other hand Black can play Bb7, Rc8, Rc4, etc... White doesn't have any compensation for the bishop pair. 0-1 (58) Sjugirov,S (2696)-Abdusattorov,N (2661) Chess.com INT 2022} *

