1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 g6 4. d4 cxd4 5. Nxd4 Bg7 6. Nde2 {This strange knight retreat has the idea of avoiding simplifications. It harmonizes well with White's fianchetto setup on the kingside.} (6. Nb3 $5 {Preventing the black idea from move 7 in the mainline of this chapter.} Nf6 7. g3 b6 $5 {Again we see this move. It makes a lot of sense when the pawn restricts a white knight on the queenside.} 8. Bg2 d6 $1 (8... O-O $2 9. e5 $1 $18 {, and Black loses a piece without compensation.}) 9. O-O (9. e5 $2 {On this occasion, this tactical issue favours the second player.} Nxe5 10. Bxa8 Bg4 11. Bc6+ Nxc6 12. f3 Be6 $17 {The exchange is more than compensated for as Black has a pawn and much better piece play.}) 9... Bb7 $1 (9... O-O $2 10. e5 $18) 10. Nd5 Nd7 $1 {An important move. The knight exchange would give White an advantage due to the opened e-file and the weakness of the c6-square.} (10... Nxd5 11. exd5 $16 {[%csl Gc6][%cal Gf1e1,Ge1e7]}) 11. c3 O-O {Black has a comfortable position. The next step is to prepare a timely e7-e6 to expel the knight from d5.}) 6... Nf6 7. g3 b5 $5 {The move-order chosen by White allows this fast and effective counterplay.} (7... d6 8. Bg2 b6 $2 9. e5 $1 $18) 8. Bg2 (8. Nxb5 $2 {The pawn is untouchable. This capture is refuted by} Qa5+ 9. Nbc3 Nxe4 10. Bg2 Nxc3 11. Nxc3 Ba6 $19) 8... Rb8 {[%csl Gb5][%cal Gg2a8,Gb8b5] Defending the pawn and getting out of the pin.} ({Again, it would be a mistake to play} 8... d6 $2 9. e5 Nxe5 10. Bxa8 $18) 9. O-O d6 ({A possible alternative is} 9... O-O 10. Nd5 d6 {Again, we must avoid the capture of the knight on d5.} 11. a4 (11. c3 b4 $1 {Getting activity on the queenside as quickly as possible.} 12. Nxb4 Nxb4 13. cxb4 Rxb4 14. Nc3 Ba6 15. Re1 Nd7 $1 {[%cal Gd7c5,Gc5d3] Excellent maneuver, seeking to reach the d3-square. Black's piece play is undoubtedly superior. An example in practice followed up with} 16. Nd5 Rd4 17. Qc2 e6 18. Nc3 Bd3 19. Qb3 Qa5 $19 {0-1 Gantar,J (2220) -Hovhannisyan,R (2619)/ Skopje MKD 2017 (25)}) (11. Nxf6+ $6 {This capture does not cause any inconveniences. Black has an easy game.} Bxf6 12. c3 b4 $1 13. Nd4 Ne5 $17) 11... b4 12. Rb1 Nd7 $1 {[%csl Gc5][%cal Gd7c5]} 13. c4 b3 $1 {secures the b4-square for the black pieces and breaks the white queenside apart.} 14. Be3 Nc5 15. Nec3 e6 16. Nf4 a6 17. Nd3 Nxd3 $1 (17... Qa5 $5 18. Nxc5 dxc5 $15 {0-1 Vasli, A (2371)-Maze,S (2557)/chess.com INT 2020}) 18. Qxd3 Ne5 19. Qe2 Qc7 $19 {[%csl Ra4,Rc4] White lacks a plan and has multiple weaknesses.}) 10. h3 ({An important option is} 10. Nd5 Nd7 $1 {Again we avoid the exchange on d5. Instead we finish development and play e7-e6 at an opportune moment.} 11. c3 (11. Rb1 O-O 12. h3 b4 13. Be3 a5 $132 {[%cal Ga5a4,Gb4b3,Ga4a3]}) 11... O-O 12. Bg5 $5 (12. Nd4 Nxd4 13. cxd4 {This transformation of the pawn structure is not so common in the Sicilian defences.} Bb7 14. Be3 Bxd5 {Black ensures equality with his more active pieces.} 15. exd5 Qa5 16. a3 Rfc8 17. Rc1 Rxc1 18. Qxc1 b4 $11) (12. a4 b4 13. Nd4 Nxd4 14. cxd4 e6 15. Nf4 Ba6 16. Re1 {[%csl Yf4]} b3 $1 {With this pawn advance, Black accelerates his play on the queenside.} 17. Be3 Nb6 $15 {[%cal Gb6c4] The position of the second player is preferable.}) 12... h6 13. Be3 a5 14. Nd4 (14. Qd2 e6 15. Ndf4 {[%csl Rf4] The knight on f4 hinders White's game.} Nde5 $17 {[%cal Ge5c4,Ge5g4]}) 14... Nxd4 15. cxd4 Nb6 $11) 10... O-O ({White also did not know how to solve the position after} 10... b4 11. Nd5 Nd7 $1 12. c3 (12. a3 $5 bxa3 13. Rxa3 O-O 14. b3 a5 15. c4 Nc5 16. Ndc3 Qb6 17. Be3 Qb4 $15 {0-1 (22) Galyamov, V (2237) -Dzhumaev,M (2495)/Tashkent UZB 2012}) 12... bxc3 13. Nexc3 O-O $15 {There is no clear plan for White.} 14. f4 $2 (14. Re1) 14... a5 15. Kh1 Nb4 16. f5 e6 17. Ne3 Ne5 18. Ng4 Nxg4 19. hxg4 Ba6 $17 {Whites position is at least painful. 0-1 (25) Iwanesko,A (2217)-Degraeve,J (2574)}) 11. a3 (11. Nd5 Nd7 $1 12. Kh2 Nc5 13. Rb1 e6 14. Ndf4 b4 $17 {1/2-1/2 Skvortsov,A (2139) -Ponkratov, P (2619)/Khanty-Mansiysk 2019}) 11... a5 12. Be3 (12. Nf4 {Anticipating} b4 13. axb4 axb4 14. Ncd5 Nd7 15. Nd3 e6 16. N5f4 Nde5 $1 $15 {[%cal Ge5c4] Black has a small plus.}) (12. f4 {An active attempt that tends to work in Black's favour, due to the weaknesses it produces.} b4 13. axb4 axb4 14. Nd5 Nxd5 $1 {One of the few cases where it is correct to capture on d5. Black seeks to take advantage of the weakness of the white king, gaining time to complete his development.} ({The standard} 14... Nd7 $5 {is also fully playable.}) 15. exd5 Qb6+ 16. Kh2 Na5 17. Rf3 Bf5 $17 {0-1 Gwaze, R (2454)-Gundavaa,B (2519) / Istanbul 2012}) 12... Nd7 $1 {With this move, Black is threatening b4 followed by the capture of the b2-pawn. Defending that pawn with a passive knight on a4 is not desirable for White.} 13. Rb1 b4 14. axb4 axb4 15. Nd5 Ba6 {The good play of the black pieces, that we saw throughout this chapter, is evident once again.} 16. Re1 e6 $1 17. Ndf4 Qc7 $15 {The black position is preferable. Black will increase his advantage.} 18. Qd2 Nce5 19. b3 Rfc8 20. Rbc1 Nc5 21. Nd4 Qb7 22. f3 Ned7 23. Nde2 Rc6 $2 ({The best continuation was} 23... d5 $1 {, leading to great advantage for the second player.} 24. exd5 e5 25. Nd3 Bxd3 26. cxd3 Nxb3 $19) 24. Bf2 Rbc8 25. h4 Ne5 26. Nd4 R6c7 27. Red1 Rd7 28. Qe1 h5 29. Rd2 $17 {Black is still preferable. 1-0 (58) Caruana,F (2808) -Vachier Lagrave,M (2796) Stavanger NOR 2017} *

