1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 g6 5. Nc3 Bg7 6. Be3 Nf6 7. Nxc6 {A secondary line that Black must have studied well.} bxc6 8. e5 {Here Black has two moves. Our choice is the fierce} Ng8 $5 {We consider this knight retreat the more combative option.} ({The other option is} 8... Nd5 $5 9. Nxd5 cxd5 10. Qxd5 Rb8 {, which is also heavily analysed.}) 9. f4 (9. Bd4 $5 {An interesting move.} Qa5 10. e6 {This pawn advance is a frequent tactical theme in this variation.} (10. f4 $5 Rb8 $1 11. Qd2 ({Too passive is} 11. Rb1 $2 c5 12. Be3 Nh6 $17 {, with good squares for the black pieces.}) 11... f6 $1 {A precise central break.} ({The capture of the pawn with} 11... Rxb2 12. Ne4 Qxd2+ 13. Kxd2 $13 {is very risky. Black has serious development problems.}) 12. Bc4 fxe5 13. fxe5 Rxb2 14. Ne4 Qxd2+ 15. Kxd2 Rb6 $1 $13 {The capture of the black rook seems unappealing. The game is complex. Black has at least equal chances.}) 10... Nf6 $1 11. exf7+ (11. exd7+ $6 {After this capture, White has problems.} Bxd7 12. Qe2 (12. Bc4 $2 {This ugly mistake is punished with the blunt} Bg4 $1 13. f3 (13. Qd2 Qb4 $1 14. Be2 (14. Bb3 Rd8 $19) 14... Rd8 15. O-O-O Ne4 16. Nxe4 Rxd4 $19 {, and Black wins.}) 13... Rd8 14. fxg4 c5 15. Bb5+ Kf8 $19 {Winning again.}) 12... c5 $1 (12... O-O {has been played.} 13. O-O-O Bg4 14. f3 Be6 15. Qe5 $1 $11 {1-0 Kabanov,N (2521)-Khismatullin,D  (2613)/Novokuznetsk 2008}) 13. Be5 O-O $15 {Black has the more comfortable game.}) 11... Kxf7 12. Bc4+ d5 13. Bb3 e5 $1 {This is our recommendation, which we believe gives Black the slightly preferable chances.} 14. Be3 (14. Bxe5 Re8 15. f4 Qb6 16. Qf3 Bh6 $17 {[%cal Gc8a6,Ga6e2,Ge8e2] Followed by Ba6. White cannot castle and Black's advantage is evident.}) 14... Re8 {[%csl Gd5,Ge5]} 15. Qd2 Be6 $17 {Black's central superiority grants him the advantage.}) 9... Nh6 10. Qf3 (10. Qd2 d6 $1 {We find this break more attractive than a straight d7-d5, as the central tension favours Black.} 11. O-O-O O-O 12. h3 (12. exd6 {Insipid simplification of the central pawns that does not cause any damage.} exd6 13. Qxd6 $2 (13. Bd4 Bxd4 14. Qxd4 d5 $11) 13... Qxd6 14. Rxd6 Nf5 15. Rd3 Ba6 16. Bc5 Bxd3 17. Bxf8 Bxf1 18. Bxg7 Bxg2 19. Rg1 Kxg7 20. Rxg2 $17 {0-1 Comp Fritz 2-Kasparov,G (2780)/Cologne 1992}) 12... Nf5 13. Bf2 c5 $1 {Excellent response from Black, giving the position a very dynamic character.} 14. g4 (14. Bxc5 $2 {This capture is a serious error.} Bb7 15. exd6 exd6 16. Bxd6 (16. Bf2 Qa5 $1 {With excellent attacking prospects in favour of the second player.}) 16... Nxd6 17. Qxd6 Qa5 $17 {Black achieves the position of his dreams in this opening. Two pawns down, but a pair of bishops, attack against the king and brutal piece activity.}) (14. exd6 exd6 15. Nd5 (15. Bxc5 $2 Be6 $1 16. Bf2 Qa5 $19 {Similar to 14.Bxc5?.}) 15... Be6 16. Bc4 Qd7 17. b3 Nd4 $15) 14... Nd4 15. Bg2 Rb8 16. Bxd4 cxd4 17. Qxd4 Qa5 $44 {With ample compensation for the sacrificed pawn.}) 10... O-O 11. Bc4 d6 $1 {Again we prefer this central advance.} ({Also perfectly playable is} 11... d5 $5 {Now the correct path for White is} 12. Bb3 $1 (12. Be2 $2 {This quiet bishop development is an imprecision.} Bg4 13. Qf2 f6 $1 {The best way to unleash the full potential of the black pieces.} 14. exf6 Bxf6 15. Bd2 Rb8 16. b3 Qd6 $5 $40 {[%csl Re1,Rf2][%cal Gf8f2,Ge7e5,Gd6a3,Ge5h2,Gf6e5] The white king does not feel safe on either side, much less in the centre. Black has a promising attack.}) (12. exd6 {This capture is not a solution for White either.} Bg4 13. Qxc6 (13. Qf2 exd6 $17) 13... Rc8 $1 ({Another excellent move is} 13... Nf5 $5 $40 14. Nd5 $140 Bxb2 15. Rb1 Rc8 16. Qa6 e6 17. Ne7+ Nxe7 18. dxe7 Bc3+ 19. Kf1 Qxe7 20. Bd3 e5 $19) 14. Qa4 (14. Qe4 exd6 15. Bb5 Qa5 $19 {[%csl Ra1,Rb5,Rc3][%cal Gg7c3,Gc8c3,Ga5b5]}) (14. Qa6 $142 Nf5 $1 {This knight maneuver, gaining time due to the threat against the white bishop, grants an advantage.} 15. Bd2 (15. Nd5 Bxb2 16. Rb1 e6 17. Ne7+ Nxe7 18. dxe7 Bc3+ 19. Kf2 Qxe7 $17) 15... Nxd6 $17 {Black enjoys great piece activity.}) 14... Nf5 ({Worth considering is} 14... exd6 $5 15. O-O $140 Qe8 $3 {This modest displacement sidestep by the queen wins the game.} 16. Qxe8 Rfxe8 17. Ba6 Rxc3 18. bxc3 Rxe3 $19) 15. Bf2 $2 (15. Bd2 $142 Qxd6 16. Bd3 Nh4 17. O-O Bd4+ 18. Kh1 Bd7 {[%csl Ra4,Rg2]} 19. Qb3 Bc6 $17) 15... Nxd6 $17) 12... Qc7 13. O-O Kh8 $1 {Preparing the f6 break. The position is highly complex.} (13... Nf5 14. Bf2 f6 $4 15. Nxd5 $18)) 12. O-O-O $1 {White offers an exchange to finish his development.} (12. O-O $2 {After this mistake, Black easily gains the advantage.} Nf5 $1 13. Bf2 (13. exd6 $4 Nxe3 14. Qxe3 exd6 $19 {The dark-squared bishop will rule the board.}) 13... dxe5 $17) (12. h3 {[%csl Gg4][%cal Ge1c1,Rc8g4] Investing time to enable long castling.} Nf5 13. O-O-O (13. Bf2 dxe5 $17) 13... Nxe3 14. Qxe3 Qc7 15. Rhe1 Rb8 $15 {Black has a promising attacking position.}) 12... Bg4 (12... Qc7 13. h3 Nf5 14. Bf2 $11) 13. Qxc6 Nf5 $13 14. Bf2 (14. Rd3 $2 Nxe3 15. Rxe3 dxe5 16. Rd3 Qb8 $19) 14... Bxd1 {Black wins an exchange but has some tactical problems, as seen below.} 15. Rxd1 Qc8 $1 (15... Qa5 $2 16. g4 Nh6 17. Rd5 $18) 16. Bd5 (16. Qxc8 Raxc8 17. Ba6 Rxc3 $5 (17... Rcd8 18. g4 Nh6 19. exd6 Rxd6 20. Rxd6 exd6 21. h3 $13 {The question in this line is whether the bad location of the black knight compensates for the exchange.}) 18. bxc3 Bh6 $13 {With a final position similar to that of the mainline.}) 16... Qxc6 (16... Rb8 $2 17. g4 $1 Nh6 18. Bxa7 $16) 17. Bxc6 Rac8 18. Bd7 Rxc3 19. bxc3 Bh6 $13 {The resulting endgame is very complex, but Black has good counterplay.} *

