1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6 6. Be2 {As in most Sicilian defences, this bishop development stands for a rather quiet game. White does not intend to refute Black's play in the opening and instead seeks a prolonged positional struggle in the middlegame.} g6 7. Nb3 {Avoiding the simplification of knights. It's possible to swap those moves (6.Nb3 and 7.Be2).} Bg7 8. O-O O-O {White has different setups to choose from.} 9. Bg5 {Active development, indirectly pressing against e7.} b6 {Once again, this move is our recommendation.} 10. Re1 (10. f4 $6 {This is usually the main plan in the Sicilian Dragon with Be2. In this case, it is not correct because Black has a strong reply.} b5 $1 {This is our recommendation, and, as we believe, a very promising idea.} (10... Bb7 {Not the best move at this moment, but the traditional way to play this type of position.} 11. Bf3 Na5 $1 {An excellent resource that gives Black a good game. Although we do not recommend the move 10... Bb7, this idea can be applied in different move-orders and transpositions. Below we show different variations to exemplify the richness of Black's game.} 12. Nxa5 $6 {While weakening his structure, this capture also enhances Black's piece activity.} (12. e5 Bxf3 13. Rxf3 (13. Qxf3 $2 dxe5 14. fxe5 Nxb3 15. axb3 Qd4+ $17 {[%csl Re5][%cal Gd4e5]}) 13... Nxb3 14. exf6 (14. axb3 dxe5 15. fxe5 ({This immediately leads to equality.} 15. Qxd8 Rfxd8 16. fxe5 Ng4 17. Bxe7 Nxe5 $11) 15... Qxd1+ 16. Rxd1 Ng4 17. Bxe7 Rfc8 ({Simpler is} 17... Nxe5 $11) 18. Bf6 Nxe5 19. Bxe5 Bxe5 20. Rd7 Rf8 21. g3 a6 {1/2-1/2 Miroslaw,M (2254)-Shishkin,V (2484)/Krakow POL 2006 (60)}) 14... exf6 15. Bxf6 Qxf6 16. axb3 Rfe8 17. Qd3 d5 $1 {A good positional move. Black activates his bishop and gets rid of his weakness.} 18. Nxd5 Qxb2 19. Rd1 Rac8 $13 {With chances for both sides.}) (12. Qe2 Qc8 $1 {A precise move, looking for activity on the diagonal a6-f1.} 13. Nxa5 bxa5 14. Rfe1 Re8 {It is necessary to defend the pawn on e7.} 15. e5 $2 (15. Rad1 $15) 15... Bxf3 16. Qxf3 dxe5 17. fxe5 Ng4 18. e6 Bd4+ $19) 12... bxa5 13. Kh1 Rb8 {[%cal Gb7a6]} 14. Qd2 Ba8 {[%cal Gb8b2]} 15. b3 Qc7 {[%cal Gc7c2,Gf8c8]} (15... a4 $5 16. e5 Bxf3 17. exf6 exf6 $1 $13) 16. Rae1 Rfc8 17. Re3 $13 (17. Nd5 Nxd5 18. exd5 Bc3 $19)) 11. Bxb5 {Other moves do not create any problems for Black.} Qb6+ 12. Kh1 Nxe4 $1 {The tactical justification of 10...b5!.} 13. Bxc6 Qxc6 14. Nxe4 (14. Na5 {leads to quick equality.} Nxc3 15. Nxc6 Nxd1 16. Nxe7+ Kh8 17. Raxd1 Bxb2 $11) 14... Qxe4 15. Re1 Qc6 16. Bxe7 Bb7 {A useful intermediate move.} 17. Re2 (17. Qd2 $2 Bxb2 $17) 17... Rfe8 $1 (17... Bxb2 $2 18. Rb1 $18) 18. Na5 Qc7 19. Nxb7 Qxb7 ({Another interesting option is} 19... Rxe7 $13) 20. Qxd6 Qxb2 $13 {The position is unclear, but Black's chances are at least equal.}) (10. Kh1 {White's aim is to play 11.f4, avoiding the line with b5 by Black.} Bb7 11. f4 Na5 $5 {Once again this idea offers the second player a dynamic game.} 12. Nxa5 (12. e5 $6 Ne4 $1 {An elegant rebuttal of White's last move. The structure of Black's pawns will look ugly, but his piece activity will guarantee him the advantage.} 13. Nxe4 Bxe4 14. exd6 Qxd6 15. Qxd6 exd6 16. Nxa5 bxa5 17. c3 Rab8 $19 {And the white pawns start to fall.}) 12... bxa5 13. Bf3 (13. e5 Ne4 $1 $132 {is similar to the variation with 12. e5?!.}) 13... Qb6 14. Rb1 $11 (14. e5 dxe5 15. fxe5 Rad8 $1 16. Qc1 Bxf3 17. exf6 exf6 18. Be3 Bxg2+ 19. Kxg2 Qb7+ 20. Kg1 f5 {Black has full compensation for the sacrificed piece due to the weakness of the white king.})) 10... h6 $5 ({Another way to get to a position similar to the mainline is} 10... Bb7 11. Kh1 (11. f4 b5 $1) 11... Rc8 12. f4 h6 13. Bh4 e5 $1 {This dynamic central blow, typical of Sicilian defences, offers Black a very interesting follow-up idea.} 14. Bg4 exf4 $1 {This exchange sacrifice favours Black.} 15. Bxc8 Bxc8 16. Nd4 (16. Nd5 $2 g5 17. Bf2 Ng4 18. Bg1 Bxb2 $19) 16... Nxd4 17. Qxd4 g5 18. Bf2 Ng4 19. Qd2 Nxf2+ 20. Qxf2 Be5 $17 {The bishop pair and the group of pawns on the kingside constitute an advantage for Black.}) 11. Bh4 Bb7 (11... g5 $2 {We believe that this move is not desirable, as it weakens the kingside too much.} 12. Bg3 Bb7 13. Qd2 Ne5 14. Qe3 Nfg4 15. Bxg4 Nxg4 16. Qe2 Ne5 17. Rad1 e6 $2 {has been played:} (17... Rc8 18. Nd4 e6 $14 {[%csl Rd6][%cal Gd4b5,Gb5d6,Gd1d6] White enjoys a slight advantage and will try to exploit the weakness on d6.} (18... Nc4 $5 19. Nf5 Nxb2 20. Nd5 $13 {The position is very complex.})) 18. Nb5 Ba6 19. c4 Qe7 20. N3d4 Rac8 21. b3 Rfd8 22. a4 $18 {With a positional advantage. 1-0 Rublevsky,S (2699)-Gashimov, V (2717)/Poikovsky 2008}) 12. f4 ({A more cautious treatment of the position does not pose Black problems, either.} 12. Bf1 Rc8 13. Qd2 (13. f4 e5 $1 {We see this dynamic central advance again in this line.} 14. fxe5 (14. f5 g5 15. Bf2 Ne7 $132 {[%cal Gd6d5,Ge7d5,Gf6d5,Gb7d5]}) 14... Nxe5 $17 {[%csl Re4][%cal Gf8e8,Ge8e4,Gb7e4,Gf6e4] Black's position is great. The backward pawn on d6 is amply compensated by the activity of the black pieces. The e4 pawn is going to be a target.}) 13... Na5 14. Bxf6 (14. Nxa5 $6 bxa5 15. Nd5 Nxd5 16. exd5 g5 17. Bg3 Bxb2 $17) 14... Bxf6 15. Qxh6 {Too optimistic.} Nc4 16. Bxc4 Rxc4 17. Rad1 Bg7 18. Qg5 (18. Qd2 Qc8 $17) 18... Bxc3 $1 {Good transformation of advantages.} 19. bxc3 e5 $1 {[%csl Rb3]} 20. Qd2 Rxe4 21. Rxe4 Bxe4 22. f3 Bf5 23. Qxd6 Qxd6 24. Rxd6 Rc8 $17 {1/2-1/2 (26) Volokitin,A (2545)-Hansen,C (2625)/Esbjerg 2002}) (12. Nd5 $2 {does not work due to the simple} Nxe4 $1) (12. a4 $5 {This is an interesting positional attempt to gain some advantage.} Na5 $1 {Black repeatedly clings to this resource.} 13. Nxa5 (13. Bf1 Rc8 14. e5 dxe5 15. Nxa5 bxa5 16. Qxd8 Rfxd8 17. Rxe5 Nd5 $11) 13... bxa5 14. Bf1 Qb6 $11) 12... e5 $1 {The thematic central push is very strong here.} 13. fxe5 (13. f5 {This move causes no inconveniences for Black.} g5 14. Bf2 Ne7 {[%csl Re4,Rf5][%cal Ge7d5,Gb7e4,Gf6e4,Ge7f5]} 15. Bf3 {Our suggestion is} Re8 $1 {[%csl Re5][%cal Ge8e5]} (15... d5 {has been played:} 16. exd5 Nfxd5 17. Nxd5 Bxd5 18. c4 Bxc4 19. Bxa8 Qxa8 20. Qd7 $2 ({Better is} 20. Rc1 $1 Rd8 21. Qh5 Bd3 $44 {, with satisfactory compensation for the exchange.}) 20... Nd5 21. g3 Nf6 22. Qa4 Bd5 $19 {0-1 Bouaziz,S (2341)-Romero Holmes,A (2514)/ Mallorca 2004/CBM 104 (61)}) 16. a4 d5 17. exd5 Nxf5 {With a complex game where Black has good chances.}) 13... Nxe5 $1 {[%csl Re4,Ge5][%cal Gb7e4,Gf6e4]} 14. Bf1 a6 $1 {[%csl Rd6][%cal Rc3b5,Rb5d6] Avoiding counterplay with Nb5. Black's position is much easier to play.} 15. Qd2 b5 16. Rad1 Nc4 $15 17. Bxc4 bxc4 18. e5 dxe5 19. Qxd8 Raxd8 20. Rxd8 Rxd8 21. Na5 Ba8 $132 {The bishop pair offers good prospects for the second player. 0-1 Kosintseva,N (2546)-Hou, Y (2578)/Mardin 2011} *

