1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 g6 3. d4 Bg7 4. Nc3 cxd4 5. Nxd4 Nc6 6. Nb3 Nf6 7. Be2 O-O 8. O-O d6 9. Re1 {White chooses a very calm setup. The aim is to play Nd5 and, after Black's capture (which we will avoid), exploit the weakness of the black pawn on e7. At no time does White aspire to play the advance f4, always looking for solidity.} b6 {Our usual choice.} 10. Bf1 ({It is possible to play} 10. Nd5 {immediately. Black has different options of equal value. We put emphasis on not capturing the knight on d5 because it is the kind of position White likes.} Bb7 (10... e6 $5) 11. Bg5 (11. Nxf6+ {has been played in practice.} Bxf6 12. c3 Bg7 13. Bf1 Rc8 14. Bg5 Re8 15. Qd2 Qd7 16. a4 Ne5 {With a dynamically balanced position. 0-1 (25) Zagrebelny,S (2490)-Tolnai, T  (2500)/Budapest 1993}) 11... e6 $1 {Our recommendation is the immediate expulsion of the knight from d5. While it is not forced, it leads to even play without any difficulties.} 12. Nxf6+ Bxf6 13. Bxf6 Qxf6 {[%csl Rb2][%cal Gf6b2]} 14. c3 Rfd8 15. Qc1 (15. Qd2 d5 $1 $15) 15... d5 $1 $11 {With a balanced game.}) 10... Bb7 11. Nd5 e6 $5 {We recommend this continuation again. After this move, White has a hard time coming up with a plan, while Black gets a typical flexible Sicilian centre. He can later opt for a d6/e5 Najdorf structure or open the position with d6-d5.} (11... Nd7 {This is the standard continuation in this line, leading to more complex positions.}) 12. Nxf6+ Bxf6 13. c3 Qc7 {Black adopts a classical way of development.} (13... Qe7 {has been played:} 14. a4 (14. Nd4 Nxd4 15. cxd4 Rfc8 $132) 14... Rfd8 15. f4 Qc7 (15... e5 $6 16. f5 $1) 16. Be3 Na5 $1 {This resource was already seen in the previous chapter.} 17. Nxa5 bxa5 18. Bf2 e5 $1 {Excellent central counterattack. Black ensures activity for his pieces.} 19. Qc1 (19. f5 d5 $1 $15) 19... exf4 20. Qxf4 Be5 21. Qh6 Bc8 22. Rad1 Be6 23. Rd2 $15 {1/2-1/2 Adams,M (2685)-Lalic,B (2565)/Hastings 1996/CBM 57 (26)}) 14. Bf4 $6 {This natural development only helps Black's interests.} ({White can't find a clear game plan. Some possibilities are:} 14. Qg4 e5 $1 $11 {Winning central squares and looking for a fast d6-d5.} 15. Bh6 (15. Be3 Ne7 16. Rad1 Bg7 17. Qh4 d5 $15) 15... Bg7 16. Bg5 Nd8 $1 {An unusual but very interesting regrouping. The knight will be perfectly located on the e6-square. At the same time, Black keeps his eyes open for two central breaks: d5 and f5.} 17. Rad1 Ne6 $1 {[%csl Ge6][%cal Ge6g5,Ge6f4,Ge6d4,Ge6c5]} 18. Be3 f5 $15 {Black has a very promising and dynamic position.}) (14. Nd4 $5 Nxd4 15. cxd4 Rfc8 {The position is close to equality, but it is uncomfortable for White.} 16. g3 b5 $1 {Gaining space on the queenside and preparing Qb6.} ({Too hasty is} 16... Qc2 $2 17. Qxc2 Rxc2 18. Bd3 Rc7 19. Be3 $11 {, and White completes his development.}) 17. Bf4 (17. Bxb5 $2 Qb6 $15 {[%csl Rd4,Rf2][%cal Gf6d4,Gd4f2,Gd4b2,Gb6d4]}) 17... Qb6 18. d5 exd5 19. exd5 Qc5 {Black has an excellent position.}) ({Perhaps the best option for White is to settle for equality after} 14. Bh6 Rfd8 15. Qf3 Qe7 $11) (14. c4 $2 {The attempt to transform the central structure is refuted with} Rfd8 $1 {Protecting the d6-pawn avoids Bf4 with tempo.} (14... a5 15. Bf4 Be5 $13) 15. Qe2 (15. Rb1 Ne5 $1 $17) (15. Bf4 Bxb2 $17) 15... a5 $1 $17 {[%csl Rb2,Rc4][%cal Ga5a3] With a great initiative on the queenside.}) 14... e5 $1 15. Be3 Ne7 $1 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Gd6d5]} 16. f3 ({To a more complex game leads} 16. c4 $5 Bxe4 17. Bh6 Bb7 18. Bxf8 Rxf8 $44 {, with good compensation for the sacrificed exchange.}) 16... d5 $1 $132 {And Black has solves his opening problems.} *

