1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 g6 4. d4 cxd4 5. Nxd4 Bg7 6. Be3 Nf6 7. Be2 O-O 8. f4 {Setting up the traditional Be2 and f4 scheme.} d6 9. Nb3 {Due to his slight space advantage, it makes sense for White to avoid simplifications on d4.} b6 {Again we recommend this move, preparing the queenside fianchetto and restricting White's knight on b3.} 10. O-O Bb7 11. Bf3 Nd7 ({A main alternative is} 11... Rc8 $5 12. Rf2 $5 {[%cal Gf2d2,Gc3d5] With the intention of immobilizing Black after Rfd2 and Nd5. Our recommendation is the very promising} (12. Qe2 {A typical choice by White.} Qc7 13. Rfd1 ({Too hasty is} 13. Nd5 {The following forced line favours the second player.} Nxd5 14. exd5 Nb4 {[%cal Gb4c2,Gb4d5]} 15. Qd2 Nxc2 16. Rac1 Bxb2 17. Be4 Bxc1 18. Rxc1 Qc4 19. Bxc2 Qxd5 $19) 13... Qb8 {A useful move, anticipating Nd5, clearing the c-file and creating the possibility of further improving the queen via the a8-square.} 14. Kh1 (14. Nd5 Nd7 $1 {[%cal Ge7e6] We have already seen this typical manoeuvre in previous chapters. By avoiding the exchange of knights, Black plans a well-timed e7-e6.} ({An error is} 14... Nxd5 $2 15. exd5 {[%csl Re7] , generating a weakness on e7.} Na5 16. Bd4 {With a comfortable advantage for White.})) 14... Rfe8 $1 {The rook is well placed on the e8-square. It fulfils two functions: over-defending e7 and enabling a central counterattack e7-e5.} 15. Qd2 (15. Nd5 Nd7 $1) 15... Qa8 $1 {Generating a lot of pressure on the long diagonal.} 16. Nd5 Nb8 $5 {[%cal Gb8d7]} 17. c3 Nbd7 18. Rf1 e6 $1 $15 {His central pressure offers Black the preferable position. 1/2-1/2 Atabayev,M (2485)-Al Modiahki,M (2550)/Baku AZE 2016}) 12... e5 $1 (12... Nb8 $5 {[%cal Gb8d7,Gc8c3] has been played in practice.} 13. Qd3 $5 (13. Rd2 $2 Rxc3 $1 ({Another interesting option is} 13... Nbd7 $5 14. e5 Bxf3 15. gxf3 Nh5 16. exd6 Bxc3 $1 17. bxc3 Rxc3 $19) 14. bxc3 Bxe4 $17) 13... Nfd7 $146 {In our opinion the way forward.} (13... Nbd7 $2 14. e5 $18) (13... Ba6 $6 14. Qd2 Nbd7 15. Rd1 Qc7 16. g4 $1 Nc5 17. Nxc5 bxc5 18. g5 Ne8 19. Nd5 Qd8 20. f5 $16 {1-0 Galkin, A (2430)-Gorelov,S (2490)/Moscow 1995}) 14. Rd1 (14. Bd4 $2 e5 $1 $15) (14. Nd4 $6 a6 $1 15. Rd1 e5 $1 $132 {With good counterplay for the second player.}) 14... Bxc3 $5 {A drastic but typical transformation of the position.} 15. bxc3 Qc7 16. Bd2 Nf6 17. g4 $2 (17. Re1 $13 {With a fighting game.}) 17... d5 $1 {A thematic central rupture before White can advance his kingside pawns.} 18. exd5 (18. e5 Ne4 $132) 18... Rfd8 $17) 13. Nb5 (13. Rd2 Qe7 $1 14. Rxd6 exf4 15. Bxf4 Rfe8 {And Black has excellent counterplay.}) 13... Ne8 $1 14. f5 {Trying to keep Black's counterplay under control, but this will not be succesful.} (14. c4 $2 exf4 15. Bxf4 Ne5 $17) 14... a6 15. Nc3 Ne7 {[%cal Ge7d5,Ge7f5,Gd6d5]} 16. Rd2 b5 17. Qe2 d5 $1 $15 {After this central push the initiative belongs to the second player.}) ({Another dynamic way of playing, worthy of being investigated in depth, is} 11... Na5 $5 12. Nxa5 bxa5 13. e5 Bxf3 14. Qxf3 dxe5 15. fxe5 Nd7 16. e6 fxe6 17. Qe4 Rxf1+ 18. Rxf1 Nf8 $11) 12. Qe1 (12. Nd4 $6 {This is an imprecision, allowing a standard punishment by Black.} Nxd4 $1 ({In practice} 12... Nc5 {has been played.} 13. Nxc6 $6 ({It was better to move back the knight:} 13. Nb3) 13... Bxc6 14. Bd4 e5 $1 15. Bxc5 (15. fxe5 Ne6 $1 16. Be3 Bxe5 $15 {And Black is in a comfortable position.}) 15... bxc5 16. f5 Rb8 17. Rb1 Rb4 $1 $17 {0-1 Mukhutdinov,T (2376)-Lomasov,S (2530)/Moscow RUS 2018}) 13. Bxd4 e5 $1 14. fxe5 (14. Be3 exf4 15. Bxf4 Ne5 $1 $17) 14... Nxe5 15. Nd5 Bxd5 16. exd5 Qh4 $15 {Reaching an ideal Sicilian position for Black. The disadvantage on the dark squares, coupled with a clumsy bishop on f3, offer White long-lasting passivity.}) 12... Rc8 13. Rd1 Na5 $5 {Again, one of the typical ideas of playing with b6 and Bb7. We think this is superior to the knight jump to b4.} (13... Nb4 $6 14. Rf2 $1 Qc7 15. Nd4 Qb8 16. Rfd2 $1 {White controls the position while Black does not find a clear plan for counterplay.} ({The normal} 16. Nd5 $2 {throws the advantage overboard after} Bxd5 $1 17. exd5 Bxd4 $1 18. Bxd4 Nxc2 19. Qxe7 Nxd4 20. Rxd4 Qc7 $17 {Reaching a position similar to those studied in the database on the Marozcy setup. The knight is a superior piece compared to the bishop and this guarantees Black an advantage. 1/2-1/2 Rodriguez Vila,A (2444)-Delgado Ramirez, N (2604)/Florianopolis BRA 2015})) 14. Nxa5 bxa5 15. Bxa7 Qc7 16. Bd4 (16. Be3 Bxc3 17. bxc3 Qxc3 $13 {With a complex game.}) 16... Bxd4+ 17. Rxd4 Qb6 18. Qe3 e5 $1 {Fixing the structure of the first player on the light squares.} 19. Rd3 ({Worse is} 19. fxe5 $2 dxe5 20. Rd3 Ba6 21. Nd5 Qe6 $17) 19... Qxe3+ 20. Rxe3 exf4 21. Ree1 Ne5 $13 {The position is complex, but it is clear that Black has very good fighting chances.} *

