1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 g6 4. d4 cxd4 5. Nxd4 Bg7 6. Be3 Nf6 7. Bc4 O-O 8. Bb3 Re8 $5 {A variation used by Vadim Zvjaginsev and recently popularized by Daniil Dubov.} 9. f3 (9. O-O d6 10. h3 Na5 11. Qd2 b6 {This position, with the small difference of the black rook on f8 and the white queen on d1, was played in several games between Anand and Kasparov.}) (9. Nxc6 {is an extremely peaceful move that does not seem very worrisome for Black.} dxc6 $8 10. Qxd8 Rxd8 {Black has no problems in this queenless middlegame.} 11. O-O (11. f3 b6 (11... Ne8 $5 12. Ke2 b6 13. Rad1 Ba6+ 14. Kf2 Nd6 15. a4 Nb7 16. Rxd8+ Rxd8 17. Rd1 Bxc3 18. Rxd8+ Nxd8 19. bxc3 Kf8 $11 {0-1 (24) Stets,D (2415)-Cornette,M  (2593)/ Rochefort FRA 2017 (92)}) 12. Kf2 Nd7 13. Rhd1 Ba6 14. Rd2 Ne5 15. Rxd8+ Rxd8 16. Rd1 Rxd1 17. Nxd1 Nc4 18. Bxc4 Bxc4 $11 {1/2-1/2 Petrov,M (2465) -Papp,G (2598)/Karlsruhe GER 2019 (44)}) 11... b6 12. h3 Ba6 13. Rfd1 Nd7 14. f4 Bxc3 15. bxc3 Nf6 $11 {1/2-1/2 Shevchenko,K (2373)-Zvjaginsev,V (2662)/ Minsk BLR 2015 (37)}) (9. f4 $5 {A very interesting alternative. The game exits the Yugoslav attack structures.} d6 10. Qf3 Bd7 {The main move is} (10... Qa5 $6 {This habitual move of the black queen is of doubtful value. The priority should be on finishing the development of the minor pieces.} 11. O-O Ng4 12. Nxc6 bxc6 13. Bd2 Qh5 14. h3 Qc5+ ({An error is} 14... Nf6 $2 15. g4 Qa5 16. e5 dxe5 17. fxe5 Qxe5 18. g5 $18) 15. Kh1 Nf6 16. Rae1 $16 {The first player is ready to start his attack on the rival king.}) 11. O-O (11. h3 $6 {The idea is to prepare long castling, but this is too slow and can be punished with} Nxe4 $1 12. Qxe4 (12. Nxc6 Bxc3+ $19) 12... Bxd4 $1 13. Bxd4 Bf5 14. Qe3 (14. Qd5 Be6 15. Qe4 Bf5 $11) 14... e5 $1 {Recovering the piece with good play.} 15. Bxe5 $8 (15. fxe5 $2 Qh4+ 16. Qf2 Qxd4 $15) 15... dxe5 16. O-O exf4 17. Qxf4 Qd4+ $1 $13) 11... Nxd4 12. Bxd4 Bc6 13. f5 $1 {The original idea behind 9. f4: Strong pressure is generated against f7. In response to this, Black has two main options.} Rf8 $6 {It seems contradictory that Black plays the rook to e8 and back. However, circumstances have changed and it is necessary now in order to continue with Nd7, seeking dominance of the central black squares.} (13... b5 $5 {The initiative developed by White on the kingside is ignored.} 14. Rad1 a5 15. Bd5 $1 {The precise move. White maintains the initiative and exerts constant pressure.} (15. Nd5 $6 {This imprecision offers Black counterplay.} a4 16. Nxf6+ Bxf6 17. fxg6 (17. Bd5 Bxd5 18. exd5 a3 19. b3 Rc8 $132 {[%csl Rc2][%cal Gc8c2] Black is going to have counterplay on the c-file.}) 17... hxg6 18. Bd5 (18. Bxf6 exf6 19. Bd5 Bxd5 20. Rxd5 Rc8 $11 {Black is very active and this compensates for his weaker structure. The position can be evaluated as dynamically equal.}) 18... Bxd5 19. exd5 Rc8 20. c3 Kg7 $13 {The position is unclear, with similar chances for both players.}) 15... Bxd5 16. Nxd5 Nxd5 17. exd5 Bf6 $1 {Probably the best practical chance.} (17... Rf8 18. Bxg7 Kxg7 19. Rde1 $16 {Blacks position is very passive.}) 18. c3 $1 {Unlike in the variation 15.Nd5, here Black is not going to have counterplay on the c-file.} Rc8 (18... b4 19. c4 $16) 19. Qe3 Rc4 $5 20. b3 Rxd4 21. cxd4 g5 $14 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gd8b6,Gg8g7,Gh7h6] White is better, but Black's position is solid, with possibilities of counterplay.}) 14. Rad1 Nd7 {The precise continuation is} 15. Be3 $1 (15. Kh1 $6 {This is not the best continuation, as it offers opportunities for the second player.} Bxd4 16. Rxd4 Kg7 $1 {Taking control over the dark squares.} 17. Qg3 (17. Qe3 {[%cal Ge3h6] Taking an interest in the h6-square, with the intention of a direct attack on the black king.} Qb6 18. Qd2 Rac8 (18... Nf6 19. Nd5 Bxd5 20. exd5 $16 {[%csl Re7,Rh6][%cal Gd4h4,Gd2h6,Gc2c3] White has his hands free due to Black's passivity.}) 19. Rf3 Qa5 {[%cal Ga5d2,Ga5e5]} 20. Rh3 Nf6 21. Qh6+ Kh8 22. fxg6 fxg6 {And Black holds off the onslaught.} 23. Rd1 $13 (23. Qxg6 $4 Nh5 $1 $19 {[%cal Gf8f1]})) 17... Qb6 18. Rd2 Nf6 $1 {Black takes control of the position and is ready for his counterplay.} 19. e5 $2 (19. Re1 $13 {With chances for both sides.}) 19... dxe5 20. fxg6 hxg6 21. Qxe5 Rad8 $1 {This tactical trick gives Black the advantage.} 22. Rdf2 ({The pawn is untouchable.} 22. Qxe7 Rxd2 23. Qxf6+ Kh7 $19 {[%cal Gc6g2]}) 22... Rd7 23. Ne2 Qb5 24. Qc3 Qg5 $17 {Black is better. 1/2-1/2 Grischuk,A (2777)-Dubov,D (2699)/ chess24.com INT 2020}) (15. fxg6 $2 {throws away any possibility of getting an advantage:} Bxd4+ $1 16. Rxd4 hxg6 17. Qg3 (17. Bxf7+ $4 Kg7 $19 {[%cal Gd7e5]}) 17... Kg7 $11 {[%cal Gd7e5,Gf8h8,Gd8b6]}) 15... Ne5 (15... b5 $4 16. fxg6 hxg6 17. Bxf7+ $18) 16. Qh3 a5 17. a4 $16 {, and White has an excellent attacking position.}) 9... d5 (9... e6 $5 {[%cal Gd7d5,Ge8e3] With the idea of executing the central break d7-d5 in the next move. This is consistent with 8...Re8 and poses problems for White to solve. We believe that it is interesting to have this possibility within the repertoire, but "only" as a surprise weapon. The main variation is} 10. Qd2 $1 (10. f4 {is a direct refutation attempt by White. He seeks to follow up with e4-e5 and play against the backward pawn on d7. At this point the natural continuations for Black fail. Let's look at two examples. The way forward for Black is the surprising} Nd5 $5 (10... Qa5 $2 11. O-O d5 12. e5 Nd7 13. Ncb5 Nxd4 14. Nxd4 Nc5 15. c3 $16 {[%csl Ra5,Re8][%cal Gb3c2,Gh2h5] Reaching a bad version of the French defence for Black. 1-0 Karjakin,S (2783) -Nepomniachtchi,I (2751)/chess. com INT 2017 (59)}) (10... d5 11. e5 Nd7 (11... Ne4 12. Nxe4 dxe4 13. Nxc6 bxc6 14. Qxd8 Rxd8 15. Rd1 $18 {[%csl Re4] With an endgame that is practically winning for the first player.}) 12. Qf3 a6 13. h4 Na5 14. h5 $18 {And White begins much earlier than expected to complete his attack. 1-0 Supi,L (2561)-Shiroma,S (2204)/Catanduva 2018 (29)}) 11. exd5 {This capture is more incisive than the previous one.} (11. Nxd5 {This capture does not create any problems for Black.} exd5 12. Bxd5 Qb6 $1 $146 {This novelty is our improvement suggestion.} (12... Nb4 $2 {has been played:} 13. Bb3 $2 (13. Nb5 $1 $16 {guarantees an advantage.}) 13... Rxe4 14. Kf2 Rxe3 15. Kxe3 Qb6 16. c3 Nc6 17. Re1 Nxd4 (17... d6 $1 $13 {should have been played, with compensation for the sacrificed exchange.}) 18. cxd4 d5 19. Kf3 Bf5 $14 {0-1 Golubev,M (2461) -Jacobson,B (2491)/chess.com INT 2021 (41)}) 13. c3 Qxb2 14. Rc1 (14. O-O $2 Qxc3 $15) 14... Qxg2 $13 {Although the engines evaluate the position as a slight white advantage, in practice it is very difficult to play with the white pieces.}) 11... exd5 12. O-O $1 {The precise sequence, that puts Black in trouble.} (12. Kf2 $6 {A lukewarm move that allows the obvious sacrifice of the exchange.} Rxe3 13. Kxe3 Bxd4+ $1 (13... Nxd4 $2 {This is an error that has been seen in practice.} 14. Nxd5 Nf5+ 15. Kd2 Bxb2 16. Re1 d6 17. c3 Be6 18. Rb1 Ba3 19. g4 $18 {1/2-1/2 Azarov,S (2574)-Dragun,K (2594)/ Rockville 2018 (34)}) 14. Kd2 $1 ({The natural route of the white king, seeking refuge on his own flank, causes him problems.} 14. Kf3 $2 d6 $1 15. h3 $1 {Necessary to avoid falling into serious problems.} (15. Nxd5 $2 Qh4 $19) (15. Bxd5 $2 Qh4 $19) (15. g3 $2 Bh3 $19) 15... Be6 $1 16. g3 Qa5 17. Qd2 Bg7 $15 {With a much more pleasant game for the second player.}) 14... Bxc3+ 15. bxc3 d4 16. cxd4 Nxd4 17. c3 Nxb3+ 18. axb3 d5 $14 {The bad location of the white king provides compensation for the second player.}) 12... Rxe3 13. Ndb5 d4 14. Nd5 d6 $5 (14... Re6 $2 15. f5 $1 $16 {With a great initiative.}) 15. Nxe3 dxe3 16. c3 Qb6 17. Qe2 $16 {And White has an advantage.}) 10... d5 11. O-O-O $1 {, allowing the advance of the central black pawns with the idea of putting pressure on them later.} Nxd4 (11... dxe4 12. Nxc6 Qxd2+ 13. Rxd2 bxc6 14. Nxe4 Nxe4 15. fxe4 $16 {With an easier endgame for White.}) 12. Bxd4 e5 13. Bf2 d4 14. Ne2 $1 {[%csl Yd4][%cal Gc2c3] Preparing a central break with c2-c3.} a5 15. c3 $1 a4 {The rapid deployment of the black a-pawn does not cause problems for the white king.} 16. Bc2 Be6 17. Kb1 dxc3 18. Qxd8 Rexd8 19. Nxc3 Rdc8 20. a3 {[%csl Ra4][%cal Gc2a4,Gc3a4]} Bf8 {Black has some weaknesses and it is not clear if he can achieve equality.} 21. Bg3 $1 {Adding a new weakness to Black's position.} ({The imprecise} 21. Bh4 $6 {has been played:} Be7 ({The correct continuation is} 21... Nd7 $1 22. Bxa4 {[%cal Ga4d7]} Nb6 23. Bb5 Bxa3 24. Bf2 Bc5 25. Bxc5 Rxc5 26. Rd6 Nc4 $11) 22. Nd5 $5 (22. Rd3 $6 Bc4 23. Bxf6 Bxf6 24. Rd7 b5 $11 {1-0 Kadric,D (2577)-Yoo,C (2455)/chess.com INT 2021  (37)}) 22... Nxd5 (22... Bxd5 23. exd5 Nxd5 24. Rxd5 Bxh4 25. Rxe5 $14 {The game is likely to end peacefully, but White still has a small plus.}) 23. exd5 Bxh4 24. dxe6 fxe6 25. g3 Bf6 26. Be4 $14 {And Black does not reach equality.}) 21... Nd7 (21... Bxa3 22. bxa3 Rxc3 23. Bxe5 $18) 22. Bxa4 Nb6 23. Bb5 Bxa3 24. Bxe5 $13 {The position is very complex, but White should keep his pawn advantage.}) 10. exd5 Nb4 11. Nde2 e6 {This is Black's idea.} 12. Qd2 (12. d6 Nbd5 (12... Nfd5 $2 {The wrong knight.} 13. Bd4 $1 Qxd6 14. Bxg7 Kxg7 15. Qd4+ $1 {A precise check by White, aiming to weaken Black's strong point on d5.} (15. Ne4 $2 Qb6 16. c3 $4 Nc6 17. N2g3 f5 $19 {0-1 Nigmatov,O (2447) -Paravyan,D (2653)/ chess.com INT 2020}) 15... e5 (15... Kg8 16. O-O-O $18) 16. Qd2 Be6 17. Nxd5 Nxd5 18. c4 $18) 13. Bd4 Qxd6 14. Bxd5 (14. O-O {This insipid continuation offers Black a comfortable game.} Nxc3 15. Bxc3 Qc7 16. Kh1 a6 17. Ng3 h5 $15 {0-1 Rasulov,V (2478)-Jojua,D (2557)/lichess.org INT 2021}) 14... exd5 15. Qd2 b5 {Fighting for the initiative!} 16. Nxb5 Qe7 {[%csl Re2][%cal Ge7e2]} 17. Nbc3 Rb8 {[%cal Gb8b2]} 18. O-O-O Bf5 {Black is creating a very dynamic game.} 19. g4 $6 (19. Kb1 $1 {is White's best defence against Black's attack.}) 19... Qb4 $1 20. b3 Nxg4 $1 {A surprising sequence.} 21. fxg4 Rxe2 22. Nxe2 Qa3+ 23. Kb1 Rxb3+ 24. axb3 Qxb3+ 25. Ka1 Qa3+ 26. Kb1 {1/2-1/2. Caruana,F (2819)-Dubov, D (2700)/Paris 2019. A short but attractive game.}) (12. Bd4 $5 {A solid option for White that needs to be taken seriously.} exd5 13. Qd2 $1 (13. O-O $5 Be6 14. Bf2 d4 $1 {Black is always looking for activity for his pieces.} 15. Nxd4 Bxb3 16. Nxb3 Qxd1 17. Raxd1 Nxc2 18. Na5 b6 19. Nc4 {1/2-1/2 Kovalev,V (2650)-Gelfand,B (2695)/Poikovsky 2018}) 13... Nc6 14. O-O-O $1 {More incisive than short castling.} Nxd4 15. Nxd4 Bd7 16. g4 $1 {Aiming to open lines on the kingside.} Bc6 17. Kb1 Nd7 18. h4 Nc5 19. h5 a5 20. a4 Qb6 21. hxg6 hxg6 22. g5 $14 {White has a small plus. 1-0 Navara,D (2740) -Gelfand,B (2703)/Batumi 2018}) (12. dxe6 $2 {It makes no sense to accept the sacrificed pawn. There is a lot of compensation due to the lack of development on White's side.} Bxe6 13. Bf2 Bxb3 14. axb3 Nfd5 $13) 12... Nbxd5 13. O-O-O Bd7 14. Nxd5 exd5 (14... Nxd5 15. Bxd5 exd5 16. Bd4 Bxd4 17. Nxd4 $16 {The knight versus bad bishop fight offers White an advantage.}) 15. Nc3 a5 16. a4 $6 {Better alternatives that guaranteed a white advantage without many complications were} (16. Bd4 a4 17. Bxd5 $16) (16. a3 $5 b5 (16... a4 $2 17. Ba2 b5 18. Bd4 $18) 17. Nxd5 $16) 16... b5 17. Nxd5 bxa4 (17... Be6 18. Bb6 Qb8 $13) 18. Bb6 axb3 19. Bxd8 Raxd8 20. Nxf6+ Bxf6 $18 {White is winning, but the position is still very complicated.} 21. Rhe1 bxc2 22. Rxe8+ Rxe8 23. Re1 Rc8 24. g4 Be6 25. Qd6 (25. Qxa5 $18) 25... Kg7 26. h3 $4 (26. h4 $16) 26... Bb3 $19 27. g5 Bxg5+ 28. f4 Bf6 29. Qb6 a4 30. Re5 Rd8 {Aravindh,C VR. (2601)- Dubov, Daniil (2703)/ Aeroflot Open A 2019. Conclusion: The Re8 variation has interesting practical ideas, although it seems that White can always get good positions. Both after the positional options and the ones connected with a kingside attack, one has to closely follow the evolution of the line.} *

