{[%evp 0,42,28,39,50,41,53,13,16,15,67,80,49,50,57,39,40,7,43,45,47,49,48,48,47,35,78,24,25,23,9,7,11,15,15,7,10,16,29,12,29,0,0,0,0]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 g6 5. Nc3 Bg7 6. Be3 Nf6 7. Bc4 O-O 8. Bb3 a5 9. O-O d6 $5 ({Our proposal is the move} 9... Nxd4 {with the idea of ​avoiding 10.Ndb5. This order is studied in the next chapter.}) 10. f3 (10. Ndb5 $5 {We believe that this is an annoying continuation that does not allow the natural development of Black’s game. Black is now doomed to passivity.} b6 (10... Ng4 11. Bg5 $16) 11. f3 (11. Bd5 {This move does not cause serious inconvenience to the second player.} Bb7 12. Qd2 e6 13. Bxc6 Bxc6 14. f3 d5 15. Nd4 Rc8 16. Nxc6 Rxc6 17. Rad1 Qe7 (17... Qc8 $11 {Full equality is reached by leaving the pin on the d-file and pressing on c2.}) 18. exd5 Nxd5 19. Nxd5 exd5 20. c3 $14 {1/2-1/2 (22) Saric,I (2661)-Damaso,R (2451)/ Jerusalem ISR 2015 (66)}) (11. a4 {Blocking the queenside and fixing Black's vulnerable queenside structure.} Nd7 12. Re1 Nc5 13. Bc4 Bb7 14. Bf1 Na7 15. Bd4 Nxb5 16. Nxb5 Bxd4 17. Qxd4 $14 {White is in a more comfortable position. 1-0 (29) Frolyanov,D (2556)-Pigusov,E (2555)/Moscow 2019}) 11... Ba6 12. Qd2 $6 (12. a4 $14 {Fixing the queenside and achieving a slight stable advantage.}) 12... Ne5 ({Black should have taken advantage of the occasion with} 12... Bxb5 $1 13. Nxb5 a4 14. Bc4 Ne5 15. Be2 d5 $132 {and Black activates his pieces.}) 13. a4 Rc8 14. Rfd1 Nfd7 $16 {1-0 (22) Fedorov,A (2601)-Malakhov,V (2700)/Moscow 2004}) 10... Nxd4 11. Bxd4 Bd7 12. a4 {Black wanted to play ...a5-a4 himself.} Bc6 13. Nd5 ({It does not cause inconvenience either.} 13. Kh1 Nd7 14. Bxg7 Kxg7 15. f4 Qb6 16. Ra2 Qb4 17. Re1 e6 18. Ra1 Nc5 19. Na2 Qb6 20. Qd4+ Kg8 21. Rad1 {½-½ Short,N (2683) -Wojtkiewicz,A (2563)/Reykjavik 2000}) 13... Nd7 $1 (13... Bxd5 14. exd5 Nd7 15. Bxg7 Kxg7 16. Qd4+ Kg8 17. Rfe1 $14 {[%csl Re7][%cal Ge1e7] With a slight advantage for White due to the weakness of the e7-pawn.}) 14. Bxg7 Kxg7 {Black has a good position, control of the dark squares (c5, b6) and has no weaknesses to worry about.} 15. Qd4+ ({Less forced is} 15. Qd2 Nc5 16. Rfd1 Kg8 {The king will be pretty safe on g8.} 17. Qe3 {Black has a decent position. We shall take a look at two possible lines.} Bxd5 $5 (17... Rc8 $5 18. e5 $2 Bxd5 19. Bxd5 e6 $1 {Good intermediate move.} 20. Bc4 (20. Ba2 Qb6 21. Rxd6 Qxb2 $19) 20... Nd7 $1 ({It is also playable} 20... d5 21. Bb5 $11) 21. Rxd6 Rxc4 22. Rad1 Rc7 23. Qd2 (23. Qd4 $2 Qg5 $17) 23... Qc8 24. Rxd7 Rxd7 25. Qxd7 Qxc2 $15 {[%csl Re5,Rg1] And Black finds himself with a slightly better edgame.}) 18. exd5 (18. Bxd5 Qb6 $11 {With a good game.}) 18... Rb8 19. Re1 {[%csl Re7][%cal Ge3e7]} (19. Bc4 Nxa4 20. Rxa4 b5 21. Bxb5 Rxb5 22. b3 Qc7 $1 $11 {[%cal Gf8c8,Gc8b8] With a balanced position since both sides have weaknesses.}) 19... b5 $1 $132 {After this blow, the queenside opens. Black enjoys decent counterplay.} 20. Qxe7 (20. axb5 $6 Rxb5 21. Qxe7 Qb6 22. Kh1 Nxb3 23. cxb3 Rxb3 $17) 20... bxa4 21. Bxa4 Rxb2 $15 {The Black position is more comfortable.}) 15... e5 $1 16. Qd2 (16. Qf2 $5 Bxd5 (16... Nc5 $6 {In general, in this structure, the knight belongs to f6.} 17. Ne3 (17. Rfd1 $6 f5 18. Qe3 fxe4 19. fxe4 Qh4 20. Nc7 Rad8 21. Bd5 Qe7 $15) 17... Qc7 18. Rfd1 Rad8 $14) 17. Bxd5 Qc7 18. Rfd1 Rfc8 19. c3 Nf6 $11 {It does not seem that Black has problems in this position.}) 16... Nc5 17. Rfd1 Nxb3 18. cxb3 Bxd5 19. Qxd5 Qb6+ 20. Kh1 Rfd8 21. Rac1 Rac8 $11 {Conclusion: The move order with 9 ...d6 with the idea of ​​a quick ...Nxd4 transposing to 9 .... Nxd4 has advantages and disadvantages. The clearest disadvantage is that the 10.Ndb5 move is allowed where Black is slightly worse. The advantage is that after 10.f3, Black is fine and avoids the difficulties of the move orders with 9 ... Nxd4. Among the secondary lines against 5.Nc3, we consider this one to be the most reliable choice.} *

