1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 g6 5. Nc3 Bg7 6. Be3 Nf6 7. Bc4 O-O 8. Bb3 a5 $5 {This is the line that we recommend for Black. His idea is to play a5-a4, in some positions overloading the defence of the e4-pawn.} (8... Ng4 $2 {This thematic idea in the Sicilian Dragon is a mistake here and gives White an advantage.} 9. Qxg4 Nxd4 10. Qd1 {There are two main options for Black.} Nxb3 {By simplifying, Black seeks to even the game.} (10... Ne6 11. Qd2 d6 12. h4 $1 {The best move for White. Rather than settling for a slight advantage, the direct attack on the Black king squeezes everything the position has to offer.} Bd7 13. h5 ({More precise is} 13. Bh6 $1 Qa5 14. Bxg7 Kxg7 15. h5 $16 {With a white advantage and excellent attacking prospects.}) 13... Qa5 14. hxg6 hxg6 15. Nd5 ({Worth considering is the move-order} 15. O-O-O Rfc8 16. Nd5 Qxd2+ 17. Kxd2 Kf8 18. Rh7 Bxb2 19. c3 $18) 15... Qxd2+ 16. Kxd2 Rfe8 17. c3 b6 18. Rh4 Rac8 19. Rah1 Nc7 20. Bg5 ({White could have kept the advantage with} 20. Nxc7 $1 Rxc7 21. Bd4 Bxd4 (21... e5 22. Be3 $16) 22. cxd4 e6 23. f4 $16) 20... Nxd5 21. exd5 b5 22. Re1 f6 $6 (22... Bf6 23. Bxf6 exf6 24. Reh1 f5 $14) 23. Be3 a5 24. Bc2 g5 25. Rhh1 Kf7 26. Bb6 a4 27. Bd4 Rh8 28. Bd3 g4 {The engines do not dislike the black position, but among humans, the game is more comfortable for the first player. 1-0 Tiviakov,S (2520)-Apicella,M (2430)/ Clichy 1991}) 11. axb3 d6 {White has several ways to gain an advantage. The one seen in the game seems best to us.} 12. Bd4 b6 (12... Be6 $2 13. Bxg7 Kxg7 14. Qd4+ Kg8 15. Rxa7 $18 {Losing a pawn without compensation.}) 13. Bxg7 Kxg7 14. Qd4+ f6 15. h4 Be6 {Tiviakov, a great specialist of the Accelerated Dragon with Black, chooses a quiet path.} 16. Nd5 {It seems more promising to play with 16.0-0-0 and advancing the kingside pawns.} Qd7 17. O-O Rfc8 18. c3 Bxd5 19. exd5 Qb5 20. Rfe1 $18 {1-0 Tiviakov,S (2640) -Mantovani,R (2365)/Ischia 1998}) 9. O-O {This move-order avoids the lines with d5. Here Black has to decide whether to allow White to play Ndb5. Our main suggestion is 9....Nxd4, which will be analyzed in the following chapters.} (9. a4 $6 {An imprecision that the second player will take advantage of to equalize quickly.} Ng4 $1 10. Qxg4 Nxd4 11. Qh4 d6 12. Nd5 Re8 13. Rd1 Nxb3 14. Bb6 Qd7 15. cxb3 Ra6 16. Bd4 Qd8 17. O-O Be6 {0-1 (23) Almasi,Z (2676)-Kramnik, V (2807)/Monte Carlo 2003}) ({One move to be well prepared against is} 9. f3 $5 {White tries to switch to a classical Sicilian Dragon.} d5 $1 {The exact continuation.} ({A misconception is} 9... d6 $2 10. Qd2 {, leading to a Sicilian Dragon Yugoslav Attack where Black's a7-a5 only weakened his position.}) 10. exd5 $5 (10. Nxd5 $2 {A tactical error. Black now has a huge variety of resources.} Nxd5 11. exd5 (11. Bxd5 $2 Nxd4 12. Bxd4 Bxd4 13. Qxd4 e6 $19 {And Black is left with an extra piece.}) 11... Nxd4 12. Bxd4 e5 $1 {[%cal Ga5a4,Gd8h4]} 13. Bf2 (13. Be3 $2 a4 14. Bc4 Qh4+ $19) 13... a4 14. Bc4 Qc7 15. Bd3 a3 $1 {[%cal Ge5e4,Gg7a1]} 16. b3 e4 $1 17. Bxe4 Qc3+ 18. Ke2 Re8 19. Qd3 Rxe4+ $1 20. Qxe4 Bf5 $19) (10. Bxd5 $5 {The best choice, but Black has many ideas at his disposal.} Nxd5 {The proper capture.} (10... Nxd4 $2 {An ugly mistake that has been played in different games.} 11. Bxd4 a4 12. Qd3 $1 $146 {Avoiding tactical motifs for Black.} (12. Qd2 $2 e6 13. Bc4 Nxe4 $1 $13) 12... Qa5 13. O-O-O $1 a3 14. b3 e6 15. Bc4 $18 {Black is running out of counterplay.}) 11. Nxd5 (11. exd5 Nb4 12. Nde2 e6 $1 13. a3 $1 ({Capturing the pawn is not consistent with the spirit of the position.} 13. dxe6 $2 Bxe6 14. O-O Bc4 $1 $19) 13... Nxd5 14. Nxd5 exd5 15. Bd4 {Trying to achieve the static advantage of a centralized knight (d4) versus a bad bishop.} Bh6 $1 {Well played. It is essential for the second player to keep the bishop pair.} 16. O-O Re8 $1 17. Kh1 (17. Nc3 Qd6 $132 {[%cal Gh6f4]}) 17... Qh4 18. Bf2 Qc4 19. Nd4 Bd7 20. Re1 Rac8 21. c3 Rxe1+ 22. Qxe1 Re8 $132 {[%cal Gb7b4] 1/2-1/2 (27) Ponomariov,R (2723)-Tiviakov,S (2667)/ Wijk aan Zee 2007}) 11... f5 $1 {A typical central counter.} (11... Nxd4 $2 12. Bxd4 Bxd4 13. Qxd4 e6 14. Nf6+ $18) 12. Nxc6 $1 (12. O-O $4 Bxd4 13. Bxd4 Nxd4 14. Qxd4 e6 $17 {[%csl Gf6][%cal Gf8f6,Gd8f6]}) 12... bxc6 13. Nb6 Rb8 {Now it is White who fights for equality.} 14. Qxd8 (14. O-O fxe4 15. fxe4 Rxf1+ 16. Kxf1 (16. Qxf1 Rxb6 $17) 16... Ba6+ 17. Kg1 Bxb2 $15) 14... Rxd8 15. Nxc8 Rdxc8 16. Rb1 (16. exf5 Rxb2 17. fxg6 Rxc2 18. gxh7+ Kxh7 19. Rd1 Bc3+ 20. Kf1 Rxa2 $19 {[%csl Rf1,Rh1]}) 16... fxe4 $1 {Black fights for the advantage, despite his poor pawn structure, as he has strong piece dynamics.} 17. b3 (17. fxe4 Rb4 (17... Bxb2 18. Ke2 Be5 $11) 18. Ke2 Rxe4 $13) 17... exf3 18. gxf3 c5 $1 19. c4 {The c5-pawn is fixed on the dark squares, but as compensation Black has attacking targets.} a4 $1 20. Ke2 axb3 21. axb3 Be5 22. h4 Ra8 23. f4 Ra2+ 24. Kf3 Bd6 25. h5 Rf8 26. hxg6 hxg6 27. Ke4 Rf5 $11 {1/2-1/2 Pashikian,A  (2556) -Petrosian,T (2606)/Yerevan 2008}) 10... Nb4 11. Nde2 (11. Ndb5 a4 12. Nxa4 Nfxd5 $15) 11... a4 $1 {A necessary move to activate the pieces.} 12. Nxa4 Nfxd5 13. Bf2 Bf5 14. O-O b5 15. Nc5 Bxb2 16. Rb1 Nc3 17. Nxc3 (17. Qxd8 Nxe2+ 18. Kh1 Rfxd8 19. Rxb2 Nc3 $13) 17... Bxc3 18. Qe2 $13 {The position is extremely complex. Engines like White a little more. We believe that Black has good practical chances.}) 9... a4 $5 {This line does not finish with complete equality for Black, but it raises interesting practical problems.} 10. Nxa4 Nxe4 11. Nb5 {Black has two main lines to choose from.} d5 $5 {We believe that this idea offers the best chances of equality or counterplay.} ({The alternative leaves White with a space advantage and no counterplay from the second player.} 11... Ra6 $6 12. c4 $1 {Gaining space in the centre.} d6 13. Qe2 $1 Nf6 14. h3 Na5 15. Bc2 $1 Be6 16. b3 Nc6 17. Rac1 Qb8 18. Bb1 Nd7 19. Rfd1 {After this move, White has completed his development with a clear advantage. There are numerous examples from practice that support this evaluation.}) 12. Bb6 {The most incisive move and the only one with which White can hope to gain an advantage.} ({If White plays passively, Black manages to coordinate his pieces.} 12. c3 $6 e6 13. f3 Nd6 $1 14. Bb6 (14. Nxd6 Qxd6 15. Bc5 Qc7 $15 {The capture of the exchange only offers a good game for Black.}) 14... Qd7 15. Nxd6 Qxd6 16. Bc5 Qc7 17. Bxf8 Bxf8 18. c4 d4 $1 (18... dxc4 19. Bxc4 Bd6 20. h3 Nd4 21. Bd3 Bd7 22. Nc3 Qb6 23. Kh1 $13 {The weakness of the dark squares offers enough compensation. 1/2-1/2 Grandelius,N (2540) -Berg,E (2594)/Norway 2009}) 19. c5 (19. f4 Bd7 20. Kh1 Ne7 $19 {[%csl Ra4,Rb3][%cal Gd7c6,Ge7f5] With a large advantage for Black.}) 19... Bd7 20. Nb6 Rd8 21. Nxd7 Rxd7 22. Rc1 Bh6 $17 {Black's pieces are much better.}) ({Nor does} 12. Nb6 {offer an advantage.} Ra5 13. Bxd5 Rxb5 14. Bxe4 Rxb2 ({If the second player wants to keep the game complicated, the way forward is} 14... Qc7 $5 15. Nd5 Qe5 16. Bf3 Rxb2 $13) 15. Qxd8 Rxd8 16. Rad1 Rf8 $1 $11 ({A mistake is} 16... Rxd1 $2 17. Rxd1 Be6 18. Bxc6 bxc6 19. Rd8+ Bf8 20. h4 $16)) 12... Qd7 13. Nc7 $1 {This leads to an interesting and complex line, where White will maintain a certain initiative. Other options are:} (13. f3 $6 {A dubious attempt to expel the centralized knight. Black has a precise continuation that offers him better play.} Ne5 $1 (13... Nb4 $2 14. Qe2 Nd6 15. Nxd6 exd6 16. c3 $16 {1-0 Bologan,V (2658)-Bouchet,N (2320)/France 2007}) 14. Nbc3 (14. Nc7 Rxa4 15. Bxa4 Qxa4 16. fxe4 dxe4 {The exchange is fully compensated. White has serious coordination problems.} 17. Nd5 Be6 18. Nxe7+ Kh8 19. Bc5 Qb5 20. Nxg6+ hxg6 21. Bxf8 Bxf8 $19) (14. Qe2 {The position is highly complex, but the analysis favours Black.} Nc4 15. Nc7 Rxa4 16. Bxa4 Qd6 17. Nxd5 Nxb6 18. fxe4 Nxa4 $19) 14... Nxc3 15. Nxc3 e6 16. Bd4 Nc6 17. Bxg7 Kxg7 18. f4 Qd6 19. Qd2 Qc5+ 20. Kh1 Rd8 21. Rad1 b5 $17 {The position has been clarified. Black has better central control and better pieces. 0-1 Badmatsyrenov,O (2386)-Belozerov, A (2492)/Irkutsk 2009}) ({A move to take into serious consideration is} 13. Qe2 $1 {The lines are less forced but promising for White.} Ne5 14. Rad1 e6 15. Bd4 {After this move, Black faces some tactical problems.} Ra5 (15... Nc4 $2 {This erratic move has been tried in practice.} 16. Bxc4 Rxa4 17. Bb3 Ra6 18. c4 {[%csl Rd5,Re4][%cal Gd1d5,Gc4d5,Gb3d5]} Bxd4 19. Rxd4 Nc5 20. Nc3 Nxb3 21. axb3 Qc6 22. cxd5 $18 {1/2-1/2 Groszpeter,A (2521)-Seres,L (2461)/Hungary 2012}) ({Nor is} 15... Qc6 {enough to achieve a balanced game.} 16. Nb6 Ra6 17. Nxd5 $1 exd5 18. Bxe5 Bxe5 19. Bxd5 Qc5 20. Qxe4 Bxb2 21. c4 $16 {The position is far from being defined, but the first player has the better chances.}) 16. Nbc3 $1 (16. Nac3 $2 {The wrong knight!} Nxc3 17. Nxc3 Nc6 $11) 16... Nxc3 17. Bxc3 Qb5 18. Qe1 Nc6 19. Bxa5 Nxa5 20. Qe3 $16 {Although the black bishop on g7 is an excellent piece, the sacrificed exchange is not fully justified.}) 13... Rxa4 $1 (13... Rb8 $2 14. Nxd5 $18) 14. Bxa4 Bxb2 15. Qxd5 (15. Rb1 $2 Nc3 $19) 15... Bxa1 16. Qxe4 $1 {This is the critical moment of the line. It looks like Black has a good position, but it is difficult for him to coordinate his pieces.} (16. Rxa1 $2 Nc3 17. Qxd7 Bxd7 $11) 16... Bf6 $5 (16... Bb2 $5 17. c4 Qd6 (17... Qf5 18. Bxc6 bxc6 19. Qxe7 $16) 18. c5 Qe5 19. Bxc6 bxc6 20. Qxc6 Bf5 21. Qd5 Qf4 22. Qf3 $16 {1/2-1/2 Kosintseva,T (2557)-Muzychuk,A (2538)/ Rostov on Don 2011}) ({Much worse is} 16... Bg7 $6 17. Nd5 e6 18. Nb4 $16) 17. Nd5 Kg7 $1 18. Rd1 $1 (18. Re1 $6 Qd6 19. Nxf6 exf6 20. Bxc6 Bf5 21. Qd5 Qxc6 22. Qxc6 bxc6 23. c4 Ra8 $11 {[%cal Gf5e6,Ge6c4,Gc4a2] Eliminating one of the two white pawns on the queenside.}) (18. Nxf6 $5 exf6 19. Re1 Qd2 20. Qe3 Qxe3 21. Rxe3 Bd7 (21... Be6 22. Bxc6 bxc6 23. a4 $16) 22. Bb5 (22. Rd3 $2 Ra8 $1 23. Bb3 Be6 $11) 22... Rc8 $14 {The position is not easy to play with the black pieces. His counterplay should be directed at the white pawns on the queenside.}) 18... Qf5 19. Qe2 $1 (19. Qxf5 Bxf5 20. Nxf6 Kxf6 21. Bb3 Ra8 $11) 19... Qe5 (19... Be6 $2 20. Nxf6 exf6 21. Bxc6 bxc6 22. a4 $16) 20. Qxe5 Nxe5 21. Nxf6 exf6 22. Rd8 $1 (22. Bb5 $2 Be6 $1 23. a4 Rc8 $1 $132) 22... Rxd8 23. Bxd8 Nc6 24. Bb6 $14 {White has a slight but comfortable advantage and is the only one who can hope to achieve victory. Conclusion: The line we analyze in this chapter has interesting practical ideas for Black, who can expect a highly complex game with many tactical themes. But with precise play by the first player, no entirely satisfactory path is in sight for Black.} *

