1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 g6 5. Nc3 Bg7 6. Be3 Nf6 7. Bc4 O-O 8. Bb3 a5 9. O-O Nxd4 {An interesting option, with the idea to avoid the line with Ndb5, but as usual, this also has its downsides.} (9... d6 10. h3 (10. Ndb5 $1) 10... Nxd4 11. Bxd4 Bd7) 10. Bxd4 d6 11. Qe2 $1 {This move is the one that poses more problems for Black, with ideas similar to Re1 but leaving room for Rad1.} (11. h3 $6 {This idea is a bit slow and allows Black to get organized.} Bd7 {[%csl Ga4][%cal Ga5a4]} 12. a4 Bc6 {The critical moment of the line 10.h3!?. Different moves have been put into practice without great success.} 13. f4 {An aggressive attempt to get an advantage.} (13. Re1 $2 e5 $1 14. Be3 Nxe4 15. Nxe4 Bxe4 16. Qd2 Qc7 17. Rad1 Ra6 {The pawn may be compensated for, but White certainly did not get any advantage from the opening. 1/2-1/2 Vishnu,P (2462)-Vazquez Igarza,R (2577)/Cappelle-la-Grande FRA 2014 (50)}) (13. Qd3 Nd7 14. Bxg7 Kxg7 15. Qd4+ Kg8 16. Bc4 (16. Rad1 Qb6 17. Qd2 Nc5 $11) 16... Qb6 17. Qxb6 Nxb6 $11 {With a balanced endgame. 1/2-1/2 (31) Guliyev,N (2548)-Pigusov,E (2555)/Moscow RUS 2019 (49)}) 13... Nd7 $1 14. Bxg7 Kxg7 15. Qd4+ Kg8 {White has numerous moves, but none leads to an advantage.} 16. f5 $5 (16. Nd5 Bxd5 $1 ({A mistake is} 16... e5 $2 17. Qe3 exf4 18. Qxf4 Ne5 19. Nf6+ Kg7 20. Rf2 $16) 17. Bxd5 Qb6 $1 {Black is willing to sacrifice a pawn to get activity for his pieces.} 18. Qxb6 Nxb6 19. Bxb7 Ra7 $1 20. Bd5 Rc7 {[%cal Gf8b8,Gb6d5,Gc7c4]} 21. Bb3 Nc4 $13 {Black's chances are at least equal.}) (16. e5 dxe5 17. fxe5 e6 $15 {[%csl Re5] The e5-pawn has become nothing but a weakness.}) 16... Qb6 $1 {Again this exchange of queens is the way to go.} 17. Qxb6 Nxb6 18. f6 {More accurate is} e6 $1 (18... Rae8 19. Rad1 $14 (19. fxe7 Rxe7 20. Rf6 $14)) 19. Rad1 Rfd8 20. Rd2 Nd7 $1 21. Rxd6 Nc5 22. Rfd1 Rxd6 23. Rxd6 Bxe4 $15 {, and it is White who must play precisely to equalize.}) (11. a4 Bd7 12. Re1 Bc6 13. Nd5 $6 e6 (13... Nd7 14. Bxg7 Kxg7 $11) (13... Nxd5 $2 14. exd5 Bd7 15. Bxg7 Kxg7 16. Qd4+ f6 17. Re3 $18 {Reaching the kind of position that the second player must avoid. 1/2-1/2 Mamedov,R  (2703)-Markoja,B (2430)/Skopje MKD 2018 (73)}) 14. Nxf6+ Bxf6 15. Bxf6 Qxf6 16. c3 Qe5 $13 {With a lot of play left in the position, Black has reached an equal game.}) (11. Re1 $1 {This move seeks to refute the move order chosen by Black.} Bd7 12. a4 $1 {Once again, we must consider this useful move.} (12. Nd5 $6 {At this moment the second player lacks time to respond with Nd7, which is the natural reaction to Nd5. However, there is a good resource available. An interesting improvement idea is} a4 $1 (12... Nxd5 $2 {As we have seen throughout the entire database, this capture is usually not a good idea for Black, leading to a passive position.} 13. Bxg7 Kxg7 14. exd5 b5 15. a3 Kg8 16. Qd4 Re8 17. Re3 $16 {With a clear advantage for White. 1-0 Ganguly,S (2654) -Guseinov,G (2614)/ Bursa 2010}) 13. Bc4 (13. Nxf6+ Bxf6 14. Bxf6 axb3 15. Bc3 bxa2 $13) 13... Bc6 $1 14. b4 $1 {This surprising move is White's best option here.} (14. Nxf6+ $6 {This simplification relieves the second player of the pressure.} Bxf6 15. Bxf6 exf6 {The black structure is broken but offers dynamic compensation.} 16. Qd4 Re8 17. f3 (17. Rad1 f5 $1 18. exf5 Qg5 $1 $132) 17... Ra5 18. Rad1 Rae5 19. Qxd6 Qxd6 20. Rxd6 f5 $132 {With good counterplay.}) 14... axb3 15. cxb3 ({Against the other capture, Black also has resources.} 15. axb3 Rxa1 16. Qxa1 Re8 $1 {[%cal Ge8e4]} 17. b4 Qd7 18. Bb3 e5 19. Nxf6+ Bxf6 20. Bb2 Bg5 $13) 15... e6 $1 16. Nxf6+ Bxf6 17. a4 (17. Bxf6 Qxf6 18. Qxd6 Bxe4 $11) 17... Be5 $1 18. Bxe5 ({Neither does the first player manage to unbalance the game after} 18. Qd2 Qf6 19. Rad1 Bxd4 20. Qxd4 Qxd4 21. Rxd4 Rfd8 22. Red1 Kf8 23. Rxd6 Rxd6 24. Rxd6 Bxe4 $11) 18... dxe5 19. Qxd8 Rfxd8 20. f3 Kf8 $11 {[%cal Gd8d4,Gf8e7,Gf7f5] White has a majority of pawns on the queenside. The second player relies on Ke7-Rd4-f5, with enough counterplay for the endgame to be even.}) 12... Bc6 13. Qd2 Nd7 14. Bxg7 Kxg7 15. Rad1 Rc8 $14 {White's position is more comfortable and he has saved the h3-move compared to some other lines. Anyway, the black position is very solid, he just has to be careful not to fall into passivity.}) 11... Bd7 12. a4 $1 {We consider this to be the most annoying move-order for Black.} (12. Rad1 {This rook move allows Black to gain quick counterplay.} a4 $1 (12... Bc6 13. e5 dxe5 14. Bxe5 Qb6 $14) 13. Bc4 {A critical moment in this line. Our suggestion is} Qa5 $1 {, seeking to avoid White's ideas with b4.} ({The most popular move, that has been seen in many games, is} 13... Bc6 $6 {But Black faces a serious problem after the response suggested by Stockfish 14:} 14. b4 $1 $146 {With the idea of preventing Black from playing Nd7.} axb3 15. cxb3 $1 Qa5 16. Nd5 Bxd5 17. exd5 Rfc8 18. a4 $1 $16 {With an excellent game for White.}) 14. a3 (14. Nd5 Nxd5 15. exd5 Rfe8 16. Bxg7 Kxg7 17. a3 b5 18. Ba2 b4 $17 {And Black is in time.}) 14... Rac8 $1 (14... Bc6 $2 15. Nd5 $16 {[%cal Gd5e7,Gd5f6]}) 15. Nd5 Nxd5 16. exd5 Rfe8 {[%cal Gb7b5,Gb5b4] Black, despite having to capture on d5, has no problems.} 17. c3 Rxc4 18. Qxc4 Bb5 19. Qb4 Qxb4 20. axb4 Bxf1 21. Kxf1 Rc8 $11 {With a balanced endgame.}) 12... Bc6 13. Rad1 (13. Nd5 Nxd5 14. Bxg7 Nf4 $1 $11) 13... Nd7 14. Rfe1 Rc8 $1 (14... Bxd4 $6 {This imprecision leaves the white pieces better prepared for the knight jump to d5.} 15. Rxd4 Nc5 $1 (15... Qb6 16. Qd2 Nf6 17. Nd5 Bxd5 18. exd5 Rac8 19. Rh4 $16 {With a promising game for the first player.} (19. Rxe7 $2 Rfe8 20. Rxe8+ Rxe8 21. h3 Re5 $44 {In exchange for the pawn, Black has good control of the dark squares.})) 16. Qd2 (16. e5 $2 Nxb3 17. cxb3 Qb6 $13) 16... Nxb3 17. cxb3 Qb6 18. Re3 {[%cal Ge3h3,Gd2h6]} Rac8 (18... Qxb3 $2 {Capturing this pawn does not seem like a good idea.} 19. Nd5 Qa2 20. Nxe7+ Kg7 21. Rxd6 $18) 19. h4 (19. Nd5 $2 Bxd5 20. Rxd5 (20. exd5 Qxd4 $19) 20... Rc5 $11) (19. Rh3 $6 f5 $1 $15 {And Black activates his pieces.}) 19... Qc5 20. Nd5 Bxd5 21. Rc3 Qb6 22. Rxd5 $14 {And White keeps pressing.}) 15. Bxg7 (15. Qe3 $2 e5 $1 {A good decision for tactical reasons.} 16. Ba7 Qc7 $13) 15... Kxg7 16. Rd4 $5 {White's plan is to continue with Qd2 and Nd5. If Black captures the knight, after Bxc6 exd5, the first player is ready to move the rook from d4 to the kingside. This is the point of his last move.} Nc5 (16... Qb6 17. Qd2 Nf6 18. Nd5 Bxd5 19. exd5 $16 {[%cal Gd4h4,Ge1e3,Gd2h6]}) 17. Qd2 ({Premature is} 17. Nd5 $2 e5 $1 18. Rd2 Nxa4 $15) (17. e5 $6 Nxb3 18. cxb3 Qb6 19. Rh4 (19. Rdd1 Qxb3 $15) {Now Black must play the cold-blooded.} 19... Qxb3 (19... dxe5 $4 {A serious mistake that loses by force.} 20. Qxe5+ Kg8 (20... f6 21. Qxe7+ Rf7 22. Rxh7+ $18) 21. Qf4 $1 h5 22. Rxh5 $1 gxh5 23. Qg5+ Kh7 24. Qxh5+ Kg7 25. Qg4+ $1 Kh7 26. Re5 $1 $18) 20. Qe3 dxe5 $1 {A difficult move to make, but the most precise.} 21. Qxe5+ (21. Qh6+ Kf6 $13 {And White cannot progress with his attack.}) 21... f6 $1 22. Qxe7+ Rf7 {[%csl Rb2][%cal Gb3f7,Rh4h7,Gb3b2]} 23. Qa3 (23. Qe2 Re8 $19) 23... Qxa3 24. bxa3 Rd7 $1 $17) 17... Qb6 18. Re3 (18. Nd5 $6 {It is still not the right time for this manoeuvre.} Bxd5 19. exd5 Nxb3 20. cxb3 Rc2 $1 $11 21. Qxc2 $4 Qxd4 22. Rxe7 Rc8 $1 $19) 18... Nxb3 19. cxb3 f6 {The critical moment for the black position. Due to the f6-move, his pawn structure will remain a bit static, but his restricted situation forces this on him.} ({A mistake is} 19... Qxb3 $2 20. Rh3 $1 {The exact rebuttal to the capture on b3.} h5 21. Rxh5 Rh8 (21... gxh5 $2 22. Qg5+ Kh7 23. Qxh5+ Kg7 24. Qg5+ Kh7 25. e5 $18) 22. Rxa5 $16) 20. h3 (20. Rh3 h5 21. g4 $4 Qxb3 22. gxh5 Rh8 $1 $17) (20. Nd5 $2 Bxd5 21. Rxd5 (21. exd5 $2 Qxd4 $19) 21... Rc5 $11) 20... Rfe8 $1 {We consider this move better than 20...Rf7 because in some lines the black pieces are activated more quickly. The black position is restricted but very solid.} (20... Rf7 $6 21. Qd1 (21. Nd5 $6 Bxd5 22. exd5 Rc1+ 23. Kh2 Rc2 24. Qxc2 Qxd4 $11) 21... Bd7 22. Nd5 Qa7 23. Rc4 Rxc4 24. bxc4 Qc5 25. b3 $14 {Black is slightly worse but very solid.}) 21. Nd5 $5 Bxd5 22. exd5 Rc1+ $1 23. Kh2 Rc2 $11 *

