{[%evp 0,52,26,25,44,44,44,44,82,49,42,34,44,37,64,44,44,19,49,31,40,36,32,34,41,22,35,39,56,64,59,73,54,52,59,54,53,53,48,37,52,15,14,21,21,28,32,5,61,13,13,5,5,9,0]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. Nf3 g6 4. d4 cxd4 5. Nxd4 Bg7 6. Be3 Nf6 7. Bc4 O-O ({Entering into one of the main lines of the Accelerated Sicilian Dragon. We recommend} 7... Qa5 {in case you want to avoid the line in this chapter.}) 8. Bb3 $1 {This is necessary to avoid tactical tricks.} ({The variations where White does not play with precision are well known:} 8. f3 $6 Qb6 9. Bb3 Nxe4 $1 ({Imprecise is} 9... Ng4 $6 10. fxg4 Bxd4 11. Nd5 Qa5+ 12. Bd2 Qd8 13. c3 Bg7 14. g5 {The position is unclear.}) 10. Nd5 Qa5+ 11. c3 Nc5 12. Nxc6 dxc6 13. Nxe7+ Kh8 14. Nxc8 Raxc8 15. O-O {In practice,} Rcd8 {has been played.} ({Black can try to get more out of the position with} 15... Rfe8 $5 16. Bd4 (16. Bf2 $5) 16... Nxb3 17. axb3 Qb5 18. Rxa7 Rcd8 $17) 16. Qc2 Qb5 17. Bxc5 Qxc5+ 18. Qf2 $11 {1/2-1/2 Paulet,I (2327)-Miladinovic,I (2570)/ Cetinje 2009}) (8. h3 $6 Nxe4 9. Nxe4 d5 $17) 8... Qa5 ({The correct move-order to play this variation should be} 8... d6 {, threatening Ng4, and after} 9. f3 {play} ({After} 9. h3 {, instead of Qa5 it seems better to us to opt for} Na5 10. O-O b6) 9... Qa5) 9. f3 $1 {Although in this database we usually recommend secondary lines, in this chapter we will suggest a more theoretical one because we believe that Black's other options are not good.} d6 $1 ({If Black does not want to enter the line that we will analyze and avoid the mainlines of the Dragon, he can try the following one:} 9... d5 $6 10. exd5 Nb4 11. Qd2 $1 {This precise move forces Black to enter an endgame that is better for White.} Nbxd5 ({A serious mistake is} 11... Rd8 $2 12. O-O-O Nbxd5 13. Nxd5 Qxd2+ 14. Rxd2 Nxd5 15. Nb5 Be6 16. Rhd1 a6 17. Nc7 {1-0 Caspi,I  (2489)-Boskovic,D (2453) /chess.com INT 2020}) 12. Nxd5 Qxd2+ 13. Kxd2 $1 Nxd5 14. Bxd5 Rd8 {The idea behind Black's combination, but it is met with an unpleasant reply.} 15. c4 $1 {Refuting Black's idea. White forces an better endgame with an advantage in which Black has no counterplay.} e6 16. Be4 $1 Bxd4 (16... e5 $2 17. Bd5 exd4 18. Bg5 $16 {[%csl Rd4]}) 17. Bxd4 Rxd4+ 18. Kc3 Rd7 $1 {The most tenacious move in a bad position.} (18... Rd8 $2 19. Rhd1 $18) 19. Rhd1 Rb8 20. Rxd7 ({Another possibility is} 20. b4 f5 21. Bc2 e5 22. Ba4 Rxd1 23. Rxd1 Be6 24. Re1 Rc8 25. Bb3 $18 {1-0 Djukic,N (2536)-Kassebaum,R  (2311)/Portoroz SLO 2016 (25)}) 20... Bxd7 21. Rd1 Be8 22. f4 $1 {White begins to strengthen his position.} Kf8 23. b4 Ke7 24. b5 $1 {The correct way to advance the majority.} b6 25. a4 Rc8 {White easily increases his advantage:} 26. Kb4 $1 (26. Kb3 h6 (26... Rd8 $2 27. Rxd8 Kxd8 28. Kb4 Kc7 29. c5 f6 30. h4 e5 31. fxe5 fxe5 32. g4 $1 $18 {[%csl Gg5][%cal Gg4g5]}) 27. a5 $1 $16) 26... h6 27. Ra1 g5 28. g3 $1 $16 {[%cal Ga4a5]}) 10. Qd2 Nxd4 $5 (10... Bd7 {transposes to the mainline of the Sicilian Dragon (B79).}) 11. Bxd4 Be6 $1 {In coherence with the rest of the base, this move is once again our recommendation.} 12. O-O-O (12. Bxe6 $6 {The capture of the bishop does not promise White anything.} fxe6 13. O-O-O Rac8 14. Kb1 Nd7 $1 {[%cal Gd7e5,Ge5c4] This manoeuvre has already been seen.} 15. Bxg7 Kxg7 16. Ne2 Qxd2 17. Rxd2 e5 $1 18. Rd3 a6 $11 {1/2-1/2 Walek,M (2330) -Vesselovsky,S (2438)/Moravia 2003}) (12. h4 $6 {This usual attack against the Sicilian Dragon is not dangerous here.} Bxb3 $1 13. cxb3 Rac8 {Preventing White from long castling.} 14. a3 (14. O-O-O Qxa2 $17) 14... Rfd8 $1 {[%cal Gd6d5,Ge7e5]} 15. h5 {White must act quickly and energetically.} ({An example of Black realising his ideas is} 15. b4 Qa6 $1 16. O-O-O e5 $1 17. Be3 d5 $19) 15... e5 $1 (15... e6 $2 {There is no time to control central squares. Black is punished after} 16. h6 $1 (16. hxg6 $6 fxg6 17. b4 Qc7 18. O-O b6 19. Rac1 {1/2-1/2 Fakhrutdinov,T (2350) -Socko,M (2462)/Warsaw 2016}) 16... Bh8 17. b4 Qa6 18. Rd1 $16) 16. Be3 d5 17. b4 Qa6 18. Nxd5 Nxd5 19. exd5 e4 $1 $13 {[%csl Re1] With strong counterplay against White's king.}) ({After} 12. O-O Nd7 13. Bxg7 Kxg7 {[%cal Gd7f6] Black does not face any problems. He will proceed with ...Nf6 followed by ...Qc5, preparing the advance of the queenside pawns.}) 12... b5 $5 {This answer is our recommendation against the move-order chosen by White.} (12... Bxb3 $2 13. cxb3 $1 Rfc8 14. Kb1 $16 {With a solid white advantage. His attack is slow but steady, while Black lacks any real counterplay.}) 13. Kb1 b4 14. Nd5 ({White can try to complicate the game with} 14. Bxe6 $5 fxe6 15. Ne2 {Here the second player has two main options. Our suggestion for Black is} Qb5 $5 $146 {Another way to play is} (15... Rfc8 16. h4 Rc6 17. g4 $1 {We believe that this is a possible improvement for the white attack.} (17. h5 $6 {has been played in a recent game.} e5 18. Be3 Nxh5 19. g4 ({An alternative is} 19. Qd3 Rac8 (19... Qa6 20. Qxa6 Rxa6 21. c3 bxc3 22. Nxc3 {, and White has compensation for the pawn.}) 20. g4 Nf6 21. Qb3+ Rc4 22. g5 Nh5 23. Rd5 Qa6 $1 {, with an unclear game.} ({A mistake is} 23... Qc7 $2 24. Rc5 $16)) 19... Nf6 20. Bh6 (20. Qd3 Qa6 $1) 20... Rac8 $1 {A good continuation if Black is content with a draw. The following sequence is forced.} ({Black loses quickly after} 20... Rf8 $4 21. Bxg7 Kxg7 22. Qh6+ Kg8 23. g5 $18) ({To play for a win, Black must play} 20... Bf8 $1 {This slows down White's attack.} 21. Bxf8 Rxf8 22. Qh6 Rf7 $1 $17 {, and Black is better.}) 21. Bxg7 (21. c3 Ra6 $1 $19) 21... Rxc2 22. Qh6 b3 $1 23. axb3 (23. a3 $4 Rxb2+ 24. Kxb2 Rc2+ 25. Kxb3 Qc5 $19) 23... Rxe2 24. Bxf6 (24. Rc1 $4 Rxc1+ 25. Rxc1 Re1 $1 $19) 24... Rxb2+ $1 25. Kxb2 Qc3+ 26. Ka2 Qc2+ $11 {Tabatabaei, M 2624- Mchedlishvili, Mikheil 2571 4th Sharjah Masters 2021}) 17... Rac8 (17... e5 $6 18. Be3 Rac8 19. Qd3 $1 (19. Rc1 $2 Ra6 $132) 19... Rxc2 20. Rc1 Rxc1+ 21. Rxc1 Rxc1+ 22. Nxc1 $16 {The extra pawn has no influence whatsoever. White is better off due to his active pieces and Black's weaknesses on the queenside.}) 18. c3 Qa6 (18... e5 19. cxb4 $18) 19. h5 (19. e5 dxe5 20. Bxe5 Ne4 $1 $19) 19... e5 {Black is running out of dynamic options while White's attack advances.} 20. Be3 d5 $5 21. exd5 Rd6 22. cxb4 Rxd5 23. Qe1 $16) 16. Be3 {[%cal Ge2d4]} (16. h4 a5 17. h5 {Black has to make an important decision.} gxh5 $1 {The correct capture.} (17... Nxh5 $2 18. Bxg7 {A serious mistake is} Kxg7 $4 (18... Nxg7 {After the capture of the knight, White has the initiative, with chances of attacking Black's king.} 19. Nd4 Qe5 20. Nc6 (20. Qh6 Rac8 21. Qxh7+ Kf7 22. Qh4 $14) 20... Qf6 21. e5 dxe5 22. g4 Rac8 23. Qd7 $16) 19. g4 Nf6 20. Nd4 Qd7 21. Qh6+ Kg8 22. g5 Nh5 23. Rxh5 gxh5 24. g6 $18) 18. Be3 Kf7 $1 {This difficult king move manages to keep Black afloat. Its idea is to free the queen from the defence of the e6-pawn.} 19. Nd4 Qc4 20. g4 (20. b3 Qa6 $13 {[%cal Ga5a4]}) 20... hxg4 21. fxg4 a4 {The position is very complex. There are many possibilities, but we believe that Black manages to defend himself.} 22. g5 Ng4 $13) 16... a5 $1 17. Nd4 Qd7 18. h4 e5 19. Ne2 Qe6 $1 {[%csl Gc4][%cal Ge6c4] Controlling the c4-square.} (19... h5 $5 20. c4 $1 {White starts to play positionally on the queenside.} (20. g4 hxg4 $1 $13) 20... Qe6 21. Qd3 Nd7 22. Qd5 $14 {[%cal Gc4c5]}) 20. Qd3 (20. g4 h5 $1) 20... a4 21. c4 Rfc8 22. Rc1 h5 $1 $13 {[%cal Gf6d7,Gd7c5] Black is fine.}) 14... Bxd5 15. exd5 (15. Bxd5 {does not lead to anything.} Nxd5 16. Bxg7 Nc3+ 17. Bxc3 bxc3 18. Qxc3 Qxc3 19. bxc3 Rfc8 $11 {1/2-1/2 Drozdowski,K  (2475)-Gorovets,A (2532)/Brownsville USA 2016}) 15... Qb5 $1 {With the idea a7-a5-a4.} 16. Qd3 (16. Rhe1 a5 17. Qe2 Qxe2 18. Rxe2 {e2} a4 19. Bc4 Rfc8 20. b3 Rc7 $1 {This way, White is prevented from placing his bishop on c6.} (20... Kf8 21. Bb5 axb3 22. cxb3 Ra5 23. Bc6 Rb8 24. g4 $14 {The endgame is more pleasant for White. 0-1 Inarkiev,E (2663) -Zvjaginsev,V (2627)/Moscow 2019}) 21. Bb5 axb3 22. cxb3 Ra5 $13 {1/2-1/2 Yu,Y (2721) -Guseinov,G (2634)/Skopje 2015} 23. Bc4 ({An error is} 23. Bb6 $2 Rxb5 24. Bxc7 Nxd5 25. Rxd5 Rxd5 26. Rxe7 Be5 $17) 23... Rb7 $11 {Black has an acceptable ending. His plan is the exchange of the dark-squared bishops.}) (16. g4 a5 $1 17. g5 Nh5 18. Bxg7 Nxg7 19. Qd3 Qxd3 20. cxd3 a4 21. Bc4 Nf5 $1 {With a stable black advantage.}) 16... Qxd3 17. Rxd3 (17. cxd3 $2 {This creative idea of opening the c-file does not cause any problems for Black.} Nd7 $1 18. Bxg7 {g7} Kxg7 19. Rhe1 Kf6 20. Re4 a5 21. Rde1 Nc5 22. Rf4+ Kg7 23. Bc4 (23. Rxe7 Nxd3 $15) 23... Ra7 $15 {It is Black who has the better chances to make progress. 0-1 Pershin,D (2400) -Zvjaginsev,V (2642)/St Petersburg RUS 2018}) 17... Nd7 $1 18. Re1 (18. f4 Bxd4 $1 {This is an improvement over the next game.} (18... Nc5 $2 19. Bxc5 $1 {After this transformation, White enjoys a positional advantage.} dxc5 20. Re3 Bf6 21. g4 $1 g5 $8 22. fxg5 Bxg5 23. Re4 Rae8 24. h4 $1 Bf6 25. g5 $1 Bd4 26. Rhe1 $18 {Gaining material and expanding his advantage.} e6 27. dxe6 fxe6 28. Rxe6 Rxe6 29. Rxe6 Kg7 30. Re7+ Kg6 31. Bc4 a5 32. Bd3+ Kh5 33. Rxh7+ {Excellent model game from White.}) 19. Rxd4 a5 20. Ba4 (20. Re1 $6 Nc5 $1 {Good positional pawn sacrifice.} 21. Rxe7 Rfe8 22. Rxe8+ Rxe8 23. Rd1 Re2 {With a decisive advantage.}) 20... Nc5 21. Bc6 Ra7 $15) (18. Bxg7 $5 Kxg7 19. Re3 Kf6 {One of the keys to this variation is knowing how to hand over the e7-pawn, to avoid ending in a very passive position.} 20. Rhe1 a5 $1 {Again we see this very interesting positional pawn sacrifice.} 21. Rxe7 (21. f4 $2 {This prophylaxis against Ne5 does not work due to} a4 $1 22. Bc4 Nb6 {[%cal Gb6c4,Gb6d5]} 23. b3 Ra7 24. g4 Rc8 25. g5+ Kg7 26. Rxe7 Rxe7 27. Rxe7 Nxc4 28. bxc4 Rxc4 $17 {With an advantage in the rook endgame.}) 21... Ne5 22. Rb7 Rfb8 $1 (22... g5 $5 {has been played} 23. Rf1 Rfe8 {1/2-1/2 (34) Gooshchin,D (2553) -Ham, S (2583)/ICCF email 2016/Corr 2017}) 23. Rxb8 Rxb8 24. f4 Nd7 {The pawn is compensated for and the game is open for all results. Some possibilities are:} 25. Kc1 (25. Ba4 Nc5 26. Bc6 Kf5 27. g3 (27. Re7 Rf8 28. Ra7 Kxf4 29. Rxa5 Ke3 30. Rb5 f5 31. Rxb4 g5 $132 {Black has strong counterplay.}) 27... Kg4 28. Re7 Rf8 $132 {[%cal Gg4h3,Gg4f3]}) 25... Nc5 26. Bc4 (26. Kd2 Nxb3+ 27. axb3 Rb5 $11) 26... h5 $5 $11 {The rather closed character of the position offers balanced chances.} (26... Kf5 27. Kd2 (27. Re7 Rb7 $1 $15) 27... Rb7 28. g3 Kg4 {With a complex game. Black can exploit White's weakened kingside pawns.})) 18... Ne5 $1 (18... Bf6 $6 {This is the strategically correct solution, using ideas already seen in the database on the Marozcy setup. However, in this case, it is not enough to equalise.} 19. Bxf6 exf6 20. Re7 {White takes possession of the seventh rank and gets an advantage.} Nc5 (20... Rfe8 $2 21. Rde3 Rxe7 (21... Kf8 $2 22. Rxe8+ Rxe8 23. Rxe8+ Kxe8 24. Ba4 Ke7 25. Bxd7 Kxd7 {The pawn endgame is lost for the second player.} 26. a3 bxa3 27. b4 $18) 22. Rxe7 Nc5 23. Bc4 $18) 21. Rde3 $16 {White will gradually prepare c2-c3, opening the position and creating a passed pawn on the queenside.}) (18... Bxd4 $6 19. Rxd4 a5 20. Rxe7 Nc5 21. Kc1 Rae8 22. Rxe8 Rxe8 23. Kd2 $16 {White is more active than his opponent.}) 19. Rdd1 g5 $1 {A difficult decision, as it weakens the pawn structure, but a correct one. Black consolidates his knight in the centre while looking for simplifications.} 20. c3 bxc3 21. Bxc3 Rfc8 22. Re4 f5 23. Rb4 Rab8 24. Rd2 Rxb4 $1 (24... Nc4 $4 25. Rxc4 Rxc4 26. Bxg7 {1-0 Ivanchuk,V (2710)-Djukic,N (2567)/ Batumi GEO 2018}) ({An interesting alternative is} 24... Ng6 $1 25. Rxb8 Rxb8 26. Bxg7 Kxg7 $15) 25. Bxb4 Rb8 26. Bc3 Ng6 $1 $15 {Black has an excellent position. His plan is to exchange dark-squared bishops and play on that colour.} *

