1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 g6 5. Nc3 Bg7 6. Be3 Nf6 7. Bc4 Qa5 $5 {This line seeks to avoid move-orders where White plays f3.} 8. O-O (8. Nb3 $2 Qb4 9. Bd3 Nxe4 $19) (8. f3 $6 {This does not work after 7...Qa5.} Qb4 9. Ndb5 (9. Bb3 Nxe4 10. Nxc6 Bxc3+ 11. bxc3 Qxc3+ 12. Ke2 dxc6 $15) 9... Qxc4 10. Nc7+ Kd8 11. Nxa8 b6 12. a4 (12. Nxb6 axb6 13. Bxb6+ Ke8 14. Be3 Ba6 15. Kf2 d6 16. Qd2 Kd7 17. Rab1 Rc8 $17 {And the black pieces dominate the position. 0-1 Milenkovic,M (2373)-Rajkovic,D (2369)/Vrnjacka Banja 2014}) 12... Bb7 13. Nxb6 $1 (13. a5 $2 {is a mistake.} bxa5 14. e5 Ne8 15. Ra4 Qe6 16. f4 Bxa8 17. Ne4 $19 {0-1 Tatekhin,V (2154)-Danin,A (2543)/Belgorod 2011}) 13... axb6 14. Bxb6+ Kc8 {The position is complex although we prefer Black.}) (8. Qd2 $2 {This is a well-known mistake in the Accelerated Dragon.} Nxe4 $1 9. Nxe4 Qxd2+ 10. Kxd2 Nxd4 $19) 8... O-O 9. Nb3 ({White can play} 9. Bb3 d6 10. h3 {, transposing to the normal line.}) 9... Qc7 {The drawback of this move is the exposed situation of the queen against a possible Nd5.} 10. Bg5 (10. Be2 d6 11. Nd5 {More accurate is} Qb8 $1 (11... Qd8 12. Nxf6+ ({White should now play} 12. f3 $1 e6 13. Nxf6+ Bxf6 14. c3 a6 15. f4 $16 {, with a better position.}) 12... Bxf6 13. c3 Rb8 14. f4 a6 15. a4 b6 16. Bf3 Qc7 17. Qe2 Na5 $1 $132 {And Black gets counterplay. 0-1 Bok,B (2596)-Kuzubov,Y (2643)/ Moscow RUS 2017 (48)}) 12. Nxf6+ (12. f3 b5 $1 13. Qd2 Bd7 14. a4 ({An error is} 14. Bg5 $2 Nxd5 15. exd5 Ne5 16. Bxe7 {Losing the way.} Re8 17. Bh4 Nc4 $17) 14... bxa4 15. Rxa4 e6 16. Nxf6+ Bxf6 17. Rd1 Rc8 $1 (17... Be7 18. Nc5 dxc5 19. Qxd7 Rc8 20. Ra6 Rc7 21. Qd2 $14 {The bishop pair and the weakness of the light squares offer a stable slight advantage to the first player.}) 18. Qxd6 Qxd6 19. Rxd6 Be8 {Black will recover the pawn with balanced play.} 20. Bb5 (20. Bc1 $2 Be7 21. Rd1 Nb4 $17) 20... Bxb2 21. c4 $11) 12... Bxf6 13. Nd4 Nxd4 14. Bxd4 Bxd4 15. Qxd4 $11 {1/ 2-1/2 Golubev,M (2476)-Bogdanovich,S (2528)/Odessa 2018}) (10. Re1 {Preparing the Nd5 manoeuvre. Black must play carefully if he does not want to fall into a bad position.} d6 11. h3 a6 12. Bg5 (12. Nd5 $2 Nxd5 13. exd5 Nb4 $1 $17 {[%cal Gc7c4,Gb4c2,Gb4d5,Gg7b2]}) 12... b5 13. Bxf6 (13. Bf1 {This solid bishop retreat does not put the second player in trouble.} Be6 $1 14. Nd5 Bxd5 15. exd5 Ne5 16. a4 b4 17. a5 Rfc8 $13 {The game is unclear, with fighting chances for both sides.}) 13... exf6 $1 {An excellent example of capturing with the e-pawn, which is a typical motif of many variations of the Accelerated Sicilian Dragon and the regular Sicilian Dragon. Black's idea consists of breaking with f5, attacking White's centre and giving life to the bishop pair.} 14. Nd5 (14. Bd3 $6 Ne7 15. a4 b4 16. Na2 Rb8 17. Qd2 a5 18. Nd4 f5 $1 $17 {0-1 Mouhamad,J (2329)-Maze,S (2615)/Le Port Marly FRA 2016 (48)}) 14... Qd8 15. Bf1 f5 $1 {The opportunity should not be wasted.} 16. exf5 Bxf5 17. c3 {With a complex game. The bishop pair compensates for the weakness on d6.}) (10. f4 d6 11. Be2 Bd7 12. Qe1 {Our recommendation is the following typical pawn sacrifice for the initiative.} b5 $1 $146 {This move has not yet been used in tournament practice.} (12... a6 $6 {has been played.} 13. Rd1 b5 14. Nd5 Nxd5 15. exd5 Nd8 16. Nd4 $16 {1-0 Wei Yi (2721)-Vachier Lagrave,M  (2723)/Leon ESP 2015 (41)}) 13. Nxb5 {This other capture also offers good counterplay to the second player.} (13. Bxb5 Nb4 14. Bd3 (14. Bxd7 Nxc2 $19) 14... Ng4 $1 {An important intermediate move, preventing the white knight from being activated via d4.} (14... a5 15. h3 a4 16. Nd4 {The position is complicated but White is better organized.}) 15. Bd2 a5 16. h3 a4 17. Nc1 a3 $132 {With excellent counterplay for Black.}) 13... Qb7 14. Nc3 a5 $1 15. a4 Nb4 16. Qd2 Nxe4 17. Nxe4 Qxe4 18. Bf3 Qxc2 $19 {With a decisive advantage. We believe that the excellent resource 12...b5 will soon gain in popularity.}) 10... e6 11. Be2 $1 {Regrouping this piece is a very good idea. The bishop on c4 was tactically exposed.} (11. f4 $2 d5 $1 {A key move in the line with 10... e6. This is even more effective with the white bishop located on c4.} (11... d6 $5 {is also interesting.} 12. Bd3 a6 13. Qe2 b5 14. a3 Bb7 15. Rae1 Rae8 16. Kh1 Nd7 {We now have a structure more similar to a Sicilian Scheveningen.} 17. Qf3 b4 18. Nd1 bxa3 19. bxa3 Na5 20. Qh3 Nxb3 21. cxb3 Nc5 22. Bb1 f6 23. Bh4 f5 $1 $17 {0-1 Godoy Bugueno,D-Panno,O (2570)/Santiago de Chile 1971}) 12. exd5 Nb4 $1 {[%cal Gb4d5,Gb4c2,Gc7c4] The standard continuation after White takes.} 13. Be2 (13. Qe2 exd5 $1 {[%cal Gf8e8]} 14. Bxf6 (14. Bd3 Re8 $19 {[%cal Gc7b6,Gc8g4,Gf6g4,Ge8e3]}) 14... Bxf6 15. Nxd5 Nxd5 16. Bxd5 Bxb2 $15 {With a black advantage.}) 13... Nfxd5 14. Nxd5 Nxd5 $19 {And all the white pieces were badly located.}) (11. Qd2 $6 d5 12. exd5 Nb4 13. Be2 (13. Qe2 $2 exd5 14. Bd3 Ng4 15. g3 Bd7 16. Bf4 Qb6 $17 {Black has excellent piece activity.}) 13... Nfxd5 14. Nxd5 Nxd5 15. c4 Ne7 16. Rfd1 Nf5 $13 {The game is unclear. If now White tries the direct} 17. c5 e5 $1 18. Bc4 Nd4 $13 {, Black has enough counterplay.}) 11... a6 12. f4 (12. Qd2 b5 $1 ({Too shy is} 12... d6 $2 13. Rad1 Rd8 14. Qf4 $18) (12... d5 $6 13. exd5 Nxd5 14. Nxd5 exd5 15. c3 Be6 {This is a good isolated pawn position for White. The difference is that the white f-pawn is on its starting square, not weakening his castling position, as is the case after 11.f4?.}) 13. a3 Bb7 (13... d6 {is another possibility, but we like the developing move more.}) 14. Rad1 (14. Bf4 Ne5 $1 15. Qe3 d6 16. Rad1 Rfd8 17. Nd2 Rac8 $15 {And Black comes out of the opening with a very healthy position. 1/2-1/2 Salgado Lopez,I (2340)-Minzer,C (2428)/Madrid 2005}) 14... Rfc8 15. Nc5 (15. Bxf6 $2 {An important concession for just one pawn.} Bxf6 16. Qxd7 Qb6 (16... Bxc3 17. bxc3 Ne5 $13) 17. Qd2 $15 {Engines prefer the black position. We also think that the second player has very good compensation for the material.}) 15... Ne5 16. b4 $5 (16. Nxb7 Qxb7 {[%cal Gb7e4,Gf6e4,Ge5c4,Gc8c2] Black has enough counterplay.}) 16... Ne8 $1 {[%cal Gd7d6,Gc7c3,Gg7c3]} 17. f4 $8 d6 $1 18. Nxb7 Qb6+ $1 {This intermediate move is a key motif here.} (18... Nc4 $2 19. Bxc4 Qxc4 20. Nb1 $18) 19. Kh1 (19. Nc5 $2 {does not work:} dxc5 20. fxe5 cxb4+ 21. Be3 bxc3 $19) 19... Nc4 20. Bxc4 Rxc4 {, and Black recovers the missing piece with a good position.} 21. Nxd6 Qxd6 22. Qxd6 Nxd6 23. Rxd6 Rxc3 24. Rfd1 h6 25. Be7 Rxc2 $13 {There is still a game to play, but the chances are balanced.}) 12... d6 ({Serious consideration deserves} 12... d5 $5 13. e5 $1 (13. exd5 $6 Nxd5 $1 14. Nxd5 exd5 15. c3 {[%csl Rf4,Rg5]} Re8 $1 $15 {Another isolated pawn position, but in this case, with the white pawn on f4 and a poorly placed bishop on g5, Black is better.}) (13. Bxf6 $2 {An ugly mistake.} Bxf6 14. exd5 Rd8 $17) 13... Nd7 14. Bd3 (14. Kh1 f6 $132) 14... f6 $1 {Starting immediate counterplay.} 15. exf6 Nxf6 $1 16. Qd2 Ne8 17. Rae1 Nd6 $17 {Dominating the central squares. The white pieces are clumsy and it's difficult to find a plan for them.}) 13. Bf3 (13. Qd2 b5 14. Bf3 (14. Rad1 $2 b4 $17 {[%cal Gf6e4]}) 14... a5 $1 (14... b4 $6 {An imprecision that the first player is able to exploit.} 15. Na4 a5 16. Rfd1 Ba6 17. Qxd6 Qa7+ 18. Qc5 $16) 15. a4 (15. Nxb5 Qb6+ $19) 15... bxa4 16. Nxa4 Rb8 17. Rad1 Rd8 $15 {Black has a good game on the queenside.}) 13... b5 14. a3 (14. e5 $2 dxe5 15. fxe5 Nd7 16. Ne4 Ncxe5 $19) (14. Qd2 $5 Bb7 15. Rad1 Ne8 {[%cal Ge8d6,Gg7d4]} 16. a3 a5 $1 $132) 14... Nd7 $1 {Quickly heading for the c4-square.} 15. Qe1 Nb6 {[%cal Gb6c4]} 16. Nd1 Nc4 17. c3 Bb7 18. Rc1 Rae8 19. Rc2 f6 $1 20. Bh4 Bh6 21. Be2 f5 $1 $17 {Black's opening is a major success.} *

