{[%evp 0,40,47,18,47,47,44,39,27,9,69,46,49,49,87,22,74,58,43,39,38,29,28,21,25,34,43,46,53,56,56,56,60,-8,-10,30,14,30,15,-26,-2,-3,-12]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 g6 5. Nc3 Bg7 6. Be3 Nf6 7. Bc4 Qa5 8. O-O O-O 9. Bb3 {Entering the mainline.} d6 10. h3 Bd7 11. Re1 (11. f4 $6 {This aggressive setup does not put the second player in trouble.} Nxd4 {Simplifications, necessary to create space for the black pieces.} 12. Bxd4 Bc6 13. Qd3 Rad8 {[%cal Gd8d3] A strange location for the rook on a8. It is fully justified though, preventing e4-e5 and supporting a central counter, as can be seen below.} 14. Nd5 {White's main idea in this line, but Black has a strong tactical response.} (14. f5 Nd7 $1 {Exploiting the weakness of the dark squares.} 15. Kh1 (15. Bxg7 Kxg7 16. Qd4+ Qe5 ({The simple} 16... Nf6 $1 $11 {is also possible.}) 17. Qxa7 b6 18. Qa6 Qc5+ 19. Kh1 b5 $15) 15... Bxd4 16. Qxd4 Qc5 17. Qd2 {[%cal Gf1f4,Gf4h4]} Kg7 $11 {[%cal Gh7h6,Gd7e5,Gd7f6] Before White can execute the Rf4-h4 manoeuvre, Black will play h6, with ideas like Rh8 and g5.}) ({In case of} 14. Rad1 {, the most precise is} Nd7 15. Bxg7 Kxg7 16. Kh1 {At this point, Black can opt for the following semi-forced sequence -} Nc5 17. Qd4+ e5 18. fxe5 Nxb3 19. axb3 dxe5 20. Qf2 f5 21. b4 Qxb4 22. Rxd8 Rxd8 23. exf5 g5 24. f6+ Kf7 25. Qe3 Qh4 26. Kh2 g4 27. Qxe5 g3+ 28. Qxg3 Qxg3+ 29. Kxg3 Rg8+ 30. Kf4 Rxg2 31. Ke5 Rxc2 32. Rg1 Bg2 33. Rd1 Bc6 34. Rg1 {1/2-1/2 (34) Mamedov,R (2642)-Guseinov,G (2610) Baku 2015}) 14... e5 $1 {Putting the rook on d8 to good use. The main move now is} 15. fxe5 {, leading to complex variations where Black is always fine.} (15. Bc3 $2 Qc5+ 16. Kh2 Nxd5 17. exd5 (17. Bxd5 Bb5 $19) 17... Bb5 $19 {Gaining material.}) (15. Nxf6+ $6 Bxf6 16. Bc3 Qc5+ 17. Kh1 Bb5 18. Qf3 Bxf1 19. Rxf1 $15 {Although there is some compensation, the black position is preferable.}) 15... Nxd5 $1 16. exd5 dxe5 $1 {A precise move that requires correct calculation.} (16... Bxd5 $2 17. exd6 Bxb3 18. Bxg7 $18) 17. Rxf7 (17. dxc6 Rxd4 18. Bxf7+ (18. Qe3 bxc6 $17) 18... Rxf7 19. Qb3 Qd5 $19 {0-1 Gilden, L-Christiansen,L/Lone Pine 1972}) 17... Rxf7 $1 (17... Kxf7 $6 {This capture is somewhat worse since the king will be exposed.} 18. dxc6+ Ke7 19. Qc3 Qxc3 20. Bxc3 bxc6 21. Bb4+ $13) 18. dxc6 Rxd4 19. Bxf7+ Kh8 $1 (19... Kxf7 $2 {Throwing the position overboard.} 20. Qb3+ Qd5 (20... Ke7 21. cxb7 $18) 21. c7 $18) 20. cxb7 (20. Qb3 bxc6 $13 {With a complex game, but we prefer the black position.}) 20... Rxd3 21. b8=Q+ Rd8 22. b4 (22. Qb3 e4 $1 $17 {White has worse pieces and a weaker king.}) 22... Rxb8 23. bxa5 e4 24. Re1 e3 $13 {With an unclear endgame.}) (11. Qd2 $2 {Allowing the well-known combination.} Nxd4 12. Bxd4 Nxe4 $19) (11. Nf3 Be6 $5 12. Bxe6 $6 {This attempt at a direct refutation does not bear great fruit.} (12. Qe2 {Transposing to the mainline.}) 12... fxe6 13. Ng5 Nd8 $1 {Black defends everything and is ready to continue with his typical Rc8, Nd7 development, with balanced play.}) 11... Rac8 12. Nf3 {A typical idea in these positions. White's idea is to remove the knight from a vulnerable position to follow up with Nd5 later.} ({Black also needs to be prepared for the direct} 12. Nd5 Rfe8 $1 {Avoiding the exchange on d5 to activate his pieces first.} 13. Bd2 Qa6 14. Bc3 (14. Nxc6 {This simplification does not generate any inconveniences.} bxc6 15. Nb4 Qb5 16. Nd3 c5 17. c4 {1/ 2-1/2 Perez Ponsa,F (2594)-Flores,D (2574)/ Buenos Aires 2017/}) 14... Nxd5 {Black is ready now.} 15. exd5 Ne5 $1 ({Too passive is} 15... Nxd4 $2 16. Bxd4 Bxd4 17. Qxd4 $16 {, and we find ourselves in the position aspired by White.}) 16. Ne2 {Preventing a possible Rxc3.} (16. a4 Rxc3 $5 {A good moment for this exchange sacrifice.} 17. bxc3 Qa5 18. Qd2 Rc8 {Planning Bf6 and Nc4. Black has a good game. It is not sensible for White to accelerate events with} 19. f4 $2 Nc4 $1 20. Bxc4 Rxc4 21. Nb3 (21. Rxe7 Bxd4+ $19) 21... Qb6+ 22. Qe3 Kf8 $15 {, and Black is somewhat better.}) 16... Bb5 $1 17. Kh1 {Preparing a quick f4.} (17. Nd4 Bc4 $1 18. Qd2 $6 (18. Nf3 Nxf3+ 19. Qxf3 Bxc3 20. bxc3 Rc5 21. Rad1 b5 $132 {[%cal Ga6b7]}) 18... Rc5 $1 $17 {[%csl Rd5] Winning a pawn.}) 17... Bxe2 18. Rxe2 Rxc3 $5 {Returning to the typical idea of the exchange sacrifice. Perhaps it is unnecessary in this position. Black hopes that the poor white pawn structure and the strong dark squared bishop will provide enough compensation.} ({Another possibility of similar value is} 18... Bf6 $5) 19. bxc3 Qa5 20. Qe1 Bf6 $1 {We believe that there is enough compensation and the idea is correct.} 21. Rd1 (21. f4 Nd7 $44) 21... Rc8 22. f4 Nd7 23. Rxe7 $2 Bxe7 24. Qxe7 Nc5 25. f5 Qd8 $1 {0-1 Lorenzo de la Riva,L (2407)-Martinez Duany,L (2510)/Barcelona 2010}) ({Worth taking into account is} 12. Qd2 $5 Rfe8 13. Rad1 Nxd4 14. Bxd4 Bc6 {There are different alternatives for the first player.} ({White gets an easy advantage after} 14... Be6 $2 15. e5 $1 $16) 15. Bxf6 (15. Nd5 Qxd2 16. Rxd2 Nd7 $13 {With a balanced endgame.}) (15. f4 Nd7 $1 {Always the same maneuver!} 16. Bxg7 Kxg7 17. Qd4+ Kg8 $11) 15... Bxf6 16. Nd5 Qxd2 17. Nxf6+ exf6 18. Rxd2 d5 $1 {With a level game.} 19. Bxd5 Bxd5 20. Rxd5 Rxc2 $11 {1/2-1/2 Kotronias,V (2524)-Mamedov,R (2688)/Moscow RUS 2017 (29)}) 12... Rfe8 (12... Be6 $5 {is an interesting option.}) 13. Qe2 $1 (13. Nd5 $2 Nxe4 $17) (13. Ng5 {Black is well placed to face this direct attempt.} Ne5 $1 14. f4 (14. Qe2 h6 (14... b5 $2 15. f4 Nc4 16. a4 $18 {[%csl Rb5][%cal Ga1a5,Gb3c4,Ga4b5]}) 15. Nf3 Nxf3+ 16. Qxf3 Qh5 $11) 14... Nc4 15. Qe2 Qc7 $1 {After this precise move, Black is fine.} (15... b5 $2 16. a4 $18) 16. Bf2 (16. a4 e6 $15) 16... e6 $1 17. e5 dxe5 18. fxe5 Nd5 $11) (13. Qd2 Be6 $1 14. Rad1 (14. Bxe6 $6 fxe6 15. Ng5 Nd8 $1 $13 {Reaching a position very similar to the variation 11. Nf3. In this atypical position, Black defends his weakness without problems. White missed his traditional goal in the opening and it can be difficult for him to find a clear game plan.}) 14... Nd7 15. Nd4 (15. Bxe6 fxe6 16. Ng5 Nd8 $1 $15) 15... Nxd4 16. Bxd4 Bxd4 17. Qxd4 Qc5 $1 {After the exchange of queens, Black has no problems.} 18. Qd2 (18. Ba4 Qxd4 19. Rxd4 Red8 20. Bxd7 Rxd7 21. e5 dxe5 22. Rxd7 Bxd7 23. Rxe5 Kf8 {1/2-1/2 (26) Robson,R (2670) -Anton Guijarro,D  (2674)/chess24.com INT 2020}) 18... b5 $1 {Starting powerful counterplay.} 19. Re3 a5 20. a3 Bxb3 $6 ({It was better to play} 20... b4 $1 21. axb4 Qxb4 $132) 21. cxb3 Nf6 22. e5 dxe5 23. Qe2 e4 24. Nxe4 Nxe4 25. Rxe4 Qc2 $11 {0-1 Robson, R (2670)-Anton Guijarro,D (2674)/chess24.com INT 2020}) 13... Be6 $5 {This move is a novelty, but it has been played before in similar positions. It is our recommendation to play with Black here. After other moves, White tends to be in a more comfortable position.} ({An example is} 13... a6 $6 14. Rad1 $1 Ne5 15. Nxe5 Qxe5 16. Bd4 Qg5 17. Qf3 Bc6 18. Nd5 $1 $14 {1/2-1/2 Gao,R (2533) -Bu,X (2681)/China 2015}) 14. Bxe6 ({If White prefers not to capture the bishop, the way forward is} 14. Rad1 Bxb3 15. axb3 a6 16. Nd5 Nxd5 17. exd5 {Now Black must make two precise moves.} Nb4 $1 18. c4 Qa2 $1 {Without this last move, the variation chosen by Black is not viable.} 19. Nd4 Bxd4 20. Rxd4 Qxb3 $13) 14... fxe6 15. Qc4 (15. Ng5 Nd8 $1 $11) 15... d5 $1 {This well-timed central counterattack neutralises all the aggressive white intentions.} 16. exd5 (16. Qb3 $5 Qb4 17. Bxa7 (17. Rad1 $5 Qxb3 18. axb3 Nxe4 19. Nxe4 dxe4 20. Ng5 Bxb2 $13 {[%cal Gb7b5,Ga7a5]}) 17... Nxe4 $1 18. Nxe4 Qxb3 19. axb3 dxe4 20. Rxe4 Ra8 21. Rea4 Bxb2 $13 {The position is very complex. Black achieved his goal of complicating the game and not falling into a passive position.}) 16... Ne5 $1 17. Qe2 Nxf3+ 18. Qxf3 Nxd5 $1 19. Nxd5 $8 exd5 20. c3 e5 $1 $13 {With possibilities for both sides.} *

